<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GRAND-PRIX-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIS BEAT HEAT, SWEEP GRAND PRIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ All conquering all weekend, the Audi R8s
driven by Frank Biela and Rinaldo Capello completed a one-two
Prototype sweep for the German carmaker in the inaugural Grand Prix
of Texas at Texas Motor Speedway last night.
</P>
<P>
   But it could have been the other way around in Round 7 of the
American Le Mans Series. Running second to Capello with 42 minutes
left in the 2 hour, 45-minute event, Biela pitted for fuel in the
No. 78 car during the race's second full-course caution. Race
leader Capello also was supposed to pit during the yellow, but a
faulty radio prevented the Italian from getting the call from his
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Capello kept the lead for 31 more minutes, when he was forced to
pit because of a deflating tire and for fuel. That allowed Biela,
who shared the No. 78 Audi with Italian Emanuele Pirro, to inherit
a lead he would carry to the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car was perfect until the end, but the main job was done
by the pit crew,'' Biela, of Germany, said during a somewhat muted
postrace celebration. ``I came in on the full-course yellow, and
that's where I gained the gap we lost in the first two stints.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning silver car led only the final 11 minutes (or nine
laps) around the 2.324-mile, eight-turn combined oval/infield road
course. That period proved particularly agonizing for Capello and
pole sitter Allan McNish of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just bad luck,'' Capello said. ``I had the radio
\Rworking\S not five minutes before the yellow flag. After
Nurburgring \Ran accident and 30th-place finish July 9\R, I said
all of our bad luck was over. This year Allan and I have rewritten
the book on bad luck. This was the only track where we don't have a
pit board.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have told Capello to bring it on in. As it was, he
continued to drive into the night ... and into the clutches of his
Joest Racing teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they had to stop because they hadn't pitted during the
yellow flag,'' Pirro said. ``Frank was trying to keep the gap big
enough to make sure we could keep the lead. Frank had the lead with
a lot of pressure, and made it.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the fourth for the Audi factory this season and
second for the No. 78 car in the ALMS. That does not include the
victory by Biela and Pirro in the prestigious 24 Hours of Le Mans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ron Fellows and Andy Pilgrim scored the first Grand
Touring Sport victory for the Chevrolet Corvette C5-R, a resounding
three-lap decision over the No. 91 Dodge Viper GTS-R driven by
Olivier Beretta and Karl Wendlinger. The 'Vette's victory marked
the first time since the Team Oreca Vipers joined the series in
June 1999 that they failed to finish first, a streak covering 12
consecutive races.
</P>
<P>
   In the Grand Touring class, the No. 23 Alex Job Racing Porsche
911 GT3 R co-driven by Randy Pobst and Bruno Lambert scored its
second consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows, a two-time winner of the Grand Prix of Dallas Trans-Am
race, drove the opening and closing stints in the closed-cockpit
No. 3 GM Goodwrench Chevrolet. Ambient temperatures again were over
100 degrees when the race started at 7:17 p.m., and up to 160
degrees in the closed-cockpit Corvette. Fellows was drained when he
turned the car over to Pilgrim during a pit stop approximately 45
minutes into the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the infield portion of the course, I had to hold my breath
because the hot air was so powerful,'' said Fellows, a native of
Canada. ``When I came in I had about a dozen ice-down towels
\Rwrapped around him\S.'' Fellows said he also was escorted back to
his garage, where he received what he called an outdoor shower.
Fellows sat in a lawn chair while a crewman sprayed water on him
from a garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt fine after about 30 minutes,'' said Fellows, the lead
development driver for the factory Corvette program.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway officials estimated all-day attendance at the track at
24,500, with approximately 9,000 on the grounds for the ALMS
feature.
</P>
<P>
   With the Audis of McNish and Pirro dominating the field, only
six of 26 cars remained on the lead-lap 38 minutes into the race.
At the one-hour mark, only the two Audis, the Panoz LMP-1 Roadster
driven by David Brabham and the BMW V12 LMR started by J.J. Lehto
had completed 48 laps. Prototypes occupied the top seven positions,
with the Corvette C5-R atop the GTS standings with Fellows at the
wheel. He was being chased by the Vipers driven by Wendlinger and
David Donohue in ninth and 10th, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Pole sitter Dirk Muller had his Porsche 911 GT3 R in the GT
class lead, 11th overall.
</P>
<P>
   McNish ended his double stint and surrendered his seat, but not
the lead, when he pitted at 8:51 p.m. during a full-course caution
brought out when Randy Wars' GT Porsche 911 developed a small fire
in the rear. Pirro also brought the No. 78 Audi R8 in for tires,
fuel and a switch to his teammate, Biela.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car's good to drive. It's comfortable,'' said McNish, who
after helping Capello get settled into the cockpit hopped over the
pit wall for another hot interview. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
