r s BC-FBC-SMU-KANSAS-TEX     09-03 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SMU-KANSAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMU OPENS STADIUM IN RED-HOT STYLE BY BEATING KANSAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TRACEY MYERS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ SMU football coach Mike Cavan was at peace Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He would be the first to admit the calm demeanor on game day was
typical. But there was something different this time, something
about this 2000 team that felt right.
</P>
<P>
   His positive attitude was reinforced later that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Josh McCown threw for 164 yards and two touchdowns and
ran for another, as the Mustangs scored 24 points in the first
quarter on the way to a 31-17 victory against Kansas in the season
opener at the new Gerald J. Ford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs (1-0) triumphed in a season opener for the first
time since 1996, when they defeated Tulsa, 17-10. The game was also
the hottest in SMU history, as the game-time temperature reached
107 degrees. But the anticipation and desire for a victory in the
new stadium might have been more intense than any Texas sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not calling this the greatest win, but it's probably the
most important win that's been here, just because of everything
that's gone on,'' Cavan said. ``For us to come out here tonight and
play like we did, it was really good. It was a big-time win for our
program.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown, who completed 14 of 25 passes, was fully aware of the
Mustangs' recent past. Losing skids had become regular, and
breaking in the 2000 season with a victory was a weight off the
team's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go 0-4, 0-5 the past two seasons, going 1-0 makes all
the difference in the world,'' McCown said. ``It was a great lift
for the crowd to be behind us, and the start we had gave us great
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore wide receiver Chris Cunningham, who caught five passes
for 58 yards, also felt the energy of the 32,267 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came out of the tunnel and to see the crowd going
crazy,'' Cunningham said, ``well, that is what I imagined when I
decided to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   They also felt the impact of a new offense. The new one-back
setup installed by offensive coordinator Larry Kueck, who also had
the same job with the Mustangs in 1990, was evident immediately.
Set up to feature the passing game, the scheme allowed McCown to
pick and choose his receiving targets. Billy Ford and John Hampton,
a Burleson High School graduate, each had a touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Kansas free safety Carl Nesmith also might have
helped. Nesmith, a preseason All-America selection who had three
interceptions last season, didn't play because of a violation of
the team's code of conduct. But the Jayhawks were stymied more by
their own mistakes than by their missing teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Several wide receivers dropped quarterback Dylen Smith's passes,
including a possible touchdown to David Hurst in the second
quarter. A bad snap on a punt gave the Mustangs the ball on the
Jayhawks' 1-yard line, setting up an easy score. Kevin Aldridge
partially blocked another punt for the Mustangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't move the ball on offense in the first quarter,''
Kansas coach Terry Allen said. ``Our demise was the mistakes we
made on our punt team, but that was a result of us not moving the
football. We can't punt the ball four times in the first quarter
and win ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith left in the third quarter with cramps but returned in the
fourth after receiving fluids. He completed 15 of 37 passes for 207
yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   SMU scored on its first drive, after dropped passes by Hurst and
Termaine Fulton doomed the Jayhawks. McCown completed all four of
his pass attempts, including an 11-yard strike to Ford for a
touchdown, and the Mustangs scored on their next three possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The victory has helped Cavan breathe a little easier, for now.
But with a Western Athletic Conference matchup against UT-El Paso
approaching Saturday, the opener will be put aside quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of things to correct, we've got a long way to
go to be a real good football team,'' Cavan said. ``But I think
these guys understand it. No matter what this win is, it's bigger
next week.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly SMU tight end Steve O'Neill suffered
a sprained left ankle late in the game but walked off on his own
power.
</P>
<P>
   Two Mustangs, defensive end Kevin Aldridge and linebacker Vic
Viloria suffered dehydration.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
