<HEADER>
A9804 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-     09-03 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN IT IN 10TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Even in this pinball era when 25 homers and 100
RBI are more staples of good seasons rather than benchmarks,
pitchers prove they still own the game.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies lefty Bruce Chen and Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown
had one of those time-warp nights in which pitching dominated with
no solution.
</P>
<P>
   Neither starter budged. The Los Angeles Dodgers finally got to
Philadelphia's bullpen in the 10th inning and won 1-0 Saturday in
front of 37,244 at Dodger Stadium. Jeff Branson doubled to right
off reliever Vicente Padilla and Branson eventually scored on Tom
Goodwin's two-out single to center as the Dodgers won for the 10th
time in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had few chances against Chen - acquired in the Andy
Ashby deal with Atlanta in July - but it didn't start out that way.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, they were poised to do something, but
Goodwin's misread on Mark Grudzielanek's pop-up to right field cost
them. Goodwin led off with a single, but he wasn't sure if Phillies
second baseman Marlon Anderson would catch Grudzielanek's bloop.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson got a glove on it, and Goodwin turned to return to
first. Anderson dropped it, but center fielder Doug Glanville
quickly picked it up and threw to second to force Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Scott Rolen booted Gary Sheffield's grounder to
put runners on first and second, but Eric Karros flew out to right
and Shawn Green popped out to second.
</P>
<P>
   The only other runner the Dodgers got off Chen in the next six
innings was Grudzielanek's two-out single to right in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley broke Chen's string of retiring 13 straight with a
leadoff single to right in the eighth, but failure to execute hurt
the Dodgers. Branson, starting at shortstop in the place of the ill
Alex Cora, popped out on his bunt attempt. Jim Leyritz popped out
in front of home plate for the second out. Goodwin singled to right
to push Paul LoDuca, running for Hundley, to third, but
Grudzielanek grounded into a fielder's choice to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Chen tied a career-high with eight strikeouts in 8 innings. He
walked one and allowed four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Brown held the Phillies scoreless through his seven innings,
yielding four hits and striking out nine. But it was a battle most
of the time. In the first six innings, the Phillies had a base
runner in all innings but the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Lieberthal, a Westlake High product, led off the
second with a double and went to third on Travis Lee's grounder to
first. Needing a fly ball to score a run, Rob Ducey instead struck
out. It was the first of seven consecutive strikeouts recorded by
Brown. He got out of the inning by whiffing Marlon Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies had another threat in the fourth when Rolen led off
with a single and Lieberthal was hit with a pitch. However, Lee and
Ducey struck out and Anderson tapped harmlessly back to the mound
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Such a pitching performance is nothing new for Brown, or
actually any of the Dodgers' big three. Brown, Chan Ho Park and
Darren Dreifort haven't been the problems, but the end of the
rotation has been inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brown did go through a three-start stretch in which he
wasn't the dominating, overpowering intimidator he usually is. In
fact, included in that span was a messy, 1-inning, nine-run outing
against the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But in his last three starts, Brown's been pitching the way he's
pitched since joining the Dodgers after the 1998 season. He took a
perfect game into the seventh inning in an Aug. 23 start against
Montreal and wound up yielding one run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Though Brown allowed three runs in seven innings in his last
start at Milwaukee, he was pitching just two days after being
confined to his hotel room with flu-like symptoms. And he was
staked to a 5-0 lead in the first inning and didn't mind trading a
hit here and there in exchange for outs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
