<HEADER>
A9805 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-ALABAMA-LADN     09-03 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-ALABAMA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA STUNS NO. 3 ALABAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Four plays into the new season and it looked
like the same old train wreck of 1999 for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays and the Bruins were already down a quarterback - Cory
Paus, who left with a separated shoulder. Four plays and they were
down on the scoreboard - Alabama's Freddie Milons returned a punt
71 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   All this and the UCLA defense hadn't even taken the field.
</P>
<P>
   While the 76,640 fans at the Rose Bowl might have been wondering
if UCLA would play a repeat of the 1999 disappointment, the Bruins,
behind tailback DeShaun Foster, began to establish a dominance the
same fans will only hope can be maintained.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins, who had lost nine of their previous 13 games, had
a host of questions when they walked onto the field, there was only
one to ask after they left it with a resounding 35-24 victory over
No. 3 Alabama:
</P>
<P>
   Where have these guys been?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're back, but I'm very excited for our
football team,'' said coach Bob Toledo, who added he considered the
victory the second-greatest since his arrival at UCLA in 1996, the
year of its greatest - when the Bruins beat USC in double overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing about this team is they worked extremely hard
and they believed and you've got to believe you can beat
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had few reasons, if any, to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did they lose Paus, who is expected to be out two to
four weeks, but they lost receiver Brian Poli-Dixon early in the
second half with a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Things worsened in the third quarter, when UCLA was unable to
take advantage of strong field position while clinging to a 21-17
lead. Backup quarterback Ryan McCann was intercepted by Alabama
free safety Reggie Myles, who raced 91 yards untouched to put the
Crimson Tide ahead 24-21 with 8:26 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came off the field I told him we needed him,'' Toledo
said of McCann. ``I didn't lose confidence in him. I just told him
that we needed him to go back out there and make a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   And McCann, who was 2 for 9 with the interception and was sacked
twice since late in the second quarter, responded. With a first
down at Alabama's 46, cornerback Hirchel Bolden bit on McCann's
pump fake, allowing Freddie Mitchell to streak by. Mitchell hauled
in McCann's throw for a touchdown and a 28-24 lead with 7:05 left
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the defense, Foster and the offensive line took care
of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, who had never carried the ball more than 24 times in his
two previous seasons, was handed the ball a school-record tying 42
times and carried it for three touchdowns and a career-high 187
yards. He also caught three passes for 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a high school game for a minute,'' Foster
said of his workload.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line, which suffered through inexperience and
injury last season, returned all five starters and gained an
average of 12 pounds per player. And they pounded on Alabama early,
putting together 19- and 13-play scoring drives in the first half.
By the fourth quarter the speedy Crimson Tide defense, with eight
returning starters from last year's ninth-ranked unit in the
nation, was worn out.
</P>
<P>
   On the 19-play drive the Bruins converted three fourth downs,
all Foster runs, including a 1-yard scoring dive that answered
Milons' punt return.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago we put too much on the quarterback because we
couldn't run the ball,'' said offensive coordinator Al Borges,
whose team enjoyed a nearly 15-minute advantage in time of
possession. ``We knew we had to get physical this season. The
quarterback's best friend is the running game. If you make (the
linemen and linebackers) play in the box, they're not able to
indiscriminately run up the field. The whole thing starts with the
aggressiveness of the offensive line and the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   If the offensive line was remarkably different than last season,
then what of the defense?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were ranked 99th and 107th in the nation in total
defense the past two seasons, but they led the country in being the
butt of handicapped jokes - in light of the scandal in which
players used handicapped parking placards on campus. It was their
turn to laugh Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They held Alabama, which returned nine starters on offense, to
265 yards in total offense. The UCLA defense also recovered three
fumbles, intercepted a pass and allowed only 10 points - the
Crimson Tide got their others on Myles' interception return and
Milons' punt return.
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Marques Anderson, a former cornerback, looked like
a natural at his new position, hitting hard, tackling soundly and
blanketing Milons when the alignment called for it. Jason Bell,
who, like Anderson didn't play last season, smothered receivers all
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And the front seven - which got only a token appearance from
tackle Ken Kocher (ankle sprain) - never allowed Alabama to
establish a running game or throw deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they got on us was trick plays,'' said
linebacker Ryan Nece, referring to a 56-yard reverse by Jason
McAddley and a throw- back screen to tight end Terry Jones for 27
yards, Alabama's only two plays longer than 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot to prove not only to ourselves, but the nation.
When you're doubted as much as we've been, you use it as
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   McAddley appeared destined for the end zone on the reverse,
which would have pulled Alabama out from beneath a 14-point deficit
to tie the score just before halftime. But Manning made a diving
shoestring tackle of McAddley at the 15. Tide quarterback Andrew
Zow was sacked twice - by linebacker Tony White and Anderson - in
the next two plays, forcing Alabama to settle for a field goal and
a 21-17 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes up for everything,'' said Bell, who sat out last
season with a heel injury. ``I'm back, I'm healthy and I'm ready to
go. And we're back, we're healthy and we're ready to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
