<SLUG> BC-BBN-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA'S MILONS CAUSES SPECIAL PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The most dangerous man on the field Saturday
was Alabama's 5-foot-7, all-purpose threat Freddie Milons.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA figured it couldn't do much to prevent him from getting the
ball on offense, since Alabama uses so many formations and methods
to get him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The kicking game, however, was an area they wanted to control.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it mission failed.
</P>
<P>
   Punter Nate Fikse's first punt went right to Milons, who juked
his way down the field for a 71-yard touchdown. He also returned
another 18 yards that he almost broke for much more. Finally,
Fikse, who averaged 45 yards on his five kicks, got the idea in the
second half and kicked the ball short and let it roll once and
putting another out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to kick it to (Milons) and Nate didn't want to
kick it to him,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``But sometimes it's
like my wedge shot, he slices it.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing 'em proud: The UCLA offensive line, which battled
inexperience, injury and lack of muscle last season, turned in the
type of dominating performance it regularly did in 1997 and 1998,
when the Bruins won 20 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Duly impressed were two members of that line, center Shawn
Stuart and guard Andy Meyers, who were on the UCLA sideline
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where they came from last year, I'm very proud of those
guys,'' Stuart said. ``They're much more athletic than we were and
tougher than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon hurt: Brian Poli-Dixon, whose only catch was a
31-yard touchdown pass from flanker Freddie Mitchell, strained a
hamstring on UCLA's first possession of the second half and didn't
return. However, the injury isn't serious and Poli-Dixon could have
returned if needed, trainer Geoff Schaadt said.
</P>
<P>
   Flingin' Freddie: Mitchell's touchdown pass was the third of his
career - every one coming in a big game. The other two came in the
1998 season opener against Texas and in the 1999 Rose Bowl against
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The play began with Ryan McCann pitching the ball to DeShaun
Foster, who swept left and tossed the ball back to Mitchell, who
threw a perfect ball that Poli-Dixon caught just inside the back
line of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, Mitchell is 4 of 5 for 126 yards, three
touchdowns and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddie Mitchell might be our best quarterback,'' Toledo
joked.
</P>
<P>
   What have you done lately?: UCLA defensive coordinator Bob Field
was thrilled with the way his defense played, particularly in light
of last year's struggles, when the Bruins allowed 444.6 yards per
game, 107th in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't getting carried away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling,'' Field said, ``but if we don't play
well next week, you'll get your pens fired up and write something
bad, and justifiably so.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA plays Fresno State next week.
</P>
<P>
   Orange eyes upon them: Corey Johnson, a former Long Beach State
athletic director, was at the game as a representative of the
Orange Bowl, which plays host to the national championship game
this season. He was not, however, seen in the UCLA locker room
after the game. !arrow!Add injuries:!off! Starting defensive tackle
Ken Kocher, who suffered a high ankle sprain nearly two weeks ago,
was on the field for several plays but did not have a tackle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
