<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUBHOUSE MEETING DOESN'T HELP ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Anaheim Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn called a
players-only meeting before Saturday's game against the Chicago
White Sox to emphasize the positive and reinforce the team's focus.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hours later, they were down, 10-0, on their way to a
13-6 loss before 29,785 at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have lost three in a row and four of five, their
record falling to 68-67, only one game over .500 for the first time
since June 20. They are five games behind Seattle in the American
League West, and although they are still only 4 games behind
Cleveland, they fell into the sixth spot in the wild-card race as
Detroit passed them.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Kent Mercker left after two innings with a
strained left rotator cuff. His spot in the rotation most likely
will be taken by Tim Belcher, who would start next Thursday in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, as all but a few players were left in the
clubhouse, Vaughn told reporters what he tried to convey to his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, what we've accomplished as a team cannot
be forgotten under any circumstances,'' he said. ``I don't want
anybody getting caught up in whatever situation we're in. You have
to give a lot of credit to this organization, to this club. A lot
of guys are setting records, breaking records. I don't want our
guys to forget that as we get down to the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels typically play in the spotlight like they're under a
heat lamp, wilting instead of thriving. They've had only one
winning September since 1991, and that came last year after the
season had long been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing greater than to be playing for the playoffs in
September,'' Vaughn said. ``It's the same game playing in April,
May and June. But focus is the main thing, especially when it comes
down to the last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few pennants are won in April and May. Pennants are won
in September.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. The Angels are 0-2 in September. Saturday's game was over
shortly after it began. Mercker gave up four runs in the second
inning and was done for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson had the big hit of the inning with a three-run
double. He added an RBI single and a three-run homer later in the
game for a career-high seven RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox went to work against the Angels bullpen for one
run in the fourth and five in the fifth for a 10-0 lead. But the
Angels responded in the sixth with five runs, three coming in on
Garret Anderson's 32nd home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't give ourselves a real chance,'' Angels manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``We had guys on base but we only had five hits.
Getting down, 4-0, we were confident, but down 10-0 ... we battled
as hard as we could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have battled all season but have struggled to
overcome an inconsistent and injury-plagued starting rotation. The
bullpen has been tested all season because of it and is showing
signs of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek is the perfect example. Saturday, he faced 11
batters, allowed five hits and walked one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need these guys (starters) to get deeper into games,'' said
Scioscia, who added he isn't worried about his team's state of
mind. ``These guys have a passion for the game. They come out every
day and want to get after it. We didn't win today, but we'll be
ready to go tomorrow, and the next day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
