<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0904-COX     09-03 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    City slow to learn value of a good tree
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a 90-degree day in a downtown parking lot last
week, the surface temperature of a parked automobile measured 150
degrees. On hot summer days, parked cars emit hydrocarbons that add
to ozone pollution, just like cars stuck in traffic jams do.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Bansley, executive director of TreesAtlanta, used a heat
gun _ an infrared thermometer that measures surface temperatures _
to make her point: Enforcing Atlanta's parking lot tree ordinance,
which requires one canopy tree (a minimum of 10 feet high with a
40-foot growth potential) for every eight parking spaces, is about
more than aesthetics. It's about curbing air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   As Bansley measured the surfaces in an unshaded lot next to a
downtown restaurant, she recorded pavement temperatures ranging
from 131 to 145 degrees in the sun. But under the one nearby shade
tree, the paving's temperature was 94 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Bansley was the first person I called when I heard the good news
that the city is starting to enforce the parking lot provision of
the tree ordinance after eight years of dormancy. Enacted in 1992,
it was challenged in court by parking lot owners for three years
before being upheld by the state Supreme Court in 1995. But with
one lone city arborist devoid of staff and no attention from the
mayor's office (except briefly before the Olympics), city parking
lots simply added to what NASA scientists describe as metro
Atlanta's ``17-square-mile and growing urban heat island.''
</P>
<P>
   In a display of how effective grass-roots efforts can be, droves
of Atlantans packed recent city budget hearings demanding funding
for the arborist's office so the city tree ordinance could be
enforced. As a result, the city hired four new arborists. Arborist
Frank Mobley has committed to enforcing the parking lot tree
requirements, although it's not clear whether they will apply only
to new lots and those being expanded or to all of them. (The
ordinance states that it applies to ``existing'' lots.)
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's ordinance, and others like it in the suburbs, ought to
be amended to require the planting of trees inside lots, too. It's
good to reduce parking lot temperatures with perimeter trees, but
if a car is parked under a tree, the heat reduction is doubled
because the fuel tank is protected from direct sunlight and fuel
doesn't vaporize as readily, said Greg McPherson, an urban forest
researcher with the U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   Trees play such an important role in fighting air and water
pollution that many urban planners say trees should be considered
``infrastructure'' just like roads and bridges _ and be funded
accordingly. They would pay for themselves in storm water
prevention savings alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although Atlanta claims trees as its signature asset, the metro
area has taken only baby steps toward valuing them, Bansley said.
Neither the governor's regional transportation agency nor business
leaders' Clean Water Initiative has considered trees as part of
their clean air and clean water strategies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still don't get it,'' said Bansley, who nonetheless
commends the governor for setting aside $30 million for metro area
green space.
</P>
<P>
   Besides fighting pollution, trees add value to businesses. In a
recent study by the University of Washington's Urban Institute,
consumers rated the quality of products in different shopping
districts. Products tested in shopping areas with large numbers of
shade trees were rated 30 percent higher than identical products
rated in shopping areas that were barren of trees.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, trees are like good teachers: undervalued for
their lasting contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
