</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0904-COX     09-03 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trailing a toxic plume
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXAS CITY, Texas _ It seems crystal clear from here. But Max
Shauck's machines are having a fit.
</P>
<P>
   We are looking down at the face of oil refining on Texas' coast.
Aside bulbous, pale storage tanks, heater and boiler stacks reach
to the sky. From here they are like many whiskers on many moles.
</P>
<P>
   Shauck's DeHavilland Twin Otter is making loops at up to 5,000
feet over Galveston Bay and the Houston Ship Channel, sampling air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   We are in what Shauck calls a ``witch's brew'' of nitrogen
oxide, sulfur dioxide and hydrocarbons, the latter being the raw
vapors from petroleum and its byproducts.
</P>
<P>
   The nitrogen oxide _ NOx _ is invisible at its source. But
shortly the sun will cook it into a layer of haze _ ozone _
otherwise known as smog.
</P>
<P>
   Shauck, who heads the Baylor University Aviation Sciences
Department, has been trolling for smog for many years. Over recent
months the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission enlisted
him to draw a portrait of what's blowing where.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Shauck's plane has joined a veritable squadron out
of Houston's Ellington Field, carrying participants in the Texas
2000 air quality study. Scientists from the Environmental
Protection Agency, NASA, U.S. Department of Energy, National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, the University of Texas and
Rice University are making Texas' most intensive air pollution
study ever.
</P>
<P>
   Shauck has flown all over Texas showing how pollution from one
region ends up elsewhere. He's shown, for instance, how emissions
from TXU Electric's Big Brown lignite-fueled plant near Fairfield
contaminates Dallas and Fort Worth, which need no such assist.
</P>
<P>
   He's shown how Gulf Coast pollution has managed to spike up
ozone levels in Crockett, some 140 miles away as the oxide flies.
</P>
<P>
   These are hardly revelations. Back in 1978 scientists enunciated
the air-flow concept of extreme long-range transport, such as East
Coast pollution recirculating all the way to the Florida Sun Coast.
Now scientists are confident that U.S.-made ozone migrates across
the Atlantic to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   DOWNWIND, UPWIND
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows where this came from?''
</P>
<P>
   The way Sergio Alvarez talks about what we're flying through, it
has the air of something the dog dragged home.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it well. His laptop computer is hooked to a row of
instruments in Shauck's plane. They breathe for science.
</P>
<P>
   They show how sun and wind affect the mix. Ozone levels rise at
midday when the NOx gets sun-scorched. At night the layer of ozone
gets compressed and moved out _ maybe from Houston to the Louisiana
coast, or north to the Piney Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone is the principal concern of the TNRCC, which is under
pressure by the EPA to curb smog in Houston, Dallas and El Paso.
Ozone-producing emissions may be stealthy in their short-term
invisibility, but they don't sneak past Shauck's plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're upwind,'' Alvarez says, as the ozone graph on his laptop
hugs the bottom during our first loop. As we put some wind between
us and the refineries of Texas City, the graph shoots skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that,'' exclaims Alvarez, who should be matter-of-fact
about such things.
</P>
<P>
   The graph shows ozone at over 150 parts per billion. The
acceptable EPA standard for a single hour is 120. The graph
moderates for a short while as we head toward and over Houston's
skyline. Now it is spiking up again. The contributors are not
refineries and chemical plants but cars along I-10, with emissions
that include such poisons as carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly Alvarez's laptop shows four abrupt spikes of sulfur
dioxide. They come from four stacks of a power plant under our
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the chemicals gauged are sulfate aerosols _ nasty,
enduring and precursing such secondary pollutants as sulfuric acid.
Sulfates stay in the air hundreds of miles.
</P>
<P>
   Shauck 's plane has gauged the air all over Texas. The Mexican
government has refused to allow monitoring flights over the border.
Such flights would not prove flattering. Mexico is a major
contributor to Texas' air pollution problems, particularly those of
Big Bend and El Paso. By the same token, pollution from Dallas-Fort
Worth has invaded Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   One objective of the Houston airborne study is to ``fingerprint
the power plant plumes,'' said Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   The route Shauck's plane has flown many times from Waco to
Dallas not only reflects pollutants from I-35's intense traffic but
also from the Big Brown plant and others. Alvarez recalled an ozone
reading over Waco one day pushing 100 parts per billion, not enough
for the EPA to swoop, but a sign of things coming.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, not a pleasant sight, even as blue sky abounds and the
view below is surprisingly clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a toxic cesspool,'' said Shauck of the air over the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not Houston's or the ship channel's problem alone.
Someone is demanding all that fuel and power, and paying
insufficient attention to cumulative results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-range transport of pollution is a serious problem,
and it's a global problem,'' said Shauck.
</P>
<P>
   Global meaning that Texas City is all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
