<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   RODMAN'S WORLD: The Worm is turning again, this time to the
Internet in a ``Big Brother-''like way. Former NBA great Dennis
Rodman has launched RodmanTV.com, a subscription-based portal (you
pay the $29.95 a month, not Rodman) offering 24/7 looks into his
Newport Beach home thanks to eight cameras offering ``live,
unedited and uncensored'' takes. (It sounds like ``Big Brother''
and Rodman changes his hair color as often as just-banished BB'er
Brittany). Another reality-TV twist: planned coverage of ``Rodman's
Road Rage,'' an MTV ``Road Rules'' knockoff?
</P>
<P>
   www.rodmantv.com
</P>
<P>
   ``DIARY OF DEATH'': Facing almost certain death, Lu Youqing is
sharing the experience _ and thousands are logging on daily to read
his ``Diary of Death.'' Lu, 37, posted his first entry Aug. 3 and
expects to die within 100 days from the tumor in his neck. His
diary comes just as PBS prepares to air ``On Our Own Terms: Moyers
on Dying,'' by Bill Moyers, on Sunday . A companion piece by
terminally ill WGCL reporter Leigh Green airs afterward. Lu's diary
is in Chinese but is worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   www.Rongshu.com
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOM-FIT NEWS: KNTV in San Jose, Calif., is the first local
television station featured on the FeedRoom, a broadband news
service offering TV-style news on the Internet that can be
personalized. ``We want to be on the cutting edge of new
technology, especially as we're based in the heart of Silicon
Valley,'' says Bob Franklin, president and general manager of KNTV.
</P>
<P>
   www.thefeedroom.com
</P>
