<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AMERICAN-AFRICA0904-C     09-03 2215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-AFRICA0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A free spirit in this season of decision
 &HT;    By Brad Buchholz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We're on the cusp of autumn, the season of
decision. And so it is that 33-year-old Wanda Hall has spent some
time considering the essential question: What sort of choice does a
conscientious American make in this era of national prosperity and
comfort? Democrat? Republican? Nader? Buchanan?
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Hall has made her call. She's packing her bags _ and
moving to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Hall leaves today, in fact, for Arusha, Tanzania _ where she
intends to devote the next three years of her life to promoting
peace in the war-torn Great Lakes region of East Central Africa,
specifically Rwanda. She'll be working for Internews, an
international nonprofit organization that supports independent
media in emerging democracies.
</P>
<P>
   In Arusha, Hall will manage the Internews office at the site of
the International War Crimes Tribunal. Yet she expects to spend
half of her time in nearby Rwanda, a nation still reeling from the
deaths of 800,000 people during the genocide of 1994. Embracing the
motto of ``Peace and justice through media,'' Hall will travel
throughout the country with an African film crew _ showing
villagers a documentary about the tribunal and its aims, and then
recording responses from Hutus and Tutsis who watch the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be showing a film about the genocide _ but what the
tribunal is doing in the aftermath of genocide,'' says Hall,
sitting in the spare living room of the house she shares with her
mother in North Central Austin. ``We'll be traveling with mediators
and facilitators _ so there will be question-and-answers and an
open discussion about what they've seen. The idea is to encourage
dialogue, so that people can start voicing concerns and getting
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job will be to go out with a camera, at the end, and
interview people _ to get their personal testimonies and ask them
what they feel the tribunal can do for them. Then we'll edit the
responses onto the end of the documentary and show them to people
at future stops. I think, in the end, this is a project that will
help people begin to rebuild their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   A noble gesture, to be sure. But why Rwanda? Why gamble with
goodness in such a dangerous and volatile place? Certainly, there
is plenty to be done in the United States. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Hall contends, quite simply, that it's easier for an individual
to make an impact overseas _ particularly in a culture looking for
new truths after its old governmental and social codes have broken
down. ``I truly believe in peace and global stability,'' she says,
in a tone that rings more of pragmatism than pie-in-the-sky
idealism. ``And I've learned that you can create little bitty
miracles in an environment of chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   CHILD OF THE '60S
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Hall was destined, by birth, to take this journey. She was
born in Berkeley, Calif., in the summer of 1967, at the height of
the American peace and civil rights movements. Her parents were
activists. Mom worked for the underground newspaper; Dad shot
photos of National Guard troops firing tear gas at student
protesters at the University of California. Their house was a site
of Black Panthers fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little girl, my mother would sing to me `You
Can't Always Get What You Want' by the Rolling Stones,'' recalls
Hall. ``Or: (From the Youngbloods), `Come on, people now/smile on
your brother/everybody get together/try to love one another right
now.' These were my `goodnight, baby' songs, my `it's time to take
a nap' songs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of divorce in 1968, it was decided that young
Wanda would be raised by her mother, Carol _ who promptly sold the
family possessions to buy a new home, a red VW microbus with a
black butterfly painted on the front. ``My mother was a hippie,''
she says, ``and we lived a hippie life.'' Together, mother and baby
cruised the California coast, camping along the way, selling crafts
at flea markets, baking bread in a makeshift oven they'd place over
their campfire.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the hippies moved to Maui, Hawaii, and lived on the
beach. ``I have memories of getting food stamps and getting this
little thing of Dannon yogurt,'' says Hall. ``We'd set it in the
sand, put a candle on each side of it and share it under the stars.
She taught me about the constellations. We bathed in the ocean. I
learned what it was to be an Anglo minority in the Asian and Samoan
culture that was Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   It was fate _ and empty pockets _ that brought Hall and her
mother to Austin in 1975. They were traveling across the country in
a camper and had run out of money in the Texas town of
Stephenville. ``Look,'' people tried to tell them. ``There's only
one place in the state where you can live as you do, and that's
Austin.'' And so it was that the hippies finally settled in the
Texas capital, where, years later, Hall became a high school honor
student at McCallum.
</P>
<P>
   Hall received her undergraduate degree in International
Relations, with a minor in French, from Simmons College in Boston.
She earned a master's degree in International Policy Studies from
the Monterey Institute of International Studies in California.
Ultimately, however, the experiences of her youth _ a
hippie-child's faith in human nature and a real-life understanding
of food-stamp poverty _ prepared her just as well for the peace
missions that were soon to come.
</P>
<P>
   CHAOS AND MIRACLES Wanda Hall's first international job was in
Moscow, two years after the collapse of the Soviet Union, in the
summer of 1993. She worked for an organization called Search for
Common Ground, and her mission was to try to help Russians resolve
social and ethnic conflicts within a culture where all the old
ground rules had been shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her projects flopped _ such as an ambitious effort to
end ethnic discrimination against Georgians and Armenians within
the Russian military. But there were successes in the areas of
health and labor and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a (television) series on conflict management: ethnic
conflict and labor conflict management in Russia. There were six
30-minute programs, with the AIDS awareness message at the end _
and the whole thing cost $50,000,'' says Hall. Her voice rises, for
the passion of the past is still in her. ``I was 26 years old at
the time. And it was like, `Man. Things can get done!'''
</P>
<P>
   Hall lived in the heart of Moscow, sharing a two-bedroom flat
with a 70-year-old woman. Their diet was mainly potatoes and
carrots. Like the rest of Russia, she waited in line, in the cold,
for bread and milk. Once, they found a lemon _ rather, they paid a
small fortune for a lemon. ``We put it on the table and talked with
each other, for two days, about what we'd do with it,'' says Hall.
``Would we use it for tea? Would we use it in a torte?
</P>
<P>
   ``In this context, I sometimes got so frustrated with Americans
who patted themselves on the back after the fall of Soviet Union,
saying, `We were right. We win. You were wrong. You lose.' And now
we'll introduce the free market. Well, I saw what the free market
did there. And yes: A lot of people got rich very quickly in
Russia. But what about the person who'd been living on a pension _
and now it's all dried up _ and now he can't buy food because
prices are skyrocketing? So many people lost all of their
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, Hall moved to Russia's neighbor to the south,
Kazakhstan, and went to work for the Soros Foundation _ a non
profit organization devoted to building free and open societies,
particularly where cultures are in crisis. And there was crisis in
Kazakhstan. Children were fainting of hunger in the middle of a
school day. The nation's libraries had shut down _ and the
out-of-work librarians were selling the books on the streets to
raise money for food. There was virtually no central heat in the
city buildings, prompting residents to gather en masse on a single
floor to generate enough body heat. The general culture was one of
nepotism and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were a diabetic in Kazakhstan, you were dead by the
time you were 15 _ because no one knew what to do to take care of
themselves,'' says Hall. But in time, she helped Kazaks establish a
nonprofit agency run by the parents of diabetic children to educate
the public about the disease and its treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Working miracles through media: This was Hall's mantra. Once,
she secured a grant to put portable video cameras in the hands of
30 Kazak citizens _ children, grandmothers, parents _ who hit the
streets to record their stories of the ``new'' Kazakhstan to be
broadcast on Kazak television. One 7-year-old shot video of orphans
living on the street, sleeping under cars. In the midst of
financial crisis, the orphanages had been closed down, the children
left to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you the orphanage reopened. It didn't,''
says Hall, her voice strong and sure. ``But the project gave a
voice to people who'd never had a voice before. And the 7-year-old
girl who held that camera learned at a very early age that she had
a voice, a power inside of her. And when she's 27, she's going to
expect more justice than exists in that population today.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CALL TO AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Hall left Kazakhstan in late 1996, having completed her
contract with the Soros Foundation and feeling the need to
re-energize. Hall had been shaken, too, by the killing of an
American compatriot she'd known there. So she spent the next 15
months in school in London, then returned home to Austin. She
reunited with her mother, took a part-time job and returned,
briefly, to an American life. Still, Hall pined for a new challenge
_ and this time, the voice within was calling her to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Why Rwanda? Because it was a culture in chaos, in need of small
miracles, and she'd been touched by the horror of the genocide. A
colleague had told her about his experience as a broadcaster in
neighboring Burundi _ producing little radio plays, written by
Africans, that dealt with themes of ethnic reconciliation. Again,
the use of media to achieve justice enthralled her.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many negative socialization forces have gotten power
through mass media,'' she says. ``It only makes sense to me that
positive ones could do so also.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, Hall learned that the best way to get a job in Rwanda _
since she had no experience anywhere in Africa _ was to fly there,
at her own expense, and get firsthand knowledge of the social
landscape in the Great Lakes region. So she spent more than a month
in the Rwandan capital of Kigali, knocking on doors, making
connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you notice about Rwanda is that it's a
tropical paradise _ and yet you know the people there have
witnessed a hell that I could barely imagine,'' she says now,
sitting in her mother's house, where there's a simple Rwandan rug
on the tile floor. ``If you drive downtown, though, you see all
these one-legged men hopping up and down the hills of Kigali with
the aid of a stick. I mean, the hills of Kigali are steep, and I
would not have thought such a thing was humanly possible. . . . But
the tenacity the people have for life there is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, on the eve of her departure, Hall's friends ask her,
gently: Why incur such an expense? Why subject yourself to personal
risk and discomfort? Why not stay in Austin _ and get a job at
Dell?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could have thought of anything else I could do with my
life, I would have pursued it,'' she says with a chuckle. ``But
when I closed my eyes and thought, `What do I want to do with my
life?' That's what I want to do, to explore a different culture
that fascinates me and accomplish something worthy _ something I
know I can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea how alive you feel, how human you feel, when
you share a meal with someone that lives across the globe from you,
and speaks a different language from you, and wears different
clothes than you. And you're laughing together, sharing each
other's humanness.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that Wanda Hall will never see Austin again. Her
mother has talked about selling their house, moving to cooler
climates in the north, and it figures to be a long time before her
daughter returns to America for a holiday visit. How much of it is
destiny? How much of it is choice? And what will she be thinking,
far from home, on Election Day, that day of American choice?
</P>
<P>
   ``As an American, I'm thankful for the opportunity to exercise
this kind of a choice _ a creative and optimistic choice _ that I
probably wouldn't be able to make had I grown up in another
country,'' says Hall, who intends to cast her presidential vote at
the U.S. embassy in Tanzania. ``When Americans cast their votes
this year, instead of thinking about how happy they are to live in
the richest country in the world, they might be thinking about how
they have the freedom to do something that is not the norm. To be
true to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Hall carries that thought with her to the skies, on the
way to a broken land, comfortable that she's cast the vote that
counts the most in the season of decision.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
