   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-MEMORIAL-SERVICE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Seventy relatives
and friends from around the world who gathered Sunday for a
memorial service at sea honoring 778 Romanian Jews and crew members
who died in 1942 when a Russian submarine sank their disabled ship,
the Struma. The sinking of the Struma was a wartime tragedy that
the world had largely forgotten. But some of the sensitivities
surrounding the episode were resurrected by the effort led by a
grandson of two of the victims to locate the wreckage and to
conduct the memorial service. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ELECTIONS (Beirut) _ The second round of parliamentary
elections. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHAS (Jerusalem) _ The former leader of Israel's powerful
Shas party, Aryeh Deri, began serving a three-year sentence for
bribery and fraud on Sunday while thousands of ultra-Orthodox Jews
prayed outside the prison. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-EARTHQUAKE-DRILL (Tokyo) _ Shintaro Ishihara, the governor
of Tokyo prefecture has long been known as a populist conservative
showman. He clearly lived up to his reputation when he turned a
hitherto boring annual earthquake readiness drill into one of the
largest military exercises that most Japanese have seen since the
end of World War II. By Howard W. French.
</P>
