<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ITALY-CHAMINADE-0904-     09-03 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-CHAMINADE-0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE JOHN PAUL BEATIFIES FATHER CHAMINADE
 &HT;    For release Monday, Sept. 4
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY _ After a century of prayers by his followers
around the world, Father William
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Chaminade was beatified Sunday by Pope John Paul during a
four-hour ceremony in the stifling
</P>
<P>
   heat at St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 pilgrims crowded into the vast square to
witness five beatifications _ including the
</P>
<P>
   much loved Pope John XXIII and the decidedly controversial Pope
Pius IX, who is accused by his
</P>
<P>
   detractors of being anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   After the 80-year-old pontiff proclaimed the beatifications _
the penultimate step toward sainthood _
</P>
<P>
   huge portraits of the newly blessed were unfurled in the square
to cheers and applause. As many as 7,000
</P>
<P>
   Marianists _ the order founded by Chaminade, a 19th Century
French priest _ were mingled in the massive
</P>
<P>
   crowd.
</P>
<P>
   For Brother John Lucier of Dayton, Ohio, the elevation of
Chaminade was the answer to more six decades of prayer. Even though
the searing heat in the square was taking its toll on Lucier, 83,
he considered it
</P>
<P>
   inconceivable to miss a minute of Sunday's ceremony. ``I would
have been there on my knees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've prayed for this every day for 63 years,'' said Lucier, a
retired chemistry professor at the
</P>
<P>
   University of Dayton, which was founded by Marianists. ``It's
the capstone of a lifetime. I didn't think
</P>
<P>
   I would live to see it. Someday he'll be declared a saint, but I
don't know if I'll be around for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the approximately 125 pilgrims from Dayton said after
the ceremony that they were elated
</P>
<P>
   and exhausted from standing _ or for the lucky, sitting _ for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Wagner, the university's director of Marianist activity, an
official at the university,
</P>
<P>
   was moved by the mass humanity gathered in the square. ``There
was this press of the crowd with everybody
</P>
<P>
   wanting their own place in the midst of this very holy
celebration,'' she said. ``I feel a bit overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, to realize that we are part of something so much bigger _
I don't think that I could put words to the experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who appeared before the adoring crowd in kelly green
robes, read the beatification
</P>
<P>
   proclamations from under a large tent. His image was displayed
on huge TV screens in the square. He
</P>
<P>
   appeared tired and frail.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff recalled the story of Chaminade, who was persecuted
during the French Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Chaminade, founded the Marianists, a religious order credited
with reviving Christianity in post-
</P>
<P>
   revolutionary France. The Society of Mary was established in the
United States in 1849 in Dayton and
</P>
<P>
   Marianists have a strong presence in the city, most notably at
the university.
</P>
<P>
   Marianists work in 34 countries with ministries in secondary and
primary schools, universities and
</P>
<P>
   technical schools, parishes, renewal centers, missions and
social justice enterprises. The gathering in Rome
</P>
<P>
   this weekend was the largest in the order's history.
</P>
<P>
   Also beatified were Italian bishop Tommaso Reggio (1818-1901)
and Irish abbot Columba
</P>
<P>
   Marmion.
</P>
<P>
   In his homily, the Pope addressed the controversy over Pius IX,
saying that holiness was not
</P>
<P>
   immune to historical influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanctity lives in history, and every saint is not removed from
the limitations and personal conditioning of our human nature,'' he
said. ``By beatifying one of its sons, the Church does not
celebrate particular historical choices he made but rather points
him out for imitation and veneration for his virtues.''
</P>
<P>
   Pius was pope from 1846 to 1878, the longest reign in church
history. This period coincided with the
</P>
<P>
   loss of the papacy's temporal power and vast land holdings when
Italy was unified.
</P>
<P>
   Pius, who adamantly opposed religious tolerance and defined the
doctrine of infallibility, once referred to
</P>
<P>
   Jews as ``dogs.'' Jews and progressive Catholics opposed his
beatification.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the crowd roared in approval when he spoke of Pope
John XXIII, known as ``The Good
</P>
<P>
   Pope.''
</P>
<P>
   For 22-year-old Adam Molina, a University of Dayton senior from
Cincinnati, the weekend brought the grand scale of his church into
focus. ``It's affected me profoundly,'' Molina said later during a
tour of the Roman Forum
</P>
<P>
   with friends. ``Things make more sense to me. Words I've used
all my life _ all these other people use
</P>
<P>
   them too _ now make sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Molina said the experiences of the weekend would linger with him
for the rest of his life. ``You can
</P>
<P>
   only get a true sense of our Catholic faith by taking a journey
like this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bert Roughton Jr. can be e-mailed at: bertr(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
