   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-XBOX (Redmond, Wash.) _ A look at Microsoft's X-Box
strategy, the company's most ambitious assault yet on the consumer
electronics market. The software giant has vowed to commit $500
million in order to elbow its way into a consumer electronics
market, which is governed by a business model that is anathema to
most of the strategies Microsoft has pursued in the software
business. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-BIZWIRES (Undated) _ In the wake of the press-release hoax
perpetrated against Emulex, and the speed with which it traveled
around the Internet, we take a look inside the business-wire
newsrooms. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IBM (Undated) _ When the computer system that IBM built to
report results at the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta
malfunctioned, the proud computing giant learned the hard way what
it is like to stumble with the whole world watching. Now, with this
year's Summer Olympics set to begin soon in Sydney, Australia, and
IBM's 40-year run as a technology supplier for the Olympics slated
to end in December, Big Blue is pushing hard to make sure it brings
home some public relations gold. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTV-GM-HUGHES (Undated) _ News Analysis: a look at General
Motors and its Hughes Electronics Corp., the unit with the
fast-growing DirecTV satellite-television business. By Laura M.
Holson.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The New Economy column: a look at
how well, or not, the international system for Internet domain-name
disputes is working. By Laurie J. Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   EB-MUSIC-TRIAL (Undated) _ In the trial this week between
MP3.com and Universal, mp3.com is trying a novel approach,
challenging the record company's control of its own copyrights. By
Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: Sports sites
are welcoming the return of the NFL, NHL and NBA seasons, because
that means an uptick in traffic _ and sales in their online stores.
A couple of years ago, many major sites tried to build their own
stores, but realized they didn't have the expertise to become
retailers. So they've increasingly outsourced their stores to other
companies, who operate those stores under the ``Sportsline'' or
``CNNsi.com'` guise. There are a host of issues that go along with
such an approach _ including the possible customer confusion. But
these Web sites say the alternative is much worse. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   TUVALU-DOMAIN (Undated) _ A look at the Internet company that
promised millions to a tiny island nation for rights to its domain:
.tv. By Jane Black.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DEBT (Tokyo) _ A major Japanese construction company,
Kumagai Gumi, is expected to ask its creditors to forgive $4.25 in
debt. By Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Sabra
Chartrand.
