<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WEB-BIZWIRES-2TAKES-N     09-03 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-BIZWIRES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOLED BY FAKE NEWS RELEASE, BLOOMBERG TAKES STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Noon, Wednesday, Aug. 30. The ``page one'' meeting
for Bloomberg News is in full swing at a conference room in
Bloomberg's midtown Manhattan headquarters. Linked by Webcams and
videoscreens, editors in Europe and the United States chew over the
day's hot news, discussing what stories belong on Bloomberg's main
screen.
</P>
<P>
   And like any good editor in chief, Matthew Winkler, a former
Wall Street Journal reporter who has led Bloomberg News since it
was founded a decade ago, is not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``This needs to be overhauled,'' Winkler said as he looked at a
story about Royal Philips Electronics, the Dutch conglomerate, with
a confusing lead sentence. On another story, he explained, ``I'm
not a big fan of this word `robust,' because it means whatever you
want it to mean. Do we mean growing demand, increasing demand? Then
why don't we say that?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the meeting was solidly in the tradition of the daily
conferences that newspapers use to discuss what stories to run.
There was just one difference. Every story that Winkler critiqued
was already out on Bloomberg's 144,000 workstations, a staple of
trading floors around the world. These first-version wire stories
needed work to meet Winkler's standards of clarity and style, but
they were accurate and on hot topics. So they were posted, whatever
their imperfections, awaiting further updates and more editing.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of financial news services, the most hotly
competitive place in journalism today. With 950 reporters and 79
bureaus, Bloomberg competes to break news with Dow Jones, Reuters
and Bridge News, along with newspaper Web sites, dozens of smaller
Internet sites and even gossipy chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The race never ends, moving with the sun from Asia to Europe to
the United States, and at any moment fortunes in trading profits
are staked on the speed and accuracy of the news that Bloomberg and
its competitors provide.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fast-growing, lucrative business, but the intense
pressure to be first is not without cost. Ten days ago, Bloomberg
committed a spectacular blunder, falling for a fake press release
and publishing a story that caused shares in Emulex, a California
communications equipment company, to plunge 55 points in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The release, which came over Internet Wire, a service that
distributes company news, claimed in suspiciously vague terms that
Emulex's chief executive had resigned and the company would restate
its earnings. Bloomberg reported the release as fact, even though
it was unable to confirm with Emulex that the news was real.
</P>
<P>
   The hoax was quickly discovered, and Emulex stock regained its
value within hours. On Thursday, federal prosecutors charged Mark
S. Jakob, a 23-year-old California man, with securities fraud for
the hoax. But Emulex investors who panicked and sold their shares
as the stock plunged are unlikely to recover their losses. One
angry investor has now sued Bloomberg and Internet Wire, claiming
he lost $15,000 as a result of their recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bloomberg will continue to use information from PR
Newswire and Business Wire, the leading press release wires, as
well as Internet Wire, without verifying its authenticity in most
cases, Winkler said. Financial news services and other media
organizations get press releases 15 minutes before they are
distributed to the general public, fueling a furious competition
among the news services to rewrite them for their subscribers
during their window of exclusivity.
</P>
<P>
   Given the sheer crush of news releases, wire services do not
generally verify their authenticity, a task impossible under
current competitive pressures. Traders watch for news intently and
react almost instantaneously to news, creating intense pressure on
the financial wires to be first with headlines and stories. To keep
up, Bloomberg has a team of seven people at its Princeton, N.J.,
bureau who monitor press release wires full-time.
</P>
<P>
   The job has grown harder, said Brian Rooney, a Bloomberg editor
at large. The number of releases has soared over the last two
years, largely due to the growing number of public companies and
startups looking for publicity, Rooney said. ``You end up with just
a lot more releases to sort through than you ever had before,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler said the hoax had caused Bloomberg to toughen its
standards on using information from press releases, even those from
PR Newswire and Business Wire. If the releases have unusual
information, Bloomberg reporters will now be required to confirm
that they are real before using them. For example, if a company
reported earnings of 60 cents per share and analysts expected
earnings of 58 cents, that would not be unusual. But if the release
reported earnings of 20 cents, a reporter would confirm the
accuracy of the release with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything on those releases is remotely a surprise, yes,
we're calling them,'' Winkler said. ``It doesn't matter who's
saying it's kosher. We're still going to ask the rabbi to bless
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Winkler also insisted the new policy would not slow
Bloomberg. ``We don't intend to sacrifice speed in any way,'' he
said. Reporters would have to be better prepared to reach company
public relations officers immediately.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some public relations firms say they want the press
release wires to institute uniform security standards to lessen the
risk of another hoax. The news wires should be careful in dealing
with press release wires that do not have strict security, said Tim
Johnson, managing director of the San Francisco office of
Golin/Harris International, a public relations agency that
represents about 450 clients worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are careful with every release,'' said David Armon, senior
vice president of PR Newswire. His company conducts a credit check
and calls back companies to verify that they are represented by the
public relations firm that claims to represent them, he said.
Still, PR Newswire cannot vouch for the factual accuracy of its
releases, he said. ``As long as the attribution checks out, the
clients are allowed to say pretty much what they want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet Wire says it has tightened its security policies since
the hoax.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the hoax is unlikely to hurt Bloomberg's long-term
growth. Thanks to the explosion in financial markets, Bloomberg has
17 times as many subscribers as it did a decade ago. The company,
which charges more than $15,000 annually for a subscription to its
workstations, will have revenue of more than $2 billion this year,
and Bloomberg's journalistic ambitions are swelling alongside its
financial resources. The service has added almost 200 reporters in
the last eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler said the hoax was a chance for Bloomberg to improve its
standards and encourage its reporters to think more critically
about unexpected news. ``This event to me is an opportunity for us
to get to a much higher level,'' he said. ``What I'm trying to do
after last week is to try to get people to think.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Winkler is intensifying efforts to have reporters
prepare for events they know are coming, like earnings releases. If
a release is unusual, reporters will be able to react immediately,
confirming the authenticity of the release.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bloomberg may not be able to put the hoax in the past as
quickly as it would like. The Emulex shareholder who says he lost
$15,000 as a result of the hoax sued Bloomberg and Internet Wire on
Thursday in federal court in New York, claiming they recklessly
disseminated misleading information about Emulex.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg and Internet Wire declined to comment on the suit,
which seeks class-action status. Floyd Abrams, an expert in First
Amendment law, said the plaintiffs face an uphill battle. The First
Amendment protects honest mistakes in news gathering, and
information about a publicly traded company is by definition of
interest to the public, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say Bloomberg would have a powerful defense, and the
only circumstances they would not is if they knew what they were
publishing was false,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
