<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COE-RACIST-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      09-03 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COE-RACIST-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOTLEGGED RACIST DISCS CIRCULATING ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early '80s the outlaw country singer David Allan Coe
released very small quantities of two underground albums of songs
that are among the most racist, misogynist, homophobic and obscene
songs recorded by a popular songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Bootlegged by fans and college fraternity members for years,
those songs have recently been stirring up new trouble on the
Internet: They are being passed around as e-mail files accompanied
by sexually explicit and racist animation, and they are being
posted as computer files on Web sites like www.whitesonly.net.
</P>
<P>
   Coe, who has long distanced himself from the music and toned
down his act for his last record deal with Sony/Lucky Dog, has
decided to start making money from the old music anyway. He is
selling the songs on one CD on his own Web site for $45 plus
shipping ($25 for cassette), though he refuses to put his name on
the disc or packaging.
</P>
<P>
   All of this comes as Coe is being exposed to a new audience,
thanks to the Detroit rap-metal star Kid Rock, who invited Coe to
be an opening act on his current tour, which ended Friday. The pair
also recently recorded several songs together in a Detroit studio.
Some music fans are wondering how Kid Rock, who has collaborated
with black rappers and has made a living through appropriating
their music, can be touring with a songwriter responsible for
blatantly anti-black material.
</P>
<P>
   In one song on Coe's ``X-Rated Hits'' CD, he rails against white
women who sleep with black men, singing that it makes him want to
throw up; in another, the chorus has it that some blacks ``never
die/They just smell that way.'' The lyrics are a far cry from the
songs Coe is better known for writing: Johnny Paycheck's ``Take
This Job and Shove It,'' Tanya Tucker's ``Would You Lay With Me (In
a Field of Stone)'' and his own hits like ``The Ride'' and
``Willie, Waylon and Me.'' In fact many of Coe's ``X-Rated Hits''
even make Eminem's heavily attacked recent album seem
tenderhearted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in my office _ black, white, male, female _ is going
to Napster and downloading these Coe songs,'' said Randy Weiner,
who is president of Aka.com, a network of hip-hop and rock Web
sites. ``And the reaction is always the same: They laugh at the
first song they hear, thinking it's a funny country parody. But by
the third or fourth song about hating women and black people, they
start to get uncomfortable and angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Coe rarely performs his obscene and racist material in
public, despite fan requests, he does sell the ``X-Rated Hits'' CD
at his shows. It is unclear, however, whether he is also selling
the music at Kid Rock concerts because of conflicting reports from
fans and spokesmen for both acts. Despite being called several
times, Coe's manager, Bill Quisenberry, would not speak on the
record about his client's ``X-Rated'' recordings or their sale. A
spokeswoman for Kid Rock said that she was unable to reach the
singer or his management for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kid Rock is a strange amalgam of influences, reveling in
white-trash culture while appropriating black music, imagery and
terminology. Embodying the contradictions of the mainstream genre
of rap-metal, Kid Rock drops black slang into his songs, like
saying that he ``macks like a real G.'' At the same time he says he
is ``a John Deere-driving ... hick.'' On one hand, hiring Coe to
open his shows is a natural fit for the side of Kid Rock that
proudly says he was brought up in a trailer (though, like Coe's
unsubstantiated boast that he killed a fellow inmate who tried to
seduce him in prison, it's a dubious assertion).
</P>
<P>
   Kelefa Sanneh, the deputy editor of Transition, a journal of
black culture, said the concert pairing is evidence that hip-hop
has infiltrated so deeply into American culture that it is no
longer necessary to be hip, multicultural and cosmopolitan _ or
even to care about black culture _ to be a part of it. ``It's no
different than when Southern rock bands in the '70s were playing
blues-rock and flying the Confederate flag,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coe's obscene songs were released briefly in 1980 and 1982 as
two homemade albums _ ``Underground'' and ``Nothing Sacred'' _ and
sold through biker magazines. ``He recorded those when he was
riding with an outlaw motorcycle gang,'' said Bill Davis, a Web
designer who runs a David Allan Coe fan site. ``They were biker
humor records, but then they became a big hit. It seems like he
gets a lot of the young college kids with the `X-Rated' stuff, and
that then turns them on to his real music.''
</P>
<P>
   On Coe's official Web site, it is explained that Coe decided to
reissue the material on one CD as ``a collector's item'' on his own
label because he was tired of seeing other people make money by
selling bootleg copies. The Web site adds that ``he will not agree
to using his name on the records or to promote their sale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
