<HEADLINE>
HOW CHICKENS FLY _ AND THREE WAYS TO MARINATE THEIR WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Remember a few years ago when you ran a recipe for cracked
goat shins?'' a reader is liable to write.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are I don't remember and my only excuse is that I have
passed on approximately 3,800 recipes since this column was
hatched.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sieger swears he has read most of them and suggests that
I republish some of the best recipes. What he specifically had in
mind were three chicken-wing marinades first published about 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but first I have to tell you _ again _ about chickens, and
their night flights over Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they're sneaky about it. By day they cluck around the
barnyard looking aerodynamically unsound. And they try to prove it
with an occasional five-yard flight ending in an explosion of
feathers and chicken curses.
</P>
<P>
   By night, however, they soar into the clouds, headed for distant
barnyards and foreign lovers.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of their flight is overwhelming. Each chicken is
equipped with two (2) wings, standard issue for ducks, robins and
Boeing 747s. They have wings, ergo they fly. And they must fly
pretty far since their wings are savored from the Texas Panhandle
to Peking (that's what we called Beijing 30 years ago) and
Pakistan, enhanced by various marinades.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, chickens and chicken wings are found in
supermarkets, vendor stalls and county markets on every continent.
</P>
<P>
   Poultry distributors are all somewhat embarrassed by all this.
Hardly anyone gets to see the chickens fly. Yet here they are
trying to peddle wings. As a consequence they are often offered to
customers like Richard Sieger at distress prices.
</P>
<P>
   None of these marinades are very expensive, either.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 smashed clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 drops Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon onion powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   Mix and pour over the wings.
</P>
<P>
   PEKING
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sherry
</P>
<P>
   2 minced green onions
</P>
<P>
   Combine in pan, heat until sugar dissolves, and pour over wings.
</P>
<P>
   PANHANDLE
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fruit juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Boil two minutes, and pour over the wings.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you cook them you should first cut the tips off
each wing and discard or save to make chicken stock. Then whack the
wings at the second joint so you have two pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Marinate refrigerated for at least a couple of hours. To cook
place on a lightly greased pan and cover loosely with aluminum
foil. Shove the pan into a 350 oven for 25 or 30 minutes, removing
foil twice to baste.
</P>
<P>
   To crisp the wings remove the foil and return to oven for
another 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The quantities of marinades listed above vary, according to the
number of chickens that crash-land in your yard between 10 p.m. and
4 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
