<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LITTLE-BOOK-REVIEW-83     09-03 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLE-BOOK-REVIEW-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT'S THE LITTLE THINGS': PERCEPTIONS, AND REALITIES, ABOUT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
Maureen Corrigan, who teaches literature at Georgetown University,
is the book critic for the National Public Radio program ``Fresh
Air.'' 
 By MAUREEN CORRIGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy being white. Consider, for instance, the plight of
a white reader of Lena Williams' ``It's the Little Things,'' a
popular exploration of how racial prejudice in America affects even
the most casual social transactions.
</P>
<P>
   According to the black people (including herself) Williams
quotes, we white folks smell like dogs when we're wet, generally
look a lot older than our age (unlike blacks, who look younger,
since, as the saying goes, ``black don't crack''), shamelessly
coddle our misbehaving children (unlike black parents, who come
down hard on children ``showing out in public'') and, of course,
can't dance, party, cook or jump.
</P>
<P>
   White women go around flipping their long, straight manes in
public, which annoys surrounding blacks, who are sensitive about
their hair, while in locker rooms across the land, white men cower
in corners when black men undress.
</P>
<P>
   A white reader of ``It's the Little Things'' seemingly has only
two choices: either to kowtow to all the genial mau-mauing here or
to get defensive and, thus, confirm what the black people whom
Williams quotes also seem to think _ that white people are
close-minded, arrogant and often just plain dumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Little Things'' grew out of an article that Williams,
a longtime reporter and now a sportswriter for The New York Times,
wrote for The Times in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The article provoked such intense reaction, particularly to the
business about whites ``flipping and flopping and slinging'' their
hair, that Williams expanded her investigations into this book,
which is clearly modeled on Deborah Tannen's megabest seller, ``You
Just Don't Understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Tannen explored misunderstandings between the sexes that she
ascribed to different male and female linguistic styles; Williams
aims to chronicle ``the racial slights and indignities'' that occur
between the races _ the everyday kinds of ``little things'' that
wouldn't get mentioned in more formal racial discussions sponsored
by government or academia.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Williams traveled around the country
participating in and sometimes mediating mixed-race focus groups.
Although ``It's the Little Things'' purports to expose remarks,
gestures and assumptions that offend Americans on either side of
the racial divide, black voices and views predominate here.
</P>
<P>
   Williams acknowledges that ``blacks appeared more willing than
whites to speak openly and honestly about their racial attitudes _
perhaps because we feel we have less to lose. Whites who shared
their thoughts and opinions did so, for the most part, only with
the assurance of anonymity.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of those anonymous whites pipe up in this book to register
resentment at affirmative action, at the O.J. Simpson verdict and
at blacks who talk back to movie screens, but even then Williams or
her black interviewees have the last rectifying word. ``We are a
vocal people,'' Williams asserts in answer to the complaint about
chattering movie-theater audiences.
</P>
<P>
   As Williams correctly notes, blacks have necessarily been
studying white behavior for centuries. But from the evidence of
this book, this hard-won experience has not necessarily generated
wisdom. Williams' interviewees spout off a lot of racial
generalizations and summon up all manner of stray anecdotes and gut
feelings to back up their essentialist convictions. Even when these
remarks seem true _ as they often do _ those truths are well known
and rarely provoke more thought.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling of the kinds of observations and musings, all
made by black interviewees, that compose much of the book: ``We all
know that once whites get in, they want to take over. They want to
be in charge, whether it's our fraternities, sororities or our
churches.'' ``Whites act as though they got all their jobs because
they were qualified. For years whites got jobs because their dad
played golf with the boss or their mother belonged to the same
bridge club as the boss's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams does little to synthesize the remarks she has elicited
from others and weighs in herself with comments like ``Deep down,
many whites truly feel that most blacks look alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Since ``It's the Little Things'' deals with people's perceptions
rather than realities about race, the book doesn't have to trouble
itself over the accuracy of these remarks. And since hardly anyone
Williams quotes brings up the issue of class, neither does she,
although a recognition of class differences would have been a
welcome corrective to the prevailing impression here that all white
people are well connected and that all black people belong to an
undifferentiated mass.
</P>
<P>
   (``An American Story,'' the new memoir by the black journalist
and lawyer Debra Dickerson, offers a smart, nuanced counterpoint to
the strange silence about class in this book _ as does much of the
great African-American fiction and autobiography of the 20th
century, from Ralph Ellison to Malcolm X to Toni Morrison.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Williams' relentless depiction of the vast incommensurability of
blacks and whites makes even their most modest social interactions
seem as fraught with incomprehension as a lunch for Captain Kirk
and the Klingons. In the pages of this book blacks seem at once
utterly different from whites yet not at all differentiated from
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the sociologist Orlando Patterson _ from whom on any single
page of his works one learns more about race in America than in
this entire book _ observes in ``The Ordeal of Integration'' that
Afro-Americans (his term of choice) are quintessentially American
in their values and traditions but have as much intragroup
heterogeneity as the many European-derived variations of white
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with ``It's the Little Things'' is the
paucity of its argument. Williams offers no tips to bridge the
racial divide that she highlights, beyond her suggestion toward the
book's end that we all lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the quality of the insights found here don't rise
above the level of your average Internet chat room, one wonders
what the point of this book is, beyond what one wag noted some
years ago when blacks began to earnestly squeeze toilet paper and
hysterically suffer from heartburn in television commercials:
Foolishness is the birthright of blacks and whites alike.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IT'S THE LITTLE THINGS'
</P>
<P>
   The Everyday Interactions That Get Under the Skin of Blacks and
Whites
</P>
<P>
   By Lena Williams
</P>
<P>
   268 pages. Harcourt. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0040 </DOCNO>
