u f BC-DIRECTV-GM-HUGHES-NYT     09-03 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTV-GM-HUGHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICAHN'S MOVE FORCES GM TO CONSIDER HUGHES DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When General Motors announced last month that Carl Icahn was
buying its stock, Wall Street analysts quickly surmised that he saw
potential in the Hughes Electronics Corp., the satellite-television
unit.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, which acquired Hughes Aircraft in 1985, has
sought ways in recent years to unlock the value of the fast-growing
unit, whose coveted satellite TV operation known as DirecTV is
expected to have 10 million subscribers by year-end. Early on, GM
issued a Hughes tracking stock, which reflects the performance of
the unit. This year, the company distributed more Hughes stock to
shareholders. But the moves have done little to appease Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Icahn, who is known for identifying undervalued assets and
who recently made a $600 million profit on his Nabisco holdings,
has raised investors' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Harry Pearce, vice chairman of
General Motors, said GM was considering an outright sale of the
company, a merger, or partnerships and joint ventures with other
companies. ``We clearly believe that the market is not properly
valuing the company,'' Pearce said. ``We are carefully evaluating
the different options.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearce declined to name Hughes suitors but outlined the three
types of businesses that GM considered likely partners: direct
broadcasters and competitors of DirecTV, media companies and
Internet or broadband concerns.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, however, has several issues to sort out before a
deal can be brokered, and any announcement is probably months away.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that an outright sale of Hughes could create a
big tax liability. General Motors bought Hughes for $5.3 billion in
cash and stock, and some analysts suggest that it could fetch $60
billion today.
</P>
<P>
   Second, General Motors gets a credit rating boost by owning
Hughes, a valuable asset, and analysts say it would be unlikely to
take any action that would jeopardize that rating. They note that a
lower rating would adversely effect its robust consumer lending
business, which accounted for 26 percent of GM's profit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Most stock analysts expect General Motors to do some type of an
equity transaction, a merger or stock exchange perhaps, with a cash
component. Pearce, too, was quick to point out that ``cash is
king.''
</P>
<P>
   But the automaker must decide what stock _ media, Internet or
otherwise _ it is willing to accept in any transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The most logical partner, according to stock analysts, would be
a media company. They point to renewed interest from Rupert
Murdoch, chairman of the News Corp., the media giant that held
discussions with Hughes earlier this year, according to people who
were briefed on the talks. Hughes' DirecTV would give Murdoch the
distribution he desires in the United States. But the News Corp. is
taking public Sky Global Networks, a satellite service for pay
television, Internet and data services, and it is not clear how
much Murdoch could offer and whether General Motors would be
willing to accept Sky Global stock.
</P>
<P>
   People who have been informed about the various discussions said
that General Motors is also mulling some type of combination with
several other media companies, including Disney, Viacom, and NBC, a
unit of General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Nabi, who follows satellite communications companies for
Merrill Lynch, said an acquirer might have to offer $60 billion for
the Hughes assets. But he warned that the acquirer or partner that
Hughes prefers might not be the one General Motors would pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a betting man, I think General Motors wants to let
Hughes think about it and come to them with an idea,'' Nabi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will go to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   Icahn has not discussed his wishes but has simply notified GM
that he is seeking to buy at least $15 million in GM stock, and no
more than 15 percent of the company. News of his interest pushed up
both GM's stock and the Hughes tracking stock. GM's shares closed
the week at $73.125, well off its recent high of $94.625 in April.
The Hughes shares, GM's class H, closed at $34.813, also well off
their $47 high point earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   From a strategic point of view, Pearce said Hughes is grappling
with whether it should align itself with one company or strike
alliances with several content providers. ``We see competing
approaches,'' he said. ``We're trying to sort that out.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors also has to decide whether nonmedia partners
would make more sense for Hughes. For instance, it could try to
merge with a competitor like Echostar Communications, which would
expand the customer list but might raise antitrust questions.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce did not discount the possibility of a merger between
Hughes and Echostar. Satellite makers now compete with cable and
telecommunications operators to provide Internet access to homes
and businesses. As such, they should be able to argue that cable
and telecommunications companies are the competition, not each
other, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes could even opt to merge with an Internet company _ an
approach considered less likely. Hughes is developing new satellite
programs that it hopes will create two-way transmission not only
with television sets, but also with personal computers and other
devices. So becoming a bigger part of the online revolution is not
out of the question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
