<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TUVALU-DOMAIN-ART-NYT     09-03 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUVALU-DOMAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC ISLAND NATION PARLEYS ITS CYBERSPACE INTO A HIGHER LIVING
STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT5  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
 Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE BLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the height of the Internet land rush in 1998, an
unusual story stood out from the rest: the tiny nation of Tuvalu
sold, for $50 million, the rights to its chunk of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Tuvalu, a string of islands halfway between Hawaii and Australia
with a population of just 10,600, had rarely made world headlines.
But the multimillion-dollar sale, to an ambitious Web entrepreneur
in Canada, changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   The story really began when Tuvalu, along with dozens of other
nations and territories, was assigned its own two-letter suffix
that signifies an Internet domain. Under the assignment, Britain
received .uk, France received .fr, and Tuvalu received .tv.
</P>
<P>
   Into this picture came Jason Chapnik, a 28-year-old entrepreneur
from Toronto. Chapnik says he came up with the idea of registering
names within the .tv domain as early as 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started brainstorming,'' Chapnik recalled in a telephone
interview from his home. ``If we could have dot-anything, what
would we want? We made lists _ dot-info, dot-law. Once we hit on
dot-tv as a concept, we knew we had it.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting the rights to the .tv domain from Tuvalu would not
be easy. Chapnik sent written proposals and spent months
researching and making contacts with the Tuvalu government. By
1997, other people had come up with the same idea. By 1998, the
Tuvalu government had narrowed the prospects down to three
companies. So Chapnik and his wife, Jodi, took a vacation and went
to the islands to make their pitch. In the fall of 1998, after
months of negotiation, Tuvalu made its decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my wife won it for us,'' Chapnik said. ``Family is
very important to them. Coming down with my wife and not business
partners spoke volumes to them.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Chapnik secured millions of dollars in
backing from a leading Internet incubator, Idealab, which provided
expertise and the capital needed to pay Tuvalu and build the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Tuvalu is to receive the $50 million over the
next 12 years. Already, the company has paid the country $18
million. The payments so far have increased the country's gross
domestic product by 50 percent and allowed the government to put
electricity on the outer islands and create scholarships for its
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Chapnik had succeeded at turning his idea into a viable Internet
business company, dotTV, which is now 50 percent owned by Idealab.
</P>
<P>
   The company's business plan is simple. It wants to be the next
Network Solutions. As the wholesaler to the registrars of .com,
.net and .org, Network Solutions made millions of dollars
registering Internet addresses, largely because of the aura of the
popular .com domain.
</P>
<P>
   DotTV believes it can have the same kind of success with its
domain, which it says is made up of the most recognizable two
letters on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has its own site at www.tv, registers
addresses on its Web site and through third parties like Dotster
and GreatDomains.com. Most prices start at $100. Words and letter
combinations with higher perceived value, like call letters of a
television station, are auctioned off, starting at $1,000. Three
names _ free.tv, china.tv and net.tv _ have each sold for $100,000,
the company said last month.
</P>
<P>
   DotTV also has tried to sell domains in more unconventional
ways. In July, it partnered with the Internet auctioneer Ibidlive
to sell domains in an auction shown on television. The auction,
which ran during a commercial break of a Seinfeld episode in Santa
Barbara, Calif., made three domain names available and encouraged
viewers to bid online. One, beach.tv, sold for $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The company's most recent success involved the Academy of
Television Arts and Sciences, which agreed to relocate from
emmys.org and emmycast.com to emmys.tv. It also sold .tv domains to
the Pax broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that is exploding,'' said Craig Francis,
dotTV's chief operating officer. ``Even at $100 a pop, which is
what most names go for,'' he added, ``this has the potential to be
very profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis would not say how many names had been sold so far, only
that it was in the tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   To sell more names, dotTV is trying to make the .tv domain
synonymous with ``rich'' media on the Web, singling out
organizations that will use video, audio and interactive features
on their sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there is this fundamental shift in the Internet from
static text to rich and engaging information that is much more
television-like,'' Francis said. ``We want the .tv domain to tell
people that this is what a site is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But achieving .com-like status for the new domain could still
prove a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Shirky, a partner at Accelerator Group, a consulting firm
that works with Web start-ups, says the company's plan is based on
the scarcity of commercially available domain names _ a scarcity
that he says is not going to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that most of the `good' .com names have been
taken,'' Shirky said. ``But the crash of the Internet market has
cooled people's desire to pay buckets of cash for an
easy-to-remember domain name.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to dotTV's hurdles, the Internet Corp. for Assigned Names
and Numbers, the international group charged with administering the
domain-name system, plans to release a set of new domains, which
might include suffixes like .web, .store and .sex, early next year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only clear winner is Tuvalu. With some of the money
it earned in the dotTV deal, it has financed the process to join
the United Nations. On Tuesday at the United Nations, the
organization will have a flag-raising ceremony for Tuvalu.
</P>
<P>
   Koloa Talake, chairman of the nation's public sector reform
program and a member of the board of dotTV, is quick to see a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's recognition of Tuvalu as an independent country
has been made possible by the relationship with dotTV,'' he said,
adding that the company was helping Tuvalu ``get into the 21st
century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0042 </DOCNO>
