<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BOTANISTS IRATE OVER CALIFORNIA STAMP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A 33-cent postage stamp to be unveiled on  &LR; Friday, commemorating
California's 150th anniversary, features a plant that some
botanists say is responsible for ruining the California coastline.
</P>
<P>
   The stamp's image is an  &UR; Art Wolfe  &LR; photograph of the rugged
Pacific coastline with plant-covered cliffs in the foreground. The
trouble, wrote botanist  &UR; Tony Morosco &LR; , vice president of the East
Bay Chapter of the California Native Plant Society, in a letter to
the postmaster, is that the plants pictured are  &LR; Carpobrotus
edulis &LR; , iceplant in common parlance.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is true that they produce very beautiful purple
flowers,'' said Morosco's letter, submitted to the postmaster two
weeks ago, ``this species is actively smothering native California
wildflowers while converting pristine coastal dune, cliff and
prairie habitats into desolate biological wastelands that our
native flora and fauna cannot survive in. It is now so widespread
and difficult to eradicate that it is understandable how it would
show up in the final round of images selected for this stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Morosco points out that the pictured plant came from Africa,
well after Europeans first came to California. The plant is
classified as an exotic pest plant. To use a stamp glorifying it
``does not celebrate the rich history of the state of California,''
he writes, ``but features one of its worst problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Morosco hasn't received an answer to his letter. The postal
service's  &UR; Susie Glover &LR;  told Personals that ``so far, most people
are thrilled'' by the new stamp. ``They like the iceplant.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A WOMAN'S LOT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Have the ladies who lunch become the ladies who want to write?
</P>
<P>
   Novelist  &UR; Lynn Freed &LR;  raised one figurative eyebrow at a Land's
End catalog description of ``neat microfiber trousers,'' picturing
the wearer: ``You're looking professional in the conference room,
while your mind keeps flashing to that novel you're writing on the
side''; and raised the other at a New Yorker ad picturing the
patient who's loving her anti-depression medication: ``Thanks to
breakthrough medicines discovered by America's pharmaceutical
companies, she's able to enjoy life again and has even fulfilled
her ambition to become a full-time writer.''
</P>
<P>
   - Hollywood madam  &UR; Heidi Fleiss &LR;  told the Los Angeles Times that
since getting out of prison last September, she has undergone
cosmetic surgery on her lips, ears, eyes and breasts. ``Being in
prison with no skin care really does a number on you,'' she said.
``You're out in that recreation yard with the sun beating down on
you. It really ages you prematurely.''
</P>
<P>
   - The New York Observer says the Gore girls ``look like they
were purchased at IKEA.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Shona Armstrong  &LR; wishes she knew where to buy a bumper
sticker she saw last week: ``Uppity Women Unite and Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals pulled down a ``Got
Prostate Cancer?'' billboard featuring New York Mayor
 &UR; Rudolph Giuliani &LR;  when the owner of a club in which the group had
scheduled a party said he found it offensive and threatened to
cancel the event. The group apologized to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Geraldo Rivera &LR; , who's thinking of running for mayor
of New York, told the New York Times, ``I expect the first reaction
to be, `Geraldo as mayor, ha ha.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And furthermore, learning that the New Yorker softball team beat
Talk magazine's,  &UR; Ed Moose  &LR; of San Francisco's Les Lapins Sauvages
_ who beat NBC and Sports Illustrated in historic victories _ is
challenging the Remnick crew to a match. Player eligibility is
apparently not geographic. Moose says he can get
 &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; , who was a star at Yale, to play first base; pal  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Brokaw &LR;  would ``probably'' be at second; and Wall Street financier
 &UR; Herbert Allen &LR;  would be in center field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `` `Lethal Weapon' is just a movie that sold a lot of popcorn.
It's not like we solved apartheid. I like Mel (Gibson), but let's
face it. I was subordinate to him. If the movie did so much for
blacks, then why am I still out there protesting the Confederate
flag in South Carolina, or blacks in prison?''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Danny Glover &LR; , who George magazine says has risked his career
to fight racism in Hollywood. Glover also said that ``neither Bush
nor Gore appeals to me,'' and he is supporting
 &UR; Ralph Nader &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
