<HEADLINE>
WILLOW BAY MOVES WEST TO CO-ANCHOR `MONEYLINE'  
 SEPARATING `HAVE ITS' FROM `HAVE IT NOTS'
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With CNN in flux after a corporate restructuring that was
announced last week, Willow Bay, an anchor on its ``Moneyline News
Hour'' program, will begin doing her job from Los Angeles Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Her co-anchor, Stuart Varney, will remain in New York, making
the 6:30 p.m., EDT, financial news program bicoastal. The program
will also include a ticker and new graphics.
</P>
<P>
   When CNN executives announced last winter that Bay would move to
Los Angeles, they said it would serve two purposes: It would give
``Moneyline'' a presence on the West Coast while also allowing Bay
to live some semblance of a normal life with her husband, Robert A.
Iger, the president of Walt Disney, who had been asked to move from
New York to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bay, who did not want a bicoastal marriage, told CNN that she
would likely have to leave ``Moneyline'' for some other duty. They
said they would rather make the show bicoastal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moneyline'' had been steadily losing ratings to its CNBC
competitor, ``Business Center,'' in the months after its longtime
anchor, Lou Dobbs, left the network. It has never recovered and has
become somewhat of a symbol of the ratings failures at CNN, which
is owned by Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The executives believed that by creating a Los Angeles anchor,
they could rejuvenate the program. C. Shelby Coffey III, the
president of CNN's financial network, CNNfn, who is in charge of
``Moneyline,'' had wanted to bolster coverage of the West Coast
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, executives were planning to build up attention for
the program's new format. But then the president of CNN's
operations in the United States, Richard N. Kaplan, resigned,
sending those plans into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, like Bay, was formerly of ABC News. Bay, like others who
were close to Kaplan, acknowledged some uneasiness now that he was
gone. ``With Rick's departure, we lose a `Moneyline' supporter, and
I'm obviously personally very distressed that he's leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been specifically assured that the current CNN
management fully supports and embraces a bicoastal `Moneyline,'''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, she added, ``CNN management has been very generous
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, while CNN executives have said they could make a lot
of changes to the programming schedule, ``Moneyline'' is still a
major moneymaker and has lost fewer viewers than other programs.
</P>
<P>
   But there will certainly be pressure for it to do better in the
ratings. Bay and Varney said they believed the changes should help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being out there on the West Coast, in the middle of the new
economy, I think that's a plus,'' Varney said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEPARATING `HAVE ITS' FROM `HAVE IT NOTS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So just how do you get to be an ``It girl?''
</P>
<P>
   ``By having `It' bigger and better and more fabulously than
others,'' said Kristina Stewart, the society editor for Vanity
Fair, which features ``The `It' Parade'' as the cover article of
its September issue. And if you generate a little controversy, too,
well then so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said she began choosing women with ``It'' some months
ago, when she ``dumped a big stack of contender photos'' on the
desk of the editor of Vanity Fair, Graydon Carter. They and several
other editors then ``dished for the better part of an afternoon,''
she said, before choosing 14 women who ``dance on the tables'' and
``change the chemistry of a room just by entering it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them: the cover subject Gwyneth Paltrow (the ``uber `It'
Girl,'' according to Stewart), scions of wealthy and well-known
families, including Patricia Herrera, daughter of the fashion
designer Carolina Herrera, and self-made ``Its,'' like Cecilia
Dean, a magazine editor who also teaches at the Parsons School of
Design (``Who needs money when every designer wants to dress you?''
the magazine asks.)
</P>
<P>
   Was Vanity Fair besieged by public relations representatives?
No, said Stewart, who noted that ``It'' women are so in demand that
they use public relations people to decline invitations, not get
them. ``The girls we chose all had to be arm-wrestled into being in
the feature,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be. But Vanity Fair has received some criticism.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, an article by Gabriel Snyder in The New York
Observer noted that the magazine's seekers of ``It'' hadn't had to
go very far _ or even to leave their building _ in their search for
Herrera, who works for the magazine, or in finding Plum Sykes, a
``bon vivant'' who works for Vogue, a sister publication of Advance
Publications' Conde Nast unit. Sykes' table-top dancing was said to
have recently resulted in the destruction of 350 champagne glasses
at a Manhattan restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder never actually uttered the word nepotism, though he
implied it. And he quoted Aimee Bell, Vanity Fair's senior articles
editor, who said the omission of Herrera and Sykes would have been
a ``disservice'' to the ``scholars of `It-girldom.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Entertainment Weekly's managing editor, James W. Seymore
Jr., was not so diplomatic. In a letter sent to Carter, he said
Vanity Fair had engaged in ``imitation'' and ``misappropriation''
in publishing its story, which he said was ``very, very similar''
to an ``It List'' cover that Entertainment Weekly runs annually
about ``the 100 most creative people in entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Seymore's letter was reported in The New York Post, which
printed much of it verbatim. Stewart called it a ``thinly-veiled
publicity stunt,'' and noted that The Vanity Fair article was
nothing like the one in Seymore's magazine, which focuses on people
who are prominent in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feature didn't even mention Hollywood,'' she said. ``It
concerned itself only with society.''
</P>
<P>
   Seymore was out of town last week, and Sandy Drayton, an
Entertainment Weekly spokeswoman, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim's letter stands on its own,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
