<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Sept. 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday will be the last day of dull, sticky weather on the
Northeast coast. A strengthening cold front will push across New
England and upstate New York with a few thundershowers. Much cooler
air will surge into the region on brisk winds from the north Monday
night. Tuesday will bring more autumnal conditions in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will continue in the Southeast as
sultry air remains across the region. The heat wave in the southern
Plains and lower Mississippi Valley will be unabated with more
record high temperatures expected from Texas to Kansas and east to
Mississippi. A few rain storms will bring temporary relief from the
heat to Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Very cool air will hover over the Great Lakes. Thundershowers
will erupt as hot air returns to the western Dakotas. Much of the
West will be cooler with patches of showers in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: ALASKAN CHILL
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Fairbanks have lost their opportunity for a final
fling of summer weather. The tally from August indicates that
Fairbanks had its lowest day temperatures since records began in
1905. The average daytime maximum did not reach 60 degrees for the
first time. However, night readings were closer to seasonal levels
so that the month concluded as the fifth chilliest August on
record. Much of the unusually cool air can be attributed to an
abundance of daytime clouds. Only four days had sunny skies last
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
