<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OLY-IBM-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      09-03 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IBM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLED IN ATLANTA, IBM ENTERS ITS FINAL OLYMPIC GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the computer system IBM built to report results at the 1996
Summer Olympics in Atlanta malfunctioned, the proud computing giant
learned the hard way what it was like to stumble with the whole
world watching.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Summer Olympics set to begin this month in Sydney,
Australia, and IBM's 40-year run as a technology supplier for the
Olympics set to end in December, Big Blue is pushing hard to make
sure it brings home some public relations gold.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which decided two years ago to end its involvement in the
Games, intends to use television and the Internet to widely
advertise its role as the 2000 Olympics' chief provider and
integrator of information technology. The centerpiece of the
campaign will be the official Olympic Games site it has set up to
handle a projected 6 billion user visits during the games, 10 times
the traffic during the 1998 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is also setting up Internet stations called Surf Shacks in
Sydney. Athletes in the Olympic Village will be able to go online
with more than 60 IBM personal computers; the public's Surf Shack,
on a barge docked in Sydney's harbor, will also show off IBM's
voice-recognition technology.
</P>
<P>
   The most crucial audience, though, may be the 1,000 or so major
customers IBM will entertain in Sydney. The visitors, including
executives from telecommunications, transportation, finance, health
care and computer services companies, will be shown the full range
of IBM's Olympics products and services at an executive briefing
center. The hoped-for payoff is the chance to discuss problems in
their businesses that IBM might solve for them. ``It's very
strategic marketing,'' said Elizabeth Primrose-Smith, the IBM vice
president in charge of sports sponsorships. ``We've found it's very
helpful for them to see us in action.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology challenge in Sydney is akin to creating a huge,
transitory multinational business almost from scratch under the
pressure of immovable deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials said that the Sydney Olympic Committee would
spend more than $100 million on information technology and
communications and receive donated goods and services from IBM and
others worth several times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to building the official Web site and systems that
handle scoring, link results to background data about the athletes
and the events, and distribute results, IBM is involved in such
diverse activities as accreditation, accommodations and management
of the athletes' medical records.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is not doing all the work itself. The accreditation system,
for example, has been subcontracted to the Sema Group, a
British-French technology services company. But IBM is the overall
systems integrator, and its Tivoli products will manage the entire
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The company has deployed about 850 computer technicians, who,
among other things, have written 12.4 million lines of code, and
who weeded out 4,000 bugs in the first six months of the year.
On-site equipment testing began last September.
</P>
<P>
   The work is winning praise from some technology managers who had
a front-row seat on the Atlanta problems. ``It's my impression
they've got everything right this time,'' said Klaus Sprick, vice
president for technology at Deutsche Press-Agentur, a German news
agency that found IBM's data feeds ``totally unreliable'' in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Atlanta humiliation was magnified because the system that
failed was the one delivering scores, times and other results to
the news media, so the problem was widely reported. The news
agencies and newspapers that had paid for the data service were
furious. Ridicule was heaped atop the anger when reports spread
that some information passed along included nonsense like tied
final scores in basketball and boxers listed as 2 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Though IBM's corporate pride suffered, the company's quarterly
earnings, issued during the Games, beat expectations and IBM's
shares jumped.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said its market researchers found that potential customers
did not seem put off, either.
</P>
<P>
   Both IBM and the International Olympic Committee say that the
problems in Atlanta had nothing to do with IBM's decision to end
its association after the Sydney games. IBM had been an Olympic
sponsor and technology supplier since 1960, but its role had
steadily expanded since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, when it came time to negotiate life after Sydney, IBM
was basking in praise for its successful role in the 1998 Winter
Games in Nagano, Japan, and wondering how much longer it wanted to
spend ever-increasing amounts on the Games. Though IBM issues no
accounting of its Olympics spending, analysts estimated that it
invested about $100 million in Nagano. Because the Summer Games are
bigger, it was certain to end up with much higher expenses for
Sydney _ perhaps double, the analysts said. If it was to continue,
it wanted more cash from the local organizing committees to offset
the costs.
</P>
<P>
   But the IOC felt that putting so much of the technology in IBM's
hands was leading to needlessly expensive technical solutions. It
also wanted to handle sponsorship of Internet-related products and
services separately from the rest of information technology so that
it could raise more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them the Internet isn't available exclusively at any
price,'' said Michael R. Payne, the committee's marketing director,
adding that the two sides disagreed over whether the Internet was a
medium or a product category that should be covered by the
information technology contract. ``We would love to have IBM
involved in some aspects as part of a consortium, as in Barcelona''
in 1992, he added, ``but they're saying that's not in their
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The man on the spot in Sydney is Thomas E. Furey, who has worked
at IBM for 37 years and who got his first Olympics challenge soon
after Atlanta when he was assigned to investigate why things had
gone so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One problem was that the Atlanta Operating Committee's
technology staff had run the project, making it hard for IBM and
other technology vendors to deal directly with the sports
organizations and other end users. It did not help that IBM's own
services group, which did much of the project management work for
the Atlanta committee, was at the time independent from the rest of
IBM, Furey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Games also came as the industry was moving from mainframe to
PC-based computing and lacked many of the tools, like Tivoli, that
were later developed to manage distributed computing systems where
processing jobs are spread over many smaller computers supported by
larger servers.
</P>
<P>
   Given the job of overseeing Nagano and then Sydney, Furey
insisted that IBM get more control over the deployment of
technology and more time for testing. ``We also lowered the
threshold of risk,'' he said. ``We didn't use any bleeding-edge
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trumpeting new products, IBM marketers are
emphasizing that many of the Internet applications being deployed
at Sydney are already being used by customers in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   After IBM announced its withdrawal from Olympic sponsorship, the
IOC signed up Sema to take on, through 2008, the bulk of the
software and systems work IBM is doing in Sydney. Gateway will
replace IBM as hardware vendor for the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the work for the 2004 Summer Games in Athens will not be
parceled out until after an IOC meeting in December, Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we read and hear about the IOC's future
direction, our role probably will prove unique,'' Craig A. Lowder,
an IBM spokesman, said. ``No single company has ever been
responsible for as much technology as we have at Sydney, and it
doesn't look like any one will be again soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
