<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-BIG-BROTHER-1STLD-     09-03 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BIG-BROTHER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WON'T ANYONE QUIT? `BIG BROTHER' HAS PLANS FOR A NEW FACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (Eds: SUBS to add that Petros' hair has also been purple and adds
Jordan's full name.) 
By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to ignite viewer interest in ``Big Brother,'' the CBS
reality television show whose ratings have paled in comparison with
those of CBS's summer runaway hit, ``Survivor,'' the producers plan
to pay one of the six remaining contestants $10,000 to quit this
week, allowing the show to introduce a fresh face.
</P>
<P>
   The producers hope that the new entrant into the camera-filled
house, where the contestants have been confined for eight weeks,
will be dynamic enough to instill some dramatic tension into the
occupants' personal relationships. Dramatic tension is an element
the producers _ and apparently most viewers _ have found
distressingly absent from ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least from the American ``Big Brother.'' Unlike the
contestants in versions of the show in other parts of the world,
the American participants are overly aware that they are on
television, the producers said. Also, American viewers seem
unwilling to accept contestants who stray from mainstream values or
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely frustrating and confounding,'' said Douglas
Ross, one of the show's executive producers. ``Will and Jordan and
Karen and Brittany have given us some great television.'' But they
are the four contestants the audience decided to eliminate. (The
house's members nominate two potential losers for the audience to
vote on in elections held every other week.)
</P>
<P>
   Left with six contestants who the producers say seem to be doing
everything possible to appear inoffensive, the show's creators have
decided to ``introduce a new impulse,'' said Paul Romer, the
producer from the Dutch company Endemol, which developed ``Big
Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Wednesday night the contestants will be presented with a
briefcase filled with $10,000 and given two minutes to decide
whether one of them will take the money and run. (The ultimate
winner of the game will receive $500,000.) What they will not know
is that if a contestant does leave, Beth, a 22-year-old from
Florida and a former alternate for ``Big Brother,'' will enter the
house as a replacement. (The producers revealed no other personal
details about Beth, other than Ross' observation that she was
``very attractive.'')
</P>
<P>
   This move has always been an option because the rules allow
anyone voluntarily exiting the game to be replaced. The producers
are resorting to the strategy, which CBS agreed to after some
initial reluctance, to stir up some conflict in a group in which
seldom is heard a discouraging word. Although the producers say
they are confident that someone will take the $10,000, if no one
volunteers _ or if the contestants cannot decide among themselves _
they will withdraw the money and probably offer it again later.
</P>
<P>
   In another departure from the European versions of ``Big
Brother,'' no one here has volunteered to quit. ``It's something in
the American mentality,'' Romer said. ``You don't want to be seen
as a quitter.''
</P>
<P>
   That mentality seems to have affected ``Big Brother'' in other
ways, too, beginning with the extreme media awareness of the U.S.
contestants. ``In the American house, our contestants never forget
they're on camera,'' Romer said. ``In Europe they stopped thinking
of the cameras very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The American group, Ross added, ``are all trying to produce
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The American show also has much less sexual tension than the
other versions. ``Europeans have seen people hooking up in the
house,'' Romer said. ``Americans are a little more prudish. Nudity
is a bigger issue here.'' Indeed, in the German version one female
contestant courted popularity by flashing her breasts on camera
``every 10 minutes,'' Romer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a bit of a problem on CBS,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing has stunned the producers more than the vote last
week to dump Brittany Petros, a 25-year-old pharmaceutical
saleswoman from Minneapolis, distinguished on the show by her
avowed virginity and her hair's changing colors (including purple
and green). She had previously won an online contest as the most
popular occupant of the house, but in the recent audience telephone
election to dismiss someone, she easily received the most votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very surprised,'' Romer said. ``But maybe the audience
felt she was too out of the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly seems to be what Petros believes. ``It's got to
be the older people who didn't like the chick with green hair on TV
maybe becoming a role model,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' thrived largely because its most overtly scheming
character, Richard Hatch, took control of the game; but the
audience, which loved to hate Richard, never had a chance to vote
him off the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Richard would have been voted out of the house the
first week on our show,'' Romer said.
</P>
<P>
   And that is clearly a large part of the problem with ``Big
Brother.'' American television viewers may love their villains, but
if you ask them to vote, they will choose more with their hearts
than with their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a traditional scripted show, audiences get hooked on the
villain,'' said Ross, whose production company, Evolution, has
created many other reality shows for American television. ``In
reality television, people start to think of the people on the show
as their friends, and so they seek to protect their friends from
the villain.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer said that in all the ``Big Brother'' versions, anyone
exhibiting ``antisocial behavior'' was quickly dispatched by the
viewers. But in the American version the threat of expulsion seems
to hang over anyone who appears the least nonconformist.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the producers should not have been surprised. Tom Smith,
the director of the General Social Survey for the National Opinion
Research Center at the University of Chicago, said that the
audience preference for inoffensive personalities on ``Big
Brother'' is little different from the conflict-avoidance
exemplified by American politics.
</P>
<P>
   It is the reason, Smith said, that ``we have two political
parties that run to the middle, with both trying to outdo the other
in looking more moderate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We penalize parties and people who are extreme,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bland politicians and, apparently, bland contestants on reality
shows like ``Big Brother'' are the results.
</P>
<P>
   Petros said that she suspected that her expression of strong
opinions had inspired as many people to dislike her as to like her.
``Some of the others are just kind of `there,''' she said. ``How
can you dislike someone who's just kind of `there?'''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Big Brother'' producers were concerned enough about the
lack of a strong personality to propose a radical way to fill the
opening that might be created by one contestant walking away with
the $10,000. They were going to bring back Jean Jordan, known only
as Jordan on the show, the student and former part-time exotic
dancer who was kicked off more than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   After some negotiation about the terms of her reassignment, the
deal fell through.
</P>
<P>
   If Beth from Florida moves into the house, she will have her
work cut out for her. She has not been watching the show because
she was so disappointed over not being one of the original choices.
And she can probably expect a less than warm welcome. In Europe,
every time a new contestant entered the game, he or she was
immediately singled out for expulsion by the disgruntled holdover
cast members. No replacement contestant has ever won the game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the producers believe this move is worth a try. ``We want
to give the show more energy,'' Romer said.
</P>
<P>
   And if this doesn't work, ``we have more ideas to stir things
up,'' he added. ``I'm sure things will start to happen. In the last
two or three weeks the prospect of winning the money is there. A
lot of scheming will go on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
