<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-JIMMY-JOHNSON0904-1ST     09-03 1624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIMMY-JOHNSON0904-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Fix in subhead.
 &HT;    Easy living for former Dolphins coach, Jimmy Johnson
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMORADA, Fla. _ He wasn't bluffing. Jimmy Johnson pledged to
disappear. He held a news conference that was carried live on ESPN
and began by telling the sports world that he was done coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' he said, ``it's final and forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, he waved goodbye, hopped in his black
Corvette and came here, a town in the Keys that says goodbye to
visitors with a sign that says, ``Catch you later!''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but eight months later, he hasn't let anybody catch him.
At least not anybody outside his close circle of friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   He used to live between goal lines. Now, at age 57, he lives
between mile markers. MM 85 and MM 90, to be exact. This is his end
zone. Other than to head off into the ocean, he has left this
little stretch of land only five times since January. To help the
Dolphins with the NFL Draft. To meet with ABC. To pick up his
father at Miami International Airport. To attend the wedding of
Stuart Weinstein, the team's security investigator. To be on hand
for a party for Nick Christin, his agent.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour into Christin's party, he plopped into a chair,
explaining that his feet hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had shoes on in a month,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He could be coaching the Dolphins. He could be in the Monday
Night Football booth or in the CBS studio. Instead, he is doing
exactly what he said he would _ fishing, snorkeling, checking his
investments on the Internet and, most of all, spending time with
the loved ones that, by his own admission, he often forgot about
while he was coaching football.
</P>
<P>
   He has turned down dozens of interview requests, including one
for this story. ``He hasn't talked to anybody,'' Christin said.
``And I don't think that's going to change in the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   He also hasn't made public appearances, unless you count the
footage of him shown at Pro Player Stadium during Dan Marino's
farewell tribute.
</P>
<P>
   His face was only there for a split second, just long enough to
show him tossing a game ball across the locker room to Marino. Yet,
that was all it took.
</P>
<P>
   The 52,000 fans filled the place with the kind of boos normally
reserved for the Jets or Bills. And even when the video moved on to
something else and the boos faded, some fans began a chant.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.J. sucks! J.J. sucks!''
</P>
<P>
   THE GUY WHO COULD MAKE IT HAPPEN
</P>
<P>
   Giddy. That was the word people used to describe the feeling on
Jan. 11, 1996, the day that Johnson took the Dolphins job.
</P>
<P>
   Every time an NFL team hires a new coach there is optimism. But
this was different. The headlines trumpeted, ``J.J.'s back.'' No
full name necessary. He had led the University of Miami to a
national title. He had worked miracles in Dallas. He would do the
same with the Dolphins. Nobody seemed to doubt this, least of all
the coach himself.
</P>
<P>
   The fans were giddy. The players were giddy. Even the owner was
giddy. Wayne Huizenga held up a doctored photo that had Johnson's
famous hair replaced with a shiny bald crown, just like his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the guy,'' Huizenga had said, ``who's going to make it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson made a lot happen, all right. He made South Florida
buzz. He created seemingly a controversy-a-week. He put the
Dolphins back in the playoffs. Three times in four years. But, in
the end, he didn't make IT happen. He didn't take the Dolphins to
the Super Bowl as promised. They lost in the second round each of
his last two years _ by 35 points at Denver and 55 at Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was saga of Jimmy and Danny, South
Florida's favorite soap opera until Elian Gonzalez came ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together _ the breathless expectations, the somber
finishes and the friction with Marino _ and you have a massive
backlash. Bring up Johnson's name on talk radio and listen to the
venom. Put his face on a big screen and hear the boos. Mention his
initials to a couple eyeing the menu at Jimmy Johnson's Bar &AMP; Grill
in Miami Beach and they go into a Dennis Miller rant. And not
because J.J.'s Classic Margarita goes for $8.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he's off in the Keys, doing whatever he's doing,''
said Lisa Mason, 32. ``He should've gone there sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say it's hard to find Johnson supporters north of
Key Largo. Just stop by his former place of employment and ask what
people there think of the boos. Watch Dave Wannstedt's face tighten
with anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a joke,'' said Wannstedt, Johnson's successor and
longtime friend. ``That's ridiculous. . . . For people to react
that way, it makes no sense. It's almost so ridiculous that it's
not worth commenting on. That's how I feel. Anybody who has any
intelligence about this sport and understands how tough it is to
win, would understand my sentiments.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jones, Dolphins president, borrows the words Marino used
when the fans booed Huizenga: ``That's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Trace Armstrong, the defensive end who as union leader
occasionally clashed with Johnson, is quick to defend his former
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of silly,'' he said. ``A lot of times, he
can be an easy target because he does go out on a limb.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Armstrong points out, there aren't very many storybook
finishes in the NFL. John Elway, he says, spoiled it for everyone
else. Made everyone dream about going out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL isn't about Cinderella stories,'' Armstrong said.
``There aren't too many happy endings.''
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL HERO
</P>
<P>
   It's shortly after noon on Tuesday, five days before the first
NFL games of the season, at a bar that claims to have the oldest
liquor license in the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie White, a bartender at Harrah and Dunn's Oceanview Inn and
Sports Pub, is testing out a new contest that will make its debut
Sunday. She is holding up a toilet seat in front of the big-screen
TV. The handful of locals who are sitting at the bar are taking
turns trying to throw a Nerf football through the seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to call it Dan's Can,'' she says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She points at the insignia on her shirt _ New England Patriots _
and insists that she has nothing against Marino. Still, if you're
looking for a place where they still love J.J., where it still
feels a little like the summer of '96, then this is it. The Keys.
The land of many marinas but no Marinos.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the Oceanview. It used to be a biker bar, a place
notorious for bloody fights. For the last five years, though, it
has been owned by a couple of former University of Miami players
and roommates.
</P>
<P>
   The bar menu includes ``Jimmy Johnson's Famous Fish Sandwich.''
And in one corner of the room, right below Dennis Harrah's Rams
jersey and a picture of Gary Dunn and the '79 Steelers, there is a
photo of Three Rings, the boat that, to South Florida's dismay,
never required a name change.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen people are on board. Right in the middle sits Johnson,
wearing a floral shirt, holding his dog Buttercup on his lap and
grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy isn't in the Oceanview on this day. But he and his wife,
Rhonda, have stopped in. They came in a couple days after the
retirement announcement. Played some games. Had a couple of beers.
Everybody pretty much left them alone. But as Johnson got ready to
leave, the guy everyone calls Kooc couldn't resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't you . . . ,'' he said, as if trying to place the face,
`` . . . Dan Marino.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson smiled and said, ``No, he's taller.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kooc is seated at a corner of the bar, sipping a draft
beer. He explains that his real name is Richard Hoffert. ``I'm the
cook,'' he says. ``So they call me Kooc _ like cook backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   He gives Johnson the ultimate compliment. Calls him a local, a
Conch. A rich Conch, but a Conch nonetheless. The man seated next
to Kooc _ he will only say everyone calls him ``Buck'' _ chimes in
with his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan should've retired earlier,'' he says. ``I thought Jimmy
did a good job. They give Dan that thing at the stadium and they
boo Jimmy? Down here, everyone treats him like a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's home is located within walking distance of everything
Buttercup could ever need _ Pet Stuff, Pet Groomer and the Upper
Keys Animal Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Johnson is a homebody. He occasionally is
seen at Woody's, the Old Tavernier Restaurant or Whale Harbor. And
he stops by Smuggler's Cove Marina about once a week. That's where
he fills up his boat's gas tank and gets a bite to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he'll buy everyone a drink,'' Buck says. ``Well, the
locals at least.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, he doesn't like to call attention to
himself. He likes to blend in, which can be tough considering some
of the people he has taken out on his boat in the last nine months
_ Wannstedt, Redskins coach Norv Turner and, surprise, former rival
Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The locals rarely talk football with him. Usually the
conversation sticks to safe topics. Like how the fish are biting.
But every so often, someone will toss out the bait _ a question
about Marino _ and wait for Johnson to lunge at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never does,'' said one Smuggler's Cove employee. ``He only
has nice things to say about Dan. And he really likes Huizenga. . .
. He seems to want to enjoy his life now. He seems very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what everyone who has seen him in in the last nine months
says. From afar, this might not look like a happy ending. Up close,
they insist, Johnson is happier than ever. No matter what people up
in Miami are doing when they see his face on a giant screen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
