   NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.04.00
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska-San Jose big hit on the Web
</P>
<P>
   Paterno top draw on coaching site
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for MNF ... and more online
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME ONLINE: All stories and urls on this page are one
click away on ajc.com/enews
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE TRY: It was far from perfect, but a free Webcast's
choppy video, lost-then-heard-again audio and system crashes did
little to stem passions of thousands of football fans who hit the
Internet on Saturday to watch the Nebraska-San Jose State game.
Danny Greenberg, senior vice president at FoxSports.com, said he
was pleased overall and hoped the Webcast was the first of many.
Fox expected about 100,000 fans to watch, but said it would not
have exact numbers for a day or two. Replays of the game are
available at the site.
</P>
<P>
   www.foxsports.com
</P>
<P>
   JOE PA ONLINE: His team may be 0-2, but Penn State coach Joe
Paterno still is regarded as one of college football's best
coaches. That's why a Web site dedicated to helping other coaches
become better professionals carries his name. CoachPaterno.com has
plays, clinics, drills, officiating news, motivational speeches and
other resources from more than 20 college coaches, including
Georgia's Jim Donnan. There is free content; a membership to
receive exclusive content costs $22 a year.
</P>
<P>
   www.coachpaterno.com
</P>
<P>
   MNF PLUS: If a game between the past two Super Bowl champions
isn't enough to make you want to watch Monday Night Football,
there's Dennis Miller in the booth. Or, there's Walt Disney
Internet Group's enhanced coverage of the Broncos-Rams game at 9
tonight from St. Louis. Interactive games, real-time statistics,
enhanced graphics, freeze frames, polls and trivia will be
accessible via several Go Network sites _ ESPN.com,
Mondaynightfootball.com, ABCSports.com, ABC.com, ABCNews.com and
NFL.com.
</P>
