<SLUG> BC-DANCE-FEST-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPTEMBER FESTIVAL AT WORLD TRADE CENTER PLAZA PRIMES ECLECTIC MIX
OF DANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The term ``downtown dance'' takes on a whole new
meaning with the ``Evening Stars'' dance week that opens on Sunday
in an outdoor theater at the World Trade Center Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   True, the kind of avant-garde dance that is usually meant by the
term, created in lofts and studios south of 14th Street, will be
represented in the new series. But the six ``Evening Stars''
programs include an impressive variety of uptown stars and styles.
</P>
<P>
   That is not surprising, given that the project is the brainchild
of Liz Thompson, executive director of the Lower Manhattan Cultural
Council, the producer of the festival. Thompson has had a long
relationship with dance at its most glittering and most funky, from
early days as a performer of the now-defunct New York Dance
Festival in Central Park, to the directorship of the Jacob's Pillow
Dance Festival from 1979 to 1989. The Pillow was founded by Ted
Shawn, who championed eclectic dance programming. And at the
Central Park festival, held in the Delacorte Theater, one could
often see ballet, modern and ethnic dance all on the same night.
</P>
<P>
   The Lower Manhattan Cultural Council, a service organization for
artists and a presenter of dance and visual arts in downtown
Manhattan for 25 years, has maintained a grass-roots approach while
changing with the neighborhood it was formed to serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were running away from downtown when LMCC was founded
by David Rockefeller and the Chase Bank,'' Thompson said in a
recent interview. ``The new downtown renaissance has allowed a
festival of this magnitude to come into being.''
</P>
<P>
   The council has traditionally provided artists with technical,
company redevelopment and grant-writing assistance and
full-production stagings. It provides work space to resident
artists, among them the dance duo Eiko and Koma, in raw space on
the 91st floor of Building 1 at the World Trade Center, where there
will be an open house on Sept. 23 and Sept. 24. Today the council
also sponsors a digital media showcase program called Thundergulch.
And with the ``Evening Stars'' week, it is moving into dance
production in a bigger and more wide-ranging way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evening Stars'' opens with the companies of Ronald Brown and
Rennie Harris, two young modern-dance choreographers. In the
dizzyingly varied ``Jazz Riffs'' on Sept. 11, tap will be
represented by the Silver Belles, a company of veteran female
dancers, and the stylish Young Hoofers. There will also be Broadway
jazz dance by Bob Fosse performed by ``A Few Good Men Dancin',''
and the avant-garde Jane Comfort and her company will perform
hip-hop-inspired work.
</P>
<P>
   The company of the downtown-dance pioneer Trisha Brown performs
on Sept. 13 in a program that includes a sneak preview of a new
work with a jazz score by Dave Douglas that will be performed live.
Ballet will be represented by the vibrant and adventurous American
Repertory Ballet of New Brunswick, N.J., on Sept. 14; the Parsons
Dance Co. presents a modern dance work on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The festival closes the Sept. 16 with ``... And Rising Stars,''
a hyper-eclectic mix of ballet and new modern dance works. The
performers include Gillian Murphy and Marcelo Gomes of American
Ballet Theater; dancers from the San Francisco Ballet; the
modern-dance troupes of Ellis Wood; the rollicking Irish-flavored
Sean Curran Co.; and RhythMEK, a new group of former Alvin Ailey
principals, who will dance in a new work by Donald Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   The criterion for the show was ``just good and interesting
work,'' Thompson said. ``I think we have to establish ourselves and
a body of work so that we can introduce more and more adventurous
dance, gently, over time. Trisha is world-renowned now but
considered avant-garde. American Repertory Ballet is a regional
company that has gone through some changes. It will be interesting
to see them in New York. David Parsons is a crowd pleaser. We open
with a dynamic double-header. And `Jazz Riffs' and `Rising Stars'
explore different aspects of dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Evening Stars'' festival was created last year when the
Port Authority, which owns the World Trade Center, was looking for
a way to make use of the plaza while it was being refurbished.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of vision at the Port Authority saw this as an
opportunity to bring world-class artists here and they got excited
about that,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   This year the festival presented three weeks of music, theater
and dance in June but added the new all-dance week for September.
</P>
<P>
   A special stage has been erected, facing out from Church Street
and framed by soaring skyscrapers. Next year Thompson said she
hopes to expand dance festival to three weeks and to offer open
daytime rehearsals that can be watched by passers-by and those
grabbing a lunchtime sandwich on the plaza.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I've tried to build new audiences wherever I've gone,''
Thompson said. ``This is a realization of a dream. The plaza is one
of the most democratic places. It's a clean, fresh space for dance
that attracts so many people: 45,000 people work in the Trade
Center buildings. Thousands pass through daily. Tourists, people
going out for lunch, people on their way to the PATH trains. Some
are CEOs, some do back-office work.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson envisions her audiences experiencing everything from
chance encounters to planned and affordable outings for families.
And if all goes as planned, some who are new to dance will fall in
love with the art and follow the companies as they perform at
uptown theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different people find beauty and meaning in a vast array of
forms,'' Thompson said. ``Now it is my passion and pleasure to try
to open paths for people to see with new eyes what they may not
necessarily have grown up with or be accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful way for a diverse audience to see a very
diverse program,'' she added. ``Just pray it doesn't rain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
