<HEADLINE>
TWO ARTISTS, SHARING A MUSEUM BUT WORLDVIEWS APART 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note language in 3rd-last graf.) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hardly a surprise to be told that every good
artist creates a world of her or his own. But to move from the
world of Alice Neel to that of Barbara Kruger (separated by a
single floor at the Whitney Museum of American Art) is to feel you
have moved from one species to another, from people who claim their
individuality as a natural right to people who see the world as one
big central casting agency in which everyone, not least themselves,
is a desirable or an undesirable type.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it's a question of temperament. Neel was a humanist
who treated her subjects with clinical compassion. Kruger is a
critic and muckraker who treats hers with satirical fury. But
history separates these artists every bit as much as temperament.
Neel was born in 1900. She came of age when the particulars of
neighborhood, region, faces and bodies, however unlovely, dominated
the culture's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many artists during the Depression, Neel worked for the
Federal Arts Project, painting all the neighborhoods of New York
City. But her love of portraiture and place had begun in the 1920s,
when she was living la vie de boheme in Greenwich Village, and it
continued through her years in Spanish Harlem and midtown
Manhattan. (It seems she never met a visual abstraction she much
liked.)
</P>
<P>
   Kruger was born midcentury, in 1945. The mass media were already
revved up in the 1920s, but baby boomers grew up during their
imperial expansion years when everything from newspapers to
televisions to computers made their way into every home and
sometimes every room of every home.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasies of advertising, movies and television belong as
much to our unconscious as do those Greek tragedies and German
fairy tales that psychoanalysts dissected in such detail. (Or as an
analyst friend of mine once said about someone: ``I get it. His
inner life is based on Tom and Jerry.'')
</P>
<P>
   Neel, who died in 1984, was a purist about her medium, devoted
to painting and painting only. Kruger is an insistent hybrid: She
reworks old (but rarely pre-1940s) and contemporary photographs
that she finds in all kinds of places _ business, movie and fashion
magazines, how-to books and manuals _ and then joins them to
uncluttered (even stark) graphic design.
</P>
<P>
   Every picture has its verbal element. And words come at you; she
covers floors and walls with them. They shout, they sneer, they
challenge. (``If you're so successful, why do you feel like a
fake?'')
</P>
<P>
   They insist on their power and righteousness, be it social,
religious, ethnic or sexual. ``What I love is more compelling than
what you love. More profound, more riveting, sexier. My taste is
more developed than yours. Hipper, more knowing, more evolved.''
And: ``God said it. I believe it. And that settles it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything is fortissimo. The images are just as strong but more
layered and fractured; her reworkings move everyday photographs
toward the gothic.
</P>
<P>
   See a middle-aged white man with strangely crumpled skin and one
eye at the bottom of his forehead. Look at the black rectangle on
his chin and read the words ``Look like us'' in white type. A large
pair of scissors lies partly open. They look black and cast a
gray-black shadow on the white surface. Between the blades is a red
box with the question ``Who speaks?'' in white type. Beneath the
handle is an identical box with the words ``Who is silent?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to get back to the human,'' I heard a woman say as
we entered Neel's exhibition space. That was no indictment of
Kruger but rather a stricken acknowledgment of the artist's power.
``Back to the human'': Neel lets us go back and see ourselves as
people who have life outside ruthless cultural and political
scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Look at her aged mother in ``Last Sickness'': the scared eyes
and the mouth pressed into a tight little line; the messy hair and
the dowdy bathrobe. It's that awful thing you see in the dying: the
physical letting go and the emotional holding on.
</P>
<P>
   The young man from Spanish Harlem in ``Call Me Joe'' is a beauty
with his pompadour and elegant long-sleeved white T-shirt beneath a
short-sleeved print shirt? Why is he so melancholy? What does he
know about his future that we don't?
</P>
<P>
   And did Henry Geldhazer, the curator of 20th-century art at the
Metropolitan Museum when Neel painted him, really want to be seen
with that chilly, rather petulant expression, trying so hard to
look languid and at ease? (Did he see that portrait before he left
Neel out of the show he was then organizing, ``New York Painting
and Sculpture: 1940-1970''?)
</P>
<P>
   Portraiture invites people to honor what sets _ or at least
appears to set _ one person apart from others. This must be why it
has become so popular again among those wealthy enough to
commission portraits of themselves and their families for
posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Work like Kruger's insists that we see ourselves in the grip of
generic thoughts, gestures and words; always on the verge of
turning into media objects or receptors.
</P>
<P>
   That both these artists did portraits of Andy Warhol says
everything about the cultural shifts that they _ and we _ have
lived through. Warhol was the white-faced, white-blond wizard of
metamorphosis, turning fine art into mass art, high culture into
pop culture. That one-of-a-kind painting became the endlessly
reproducible photograph and print; introspection became
advertising; and the individual as psychological subject became an
icon for mass worship.
</P>
<P>
   Neel turned Warhol back into a psychological subject. She
painted him with his shirt off, in 1970, two years after he had
been shot by Valerie Solanis. His eyes are closed; his hands are
pressed between his knees; his breasts sag and he wears a stomach
brace. He looks like the weary old working-class man, born Andy
Warhola, that he might have become had he not remade himself so
relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Kruger places Warhol on the border between the private and the
public, or between the psychological and the iconographic. In her
photograph he looks cannily boyish, as he did at his peak. But wary
too (look at how his hand touches his cheek). All this wizardry had
its price. And there in the middle of his face are the words ``Not
cruel enough.''
</P>
<P>
   And framing his face, in red, are words that serve as an elegy
not unlike the one that F. Scott Fitzgerald had a nameless mourner
offer at Jay Gatsby's funeral: ``The poor son of a bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruger's four-square elegy reads: ``Not beautiful enough.''
``Not man enough.'' ``Not real enough.'' ``Not pathetic enough.''
She does the same thing with portraits of Malcolm X, Eleanor
Roosevelt and Marilyn Monroe. They form a quartet of cautionary
ghost stories.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the work of these women makes me think artists worry
too much about being ahead of their time. Maybe the hardest thing
of all is to be a real part of one's time, to take it in with all
the courage and imagination one can muster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
