<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DEVICES TO MAKE LIFE AT HOME EASIER FOR HANDYMEN, COOKS AND
COMPUTER MAVENS 
</HEADLINE>
 uf-PATENTS-NYT   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labor Day celebrates industry and work with the ultimate salute:
a day off. The rest of the year, inventors strive to find ways to
make work and everyday tasks easier.
</P>
<P>
   Roofers who install tiles on houses may appreciate a pair of
work shoes patented by James Mills. He has invented footwear with
adjustable pitch, so that a roofer, or a firefighter or chimney
sweep, standing on a steep roof can remain upright. His shoes are
actually shoe boards that fit over the foot, with or without
conventional shoes. The boards attach to a base that holds a
contact pad made of foam rubber. Brackets extending from the
underside of the shoe board to the top of the base are connected
with a rod. A series of holes in the brackets allow the pitch of
the footwear to be adjusted with a pin to match the slant of a
roof. A wearer would use the shoes standing with one leg downroof
from the other. Mills, who lives in Valparaiso, Ind., received
patent 6,035,557.
</P>
<P>
   Any parent whose daily tasks include picking up plastic building
block toys may like the vacuum cleaner attachment patented by
Anthony Vandenberg. Vandenberg's curved pipe can be attached to a
standard vacuum cleaner hose so blocks can be suctioned off the
floor. A plate inside the pipe directs the blocks into a channel
connected to a transparent container. Vandenberg says in his patent
that dirt and dust could still flow into the vacuum cleaner bag,
and that a spring-loaded probe would clear out any blocks stuck in
the pipe. The container comes with a hinged bottom so the blocks
can be dumped into a toy box. Vandenberg received patent 6,048,249.
</P>
<P>
   HELP WITH COOKING, IN THE KITCHEN OR OUT
</P>
<P>
   Cooks will be interested in Leonhard May's remotely programmable
oven. May, who lives in North Royalton, Ohio, has patented an oven
that cooks can control via computer modem. A cook can dial into a
microprocessor on his oven and program cooking mode, temperature
and duration. A cook can modify those directions later, and bring
up the oven's progress on his computer screen. May received patent
6,080,972.
</P>
<P>
   Any chef compiling an omelette might welcome Stephen Herbruck's
patented egg carton. The box has compartments shaped to hold eggs,
like a traditional egg carton, but adds compartments intended to
hold other ingredients. Herbruck, from Saranac, Mich., designed his
carton so that the number of ``other'' compartments match the
number of egg holders, so the carton can carry the correct amount
of ingredients for an omelette or any egg dish, or even Easter egg
painting supplies. He received patent 5,927,501.
</P>
<P>
   For those who like the convenience of store-bought cookies but
the luxury of fresh-baked ones, there's the toaster cookie invented
by Sarath Katta, Sambasiva Chigurupati and Wayne Moore, all from
Omaha. The cookies are pre-baked so that after they're bought, the
baking can be finished in a home toaster oven. Each one is coated
with flavors so that when the cookies are heated, the flavors
release a scent. After a few minutes in a toaster oven, the cookies
are soft, chewy and smell like fresh-baked, the inventors said in
their application. Their patent, which belongs to ConAgra Corp., is
6,093,437.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen clean-up could be improved with a couple of patents for
dishwashers. In Baljit Singh's design for a combination sink and
dishwasher, a dishwasher is installed adjacent to a sink. A common
wall divides the two. A basket slides from within the dishwasher,
through an opening in the common wall, until it rests in the sink.
Dirty dishes can be rinsed and loaded into the basket, which is
then returned to the dishwasher. Singh, who lives in Norwalk,
Calif., won patent 5,934,298.
</P>
<P>
   In Alan Cassalia's patented dishwasher, the bottom rack extends
and retracts like the conventional lower racks that holds pots,
dishes and a flatware basket. But Cassalia, who lives in Richboro,
Pa., added scissor-arm support brackets that allow the lower rack
to be pulled out and then raised to the same height as the upper
rack. He received patent 5,971,513.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE THAT BOLSTERs WEAK GRAMMAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone whose job involves writing could probably use the
``grammar-check'' invented by Anthony Krueger and Ronald Fein for
the Microsoft Corp. Their invention works like the spell-check
function included in word-processing software. When someone working
on a document stops typing, the patented software takes advantage
of the idle time to extract sentences from the text and analyze
them for ``proper grammatical composition,'' the patent says. If
the sentence includes bad English, an error icon will appear on the
computer screen. The writer can click on the icon to bring up a
menu with suggested corrections that the inventors say will ``most
likely correct each error.'' They received patent 6,012,075.
</P>
<P>
   Any worker who relies on a laptop might appreciate the portable
stand patented by John Troyer. The stand has a pair of feet, a pair
of support posts, and a horizontal platform with wings to hold a
laptop. The stand parts are collapsible so that it will fit in a
suitcase, but when it is fully extended it ``is capable of holding
a laptop computer at the proper height and angle for use,'' Troyer,
who is from Cincinnati, wrote in his patent. He received patent
6,076,787.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C., 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
