u s BC-FBC-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-03 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SOUL SEARCHING AT ALABAMA AND PENN STATE, AND BOOS
AT FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Here are three reasons why the college
football season matters as soon as the ball is teed up on the first
full weekend of games:
</P>
<P>
   --The first national title casualty was recorded as
underappreciated UCLA beat over-rated Alabama, 35-24.
</P>
<P>
   --Little Toledo of the Mid-American Conference prompted soul
searching in no less a gridiron icon than Joe Paterno by whipping
the Nittany Lions, 24-6, on Penn State's home field.
</P>
<P>
   --Florida fans booed the sloppy performance of their team and
Coach Steve Spurrier punted on third-and-26 rather than watch his
inept offense stumble through another play. The Gators were beating
Ball State, 33-19, at the time!
</P>
<P>
   Name another sport where opening day matters as much it does in
college football, where standards vary from program to program and
so often are interconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Here on Saturday afternoon, Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie bounced
off the field, hugged his athletic director, Kevin White (who may
or may not fire him) and raised his hands asking a sellout crowd
for more noise. The Irish had outlasted Texas A&AMP;M, which was ranked
No. 25, by 24-10 for their first victory since midseason last
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day in Columbia, S.C., Davie's predecessor, Lou
Holtz, had to chase goal-post-seeking fans off the field so South
Carolina could officially finish a 31-0 shutout of New Mexico
State. It was the Gamecocks' first victory in 21 games _ 11 of
those losses were under Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought that an Alabama team ranked No. 3 in the
nation would go to the Rose Bowl to begin a national title drive
against a U.C.L.A. team that had the 107th-ranked defense in the
nation last year, only to leave there upset and preoccupied with
different numbers? Mainly, the number of losses by other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have an opportunity to achieve all our goals,''
Alabama offensive guard Griff Redmill said. ``They say if you're
going to lose, lose early. You can't lose any earlier than we lost
today.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible for the Crimson Tide to climb back to the Bowl
Championship Series title game. In 1993, Florida State lost to
Notre Dame during the season and earned the title. In 1996, Florida
lost to Florida State but was declared national champion after
winning a rematch against the Seminoles in the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But it's unlikely. Alabama must win its next 10 games, as well
as the Southeastern Conference championship game, and hope that
only one other team goes undefeated. Then they must hope that the
computers and the polls rank them as the toughest of the one-loss
teams. Either way it makes for a tense season.
</P>
<P>
   And who would have thought that Paterno might have to wait until
next year to notch the seven victories needed to pass Bear Bryant
as the coach with the most Division I-A victories at 324? Seven
victories come as sure as the cold to Happy Valley in autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Nittany Lions lost the defensive stars LaVar Arrington
and Courtney Brown to the National Football League and their opener
to Southern California. Yes, quarterback Rashard Casey may be
distracted after being arrested on May 14 and charged in the
assault of an off-duty police officer in his hometown, Hoboken,
N.J. But Toledo? In Beaver Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to take a realistic look at whether we are any
good,'' Paterno said after the loss. ``We have not played a decent
offensive game in two weeks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You expect the caustic Spurrier to show his disgust when
quarterback Jess Palmer goes 21 of 46 against a team that had not
won in 17 consecutive games. Spurrier did _ midway through the
third quarter when, facing third-and-26, he decided to punt. ``It
was like third-and-50,'' he said. ``We were just hoping to not get
it blocked.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the thickest-skinned Gators were stunned on the
subsequent drive when the Florida Field crowd serenaded them with
boos after Ball State blocked a punt and recovered it on Florida's
13-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever been booed by my own fans,'' tailback
Bo Carroll said. ``It wasn't exactly the outcome we wanted. The
fans weren't thrilled either. Maybe everyone gets a little spoiled.
They're used to us throwing up 60.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida forced a Ball State turnover and went on to a 40-19
victory. But Spurrier was not surprised at how the school's fans
treated his team. ``We didn't play that super,'' he said. ``We
won't be too full of ourselves after this one. We've got a lot of
improving to do.''
</P>
<P>
   They better. As Week 1 demonstrated, the college football season
can be over for some teams almost as soon as it begins. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
