<P>
   GORE-LABOR _ COLUMBUS, Ohio _ If organized labor's muscle helps
Democrat Al Gore carry Ohio in this year's presidential election,
much of the push will come from union members like Mary Kay Thomas.
Thomas, 43, doesn't drive a truck, assemble automobiles or bend
steel _ muscular jobs historically associated with the labor
movement. Instead, Thomas, deputy clerk for the Dayton Municipal
Court, is a public employee and a member of Local 101 of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees
(AFSCME). As a member of a public employees' union, Thomas
increasingly represents the face of organized labor on this first
Labor Day of a new century. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-INTERNET _ WASHINGTON _ In the not so distant future,
experts say, White House candidates will be debating on the
Internet, with the voters posing the questions. Even now, the Bush
and Gore web sites _ which, not so long ago, were merely novelty
items in presidential campaigns _ have emerged as essential
campaign tools. They have also sparked a lively internal debate on
which camp is doing a better job in the cyberspace contest. (Glass,
Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-AFRICA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ We're on the cusp of autumn,
the season of decision. And so it is that 33-year-old Wanda Hall
has spent some time considering the essential question: What sort
of choice does a conscientious American make in this era of
national prosperity and comfort? Democrat? Republican? Nader?
Buchanan? Wanda Hall has made her call. She's packing her bags _
and moving to Africa. (Buchholz, Austin American-Statesman) WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED.
