<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-MEMORIAL-SERVI     09-03 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-MEMORIAL-SERVICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JEWS LOST IN WORLD WAR II, FLOWERS AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Ogen Rintzler came from Israel to the
blue-green waters of the Black Sea on Sunday afternoon to say
farewell to his parents and to heal a wound even deeper than their
loss. Chefner Tudor made the journey in memory of his best friend.
Ilana Blum came to acknowledge the father whose death she had long
refused to accept.
</P>
<P>
   They were among 70 relatives and friends from around the world
who gathered for a memorial service at sea honoring 778 Romanian
Jews and crew members who died in 1942 when a Russian submarine
sank their disabled ship, the Struma.
</P>
<P>
   They all had their own memories of loss as a cantor's voice
carried the song of the dead across the calm, sun-drenched water.
They wept, they held each other and they seemed to find solace in
finally saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can pass this memory to the next generation so that
they don't forget the Struma,'' said Rintzler, 73.
</P>
<P>
   The sinking of the Struma was a wartime horror that the world
had largely forgotten. But some of the sensitivities surrounding
the episode were resurrected by the effort led by a grandson of two
of the victims to locate the wreckage and to conduct the memorial
service. The Turkish government refused at first to grant
permission for dives to try to find the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   When the divers went down anyway, their vessel was boarded by
the Turkish Coast Guard and the crew was held for several hours.
Their release came only through the intervention of one of the
country's wealthiest families.
</P>
<P>
   Approval for the dives finally came after Prime Minister Ehud
Barak of Israel raised the issue with his Turkish counterpart,
Bulent Ecevit, during a state visit late last month. By then, time
was too short to find the wreck. But the search leader said he was
confident it was in 250 feet of water, about 5 miles offshore near
where the Bosporus joins the Black Sea north of Istanbul. They also
discovered the graves of seven victims in the cemetery of a coastal
village.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the modern search for the Struma was enmeshed in
politics, so was its sinking at the height of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Struma left the Romanian port of Constanza on Dec. 11, 1941,
carrying Romanian Jews fleeing persecution and heading for
Palestine. Its engine failed on the Black Sea and it was towed into
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, trying to remain neutral, refused to allow anyone off
the ship. The British, who controlled Palestine, were refusing
entry to large numbers of Jews because they did not want to
antagonize the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very clear policy of restricting immigration to
Palestine,'' said David Logan, the British ambassador to Turkey,
who attended Sunday's service with his wife, Judy. ``In retrospect,
we could obviously have adopted a more humane attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Struma sat in Istanbul for 70 days, growing more squalid by
the day. The ship was a converted steamer with a single outlet for
fresh water. The only food came from the city's Jews. Efforts to
repair the engine failed.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 23, 1942, the police towed the Struma up the Bosporus as
passengers hung signs from its sides pleading ``Help us.'' The ship
was set adrift in the Black Sea and at dawn the next day it was
sunk by a Russian submarine for unknown reasons. Only one person
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was the biggest loss of life in the exodus to
Palestine, the episode might have remained relegated to academic
studies if not for Greg Buxton, a computer programmer from
Birmingham, England, whose paternal grandparents perished on the
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Buxton spent two years and all of his money organizing the
search. He said Sunday that he expects that future efforts by the
governments of Israel and Turkey will find the ship. But from the
outset, he said the more important goal was remembering those who
died with the memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   Ogen Rintzler was 14 in early 1941 when his father and mother,
Ahron and Fanni Rintzler, sent him, their only child, to Palestine.
His parents had visited the country in the 1930s and his father
fell in love with the dream of a Jewish homeland. His parents
booked passage on the Struma to join him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire family was against my parents getting on the
Struma,'' Rintzler said. ``They sent a rabbi to convince my father
not to take the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Rintzler has remained in Israel, marrying, building a business
career, raising his own children. He learned to live with the
deaths of his parents, but several years ago he discovered
something that renewed and increased his sorrow. An uncle told him
that his mother was pregnant when she boarded the ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the heaviest blow,'' Rintzler said mournfully,
looking at a photograph of himself as a boy with his parents in
Bucharest. ``Knowing what they suffered, what my mother suffered
while she was pregnant, it was worse than the deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Chefner Tudor, 80, came to Istanbul from Haifa, Israel, to honor
his best boyhood friend, Norbert Storfer. Were it not for an
accident of history, someone might have been there Sunday
remembering Tudor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was registered on the Struma, but there were delays and
another ship became available,'' Tudor said. ``I told Norbert he
should come with me, but he said he was enrolled on the Struma and
he would wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Tudor sailed on the Dorian II, arriving in Istanbul with about
600 Jews from Romania and Bulgaria. The people from that earlier
ship were allowed to disembark and proceed to Palestine by train
and bus, and Tudor has lived there ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Horia Lobel was the doctor on the Struma. His pregnant wife
stayed behind and planned to join him with the baby in Palestine
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was always waiting for him to send for us,'' said
Ilana Blum, the daughter Lobel never knew. ``There were rumors of
survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Blum, a professor at a Tel Aviv medical school, and her mother
were given shelter by a Christian family in the Romanian mountains
during the war. She was 14 before she knew she was Jewish. She was
58 before she accepted her father's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, I always thought that maybe he somehow survived,''
she said sadly as flowers tossed onto the sea by mourners floated
past the ship. ``Now I have closed the circle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
