<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-AIDE-PROFILE-NYT     09-03 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-AIDE-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AIDE EARNS HER STRIPES ON PASSION AND COMMITMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wispy young woman paces at the back of the crowd, nodding
incessantly as Al Gore makes another arcane point about the
intricacies of Medicare. She claps tentatively and pumps her fist a
little, almost as if afraid that someone will see. It is not every
27-year-old, after all, who can be driven to ecstasy by a
candidate's pledge to put the Medicare surplus in a lock box.
</P>
<P>
   But Sarah A. Bianchi is not just any twenty-something. In the
five years since she graduated from Harvard, where she shared a
suite in Leverett House with Gore's eldest daughter, Karenna Gore
Schiff, Bianchi has worked as an assistant to the associate
director for health at the Office of Management and Budget and an
assistant director for health policy at the president's domestic
policy council. From there, she became the senior health care
adviser to the vice president and now serves as deputy issues
director of the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore has increasingly built his politics on his passion for
policy, Bianchi has become one of his most visible staff members.
Last week, after pulling near all-nighters to compile briefing
papers on health care, she worked the campaign's press filing
centers doggedly and sat in on conference calls, answering
reporters' questions about the details of Gore's proposals and
taking shots at those of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, at a health care forum in Albuquerque, N.M., a woman
in the audience asked Gore whether his proposal to expand the
federal Children's Health Insurance Program would cover prenatal
care. He had no idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Sarah out there somewhere?'' Gore pleaded, scanning the
crowd. She wasn't, having stayed in a nearby filing center, where
reporters and Gore aides were watching the event on closed-circuit
television.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing her name, Bianchi scurried to his rescue. She assured
the woman, and Gore, that the proposal would restore prenatal care
coverage that had been eliminated several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that Gore's been fighting for for a long
time,'' Bianchi told the woman.
</P>
<P>
   And then Gore, laughing at himself, said, ``As I was saying,
part of my proposal is to restore the coverage for people in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the campaign, according to Gore and his
aides, Bianchi has earned a place at the table with a passionate
commitment to social policy, a steel-trap mind for numbers, a quiet
confidence that belies her age, and a determination that policy not
be compromised by politics. If some Gore aides once dismissed her
because of her youth, they now know that she has the vice
president's complete confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in an interview, described Bianchi _ ``Sarah B.'' to the
Gore family _ as ``scary smart,'' and possessing an encyclopedic
expertise on health and welfare policy.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't it make him nervous to place someone so young in a
position of such responsibility and visibility? ``Yes,'' he said,
``it did. For about a week. After that I lost any apprehension at
all. She handles herself like a seasoned pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Bianchi, an Atlanta native, has long been enamored of policy. In
college, she wrote a senior thesis about welfare reform in Georgia.
Her father is the founding headmaster of a progressive private
school. Her mother is a developmental psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   She came to know the Gores through her ties to Schiff. But
several Gore aides said she had risen on her merits, and Ronald
Klain, Gore's former chief of staff, said he first hired her
without even knowing of her connections to the Gores.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns, of course, are often populated with bright young
people who are valued for their enthusiasm, their stamina and their
willingness to sleep on futons. Gore's research director, David
Ginsberg, is 25. Michael B. Feldman, a senior adviser, is 31.
Gore's national field director, Donnie Fowler, is 32, as is his
speechwriter, Eli Attie. His press secretary, Chris Lehane, is 33.
</P>
<P>
   Bianchi, a fan of black pinstripes, fuels her days with candy
bars and Diet Cokes. Her cell phone has become an appendage, and
she acknowledges that she has no life outside the campaign. But
youth, she suggests, can be overcome, particularly with a resume as
deep as hers and a long list of mentors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable,'' Bianchi said, ``that I've had a lot of
experiences that, though they were quick, have built on each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   She admitted feeling the doubts of her colleagues in early
strategy sessions, but said that Gore had helped establish her
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there have been meetings with senior staff where they
come in and think, `What is she doing here?''' Bianchi said. ``But
then he'll call on me and say, `Sarah, tell us about that
program.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bianchi's most important role, said several Gore aides, may be
in fighting the temptation to push the campaign's rhetoric beyond
the limits of its policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have definitely been moments when far more important
people than me were advocating a position that I was not,'' she
said. ``You know, it's `Why can't we say it this way?' and I have
to say, `Because it's not true.' And then they say, `Well, can't we
just make it true?' And you have to say, `No.'''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff said that Bianchi was ``not afraid to be the buzz kill''
in staff meetings. ``When there's something that might play well
politically,'' Schiff said, ``Sarah's always the reality check.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
