<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-INTERMEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDCOM SAID TO BE IN TALKS TO BUY INTERMEDIA
</HEADLINE>
 By   ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WorldCom Corp. is in advanced talks to acquire Intermedia
Communications Inc., a telecommunications operator, for almost $3
billion in cash and stock, executives close to the negotiations
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Intermedia, based in Tampa, Fla., has been an extremely
attractive takeover target because it has a 54 percent stake in
Digex Inc., a Web hosting company, which provides storage for
corporate Web sites, monitors their performance and maintains
Internet connections. It is viewed as the crown jewel of
Intermedia, which sells phone services to businesses and government
agencies and Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to the deal, WorldCom entered
negotiations with Intermedia last week after talks between
Intermedia and Global Crossing, the telecommunications company
based in Hamilton, Bermuda, broke down. A third suitor, Exodus
Communications Inc., offered to acquire Digex, based in Beltsville,
Md., for close to $8.5 billion in stock but was rebuffed by
Intermedia.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Intermedia put its Digex stake, for which it paid $150
million in cash in July 1997, up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   According to the executives, WorldCom is negotiating to pay
about $39 a share for Intermedia and take on nearly $3 billion of
the company's debt. That would represent about a 70 percent premium
to Intermedia's closing price on Friday of $22.88.
</P>
<P>
   The executives cautioned that the deal could still fall apart
and that Digex could quash the deal. A purchase of Intermedia would
be WorldCom's first significant deal since its proposed merger with
the Sprint Corp.oration collapsed because of opposition from
antitrust regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
