<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9998 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-LABOR0904-COX     09-03 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LABOR0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore may benefit from increased numbers of unionized public
employeesBy William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ If organized labor's muscle helps Democrat Al
Gore carry Ohio in this year's presidential election, much of the
push will come from union members like Mary Kay Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 43, doesn't drive a truck, assemble automobiles or bend
steel _ muscular jobs historically associated with the labor
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Thomas, deputy clerk for the Dayton Municipal Court, is
a public employee and a member of Local 101 of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees (AFSCME).
</P>
<P>
   As a member of a public employees' union, Thomas increasingly
represents the face of organized labor on this first Labor Day of a
new century.
</P>
<P>
   Both nationally and in Ohio, the percentage of public employees
in the labor movement is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 43 percent of the nation's 16.5 million union members
were public employees, up from 32 percent in 1983, the first year
the U.S. Census used sample sizes large enough to provide reliable
state-by-state breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, the percentage went from 24 percent in 1983 to 35
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the percentage of all public sector workers
belonging to unions has been increasing while the percentage of
private sector workers with union cards has declined.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, 22.5 percent of private employees were union members in
1983, compared to 13.4 percent in 1999. The percentage of Ohio
public employees belonging to unions has increased from 39.3
percent in 1983 to 47.7 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio labor leaders, such as state AFL-CIO President William
Burga, say there's unity between these two streams of the labor
movement. Detractors, such as economist Leo Troy of Rutgers
University, say private sector and public sector workers have
different political and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this year's presidential election could turn on
who's right.
</P>
<P>
   THE PRESIDENTIAL RACE AND LABOR'S CHANGING FACE
</P>
<P>
   Thomas enthusiastically backs Gore for president. She
particularly liked what she considered his sparkling performance at
the Democratic National Convention and his choice of Sen. Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut as his running mate. Lieberman, an
Orthodox Jew, is the first person of his faith to run on a major
party's presidential ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good. I'm energized,'' said Thomas. ``I got a positive
outlook for Gore since he picked a running mate. It added some
diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and Gore, she said, are for the ``working folks,''
while Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his running mate Dick Cheney
aren't.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time during this presidential season, whatever
sparkle Gore has as a presidential candidate didn't attract some of
the nation's old-line private sector unions. The United Auto
Workers briefly flirted with endorsing consumer advocate Ralph
Nader before throwing in with Gore just before the Democratic
convention last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters still haven't endorsed a candidate, although
they're expected to do so in the next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's support for normalizing trade relations with China
chilled his relations with the auto workers and other industrial
unions. As Bill Clinton's vice president, he also supported the
North American Free Trade Agreement, which industrial unions
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned. There's still concern,'' said Burga, formerly
a steelworker. ``I think it's dissipating. We're seeing a lot of
enthusiasm now.''
</P>
<P>
   Burga said Gore helped himself at the convention by pledging to
support making workers' rights part of trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Bush won't listen to us,'' Burga said. ``We think
we have a chance of Gore doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said she understands how industrial workers feel about
the trade issue, although it doesn't affect her directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess as public employees we're not part of the trade
agreement. We're not shipping off a lot of our main jobs,'' she
said. ``I'm very sympathetic to their causes.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy, distinguished professor of economics, said, however,
public employees generally ``don't give one hoot'' about trade
agreements. In fact, said Troy, they benefit by lower prices for
consumer goods that result from free trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This labor solidarity is just a slogan,'' he contended. ``In
reality it's like Swiss Cheese. It's full of holes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said public employee unions seek more government spending
that will result in more jobs for their members, while well-paid
union members in the private sector, such as auto workers, don't
want to pay the high taxes that come with more public spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush can tap into that, he'll take a lot of private-sector
(union members),'' Troy said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kate Bronfrenbrenner, director of labor education at Cornell
University, said Troy misjudges public employees.
</P>
<P>
   In states like Ohio, she said, industrial workers have raised
the consciousness of public employees on the trade issue. Public
employees understand that the loss of industrial jobs due to unfair
trade practices will affect the tax base and, ultimately, affect
their jobs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade deficits hurt the public sector,'' Bronfrenbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   SHRINKING PRIVATE UNIONS AND GROWING PUBLIC UNIONS
</P>
<P>
   Trade deficits, said Ohio AFL-CIO president Burga, are bad for
unions and for the country.
</P>
<P>
   They mean fewer American manufacturing jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we end up losing manufacturing, at some point it will cost
our economy because this country cannot survive on a service and
high-technology economy. We have to have manufacturing to survive
in this world or else we'll just continue a downward standard of
living,'' Burga said.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of union members in manufacturing has been dramatic
both in overall numbers and percentages. The total number of
members in unions representing auto, steel and other manufacturing
workers went from 5.3 million in 1983 to 3 million last year. In
Ohio, the drop was from 461,916 manufacturing union members in 1983
to 304,452 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing unions no longer dominate Ohio's labor landscape.
The two biggest unions in the state represent public employees _
the Ohio Education Association, with 117,000 active members,
including teachers and education support employees ; and AFSCME,
Mary Kay Thomas' union, with 104,069 members, representing a broad
cross section of public sector workers.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Leibensperger, secretary-treasurer of the OEA, said his
group historically has ``supported our brothers and sisters in the
labor movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The OEA's major focus, however, is on education _ improving the
work lives of school employees and the conditions for learning in
public schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a major reason why the OEA and its parent organization,
the National Education Association, back Gore, he said. For
example, he said, Gore opposes vouchers which would let parents use
public money to send their children to private schools while Bush
favors them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are very much energized by the voucher issue,''
Leibensperger said.
</P>
<P>
   A LABOR CAST OF 400 FOR THE ELECTION
</P>
<P>
   As always, the outcome of the presidential election will depend
on which side does better at getting its voters to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Burga said electing Gore is the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have over 400 local union activists who are serving as
(election) coordinators,'' Burga said. ``We're going to have more
people than we ever had working full time (on the election).''
</P>
<P>
   In Dayton, Wes Wells, executive director of the AFL-CIO Regional
Labor Council, which covers 11 counties, said his group will have
100 people working for Gore and other labor-backed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do our job, which we intend on doing, you're going to
see labor being a main player in this election,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
