<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FIRESTONE-LABOR-NYT &LR;      09-03 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS REPORTED IN TALKS AT FIRESTONE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiators for Bridgestone/Firestone and the union representing
8,000 of its workers continued talks in St. Louis on Sunday as they
sought to reach a tentative contract and avert a threatened strike.
</P>
<P>
   The union, the United Steelworkers of America, said there had
been enough progress in the talks to warrant keeping workers on the
job even though the union originally planned to begin a strike
early Saturday if no agreement was reached by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still slogging away,'' said John Duray, a union
spokesman. ``If progress weren't being made, we wouldn't still be
at the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Bridgestone/Firestone, which is based in
Nashville, also said Sunday that they were optimistic that a
settlement could be reached without a walkout threatened at nine of
its 11 U.S. factories.
</P>
<P>
   A strike would involve workers at factories in Akron, Ohio;
Bloomington, Ill.; Decatur, Ill.; Des Moines, Iowa; Noblesville,
Ind.; Oklahoma City, Okla.; Russellville, Ark.; LaVergne, Tenn.;
and Warren County, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Smith, mobilization coordinator for Steelworkers Local
1055 in LaVergne, said the workers were poised to go on strike if
the talks fall apart. ``We're on the ready whether to have a work
stoppage or a tentative agreement,'' Smith said. ``And if they want
us to help them rebuild their reputation, then we're ready to do
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 8,000 union members are covered by a master contract
that expired on April 23. Since then, they have been working under
a temporary contract extension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MOVIE-THEATER-BOOM-AR     09-03 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-THEATER-BOOM-ART-(1450)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE INDUSTRY MONEY PROBLEMS, COMPETITION SPURS MORE MOVIE
THEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For moviegoers weary of long lines, sticky floors and
poor sight lines, the two huge new theaters facing each other on
Times Square at 42nd Street near Eighth Avenue _ a block once home
to several seedy flophouses _ are a welcome improvement. They offer
comfortable stadium seating, clean surroundings and the latest
digital-sound technology. Together, they have 38 screens and more
than 8,100 seats.
</P>
<P>
   But for analysts who follow the movie theater industry, those
two costly new movie houses, the Loews Cineplex 42nd Street E-Walk
and the AMC Empire 25, are examples of an industry in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Longstanding distribution practices force them to compete with
each other for films, and there are just not enough hits to go
around, especially during a lackluster summer like the current one.
Since theater companies do not allow any film to be shown in more
than one theater in a ``film zone,'' which usually encompasses an
area of three to five square miles. The Loews multiplex theater
that opened in the basement of the Virgin Megastore in Times Square
just four years ago is relegated to showing movies well past their
prime.
</P>
<P>
   After AMC opened a popular 24-screen theater in Dallas in 1995,
developers and theater companies began building gigantic
multiplexes at a frenzied pace. In five years, the number of movie
screens in the country has grown to more than 37,000 from slightly
fewer than 28,000, the number that most analysts agree is the
maximum that can exist profitably.
</P>
<P>
   As companies open large, luxurious megaplexes _ which generally
have at least 14 screens and always offer stadium seating _ they
often find themselves taking business away from older, smaller
megaplexes that lack the most up-to-the-minute amenities. Often
stuck with long-term leases, the exhibitors have not been able to
close unprofitable theaters fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mass suicide,'' Sean J. Egan, the managing director
of Egan-Jones Ratings Co., a bond-rating firm in Wynnewood, Pa.,
said of the building spree. ``They see their competitors putting up
new attractive theaters so they think that to be competitive they
have to do that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the publicly-traded theater companies have
watched their stock prices plunge. Bond ratings have plummeted. A
few companies, like Carmike Cinemas, a chain based in Columbus,
Ga., and Edwards Theaters, of Newport Beach, Calif., have filed for
bankruptcy protection. Others, like Regal Cinemas and United
Artists, are teetering on the edge or struggling. AMC, for example,
cut administrative costs by $20 million last year, including
dismissing more than 100 people. Most recently, Loews Cineplex, the
nation's fourth-largest movie-theater chain and the dominant
company in New York, said on Aug. 25 that it might default on its
debt payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is somewhat of a universal problem for the industry,''
said Dick Westerling, a spokesman for Regal Cinemas in Knoxville,
Tenn. ``We've had a heavily leveraged scenario that has accompanied
the overbuilding. And to have a future, you had to build. It's a
challenging time for all of us in exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these industry-wide problems, more new megaplexes are
being built in New York and elsewhere in the country because of
competitive pressure or commitments that predate the theater
industry's overbuilding and steep financial reversals. Loews
Cineplex plans to open a 14-screen theater on 34th Street and
Eighth Avenue in 18 months. In Ontario, Calif., two new megaplexes
run by Edwards Theaters and AMC face one another across a parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   The theater-building boom began during flush times for the movie
business. In the 90s box-office grosses were steadily increasing,
financing was cheap and there was clearly a need to improve the
movie-going experience. Many of the cramped older multiplexes had
been incorporated into shopping centers almost as an afterthought,
merely to bring in evening traffic. Audiences were grumbling about
inconvenient show times, sold-out showings and tiny screens. There
was concern that more affordable home entertainment equipment and
other technological advances would prove more attractive
alternatives for moviegoers. At first, exhibitors that opened in
new, underserved markets did well, said David H. Allen, a media and
entertainment analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``All the big
players were getting returns on their capital of 20 or 30
percent,'' he said. ``It was like minting money.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry expected its new theaters to be popular, but it had
not anticipated a major change in moviegoing habits: As megaplexes
proliferated, people began bypass the older multiplexes closer to
their homes and to travel farther to go to one of the newer
megaplexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew from the outset the broad geographic appeal that a
megaplex would have,'' said a spokesman for AMC, Richard J. King,
``but we did underestimate the effect they would have on the older
multiplexes. We were a little surprised by the pace.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Besides cannibalizing their multiplexes, the exhibitors cut into
their revenues by having so many screens in each megaplex. With
multiple screens, an exhibitor can show widely anticipated movies
like this summer's ``The Perfect Storm'' or ``The Patriot'' in
several auditoriums at once, staggering starting times and making
it unlikely that anyone will be turned away. But that means a film
will have a shorter life in the theater, because most people who
want to see a particular movie will catch it during the first two
weeks of its run, when the lion's share of the proceeds go to the
film studio, not the exhibitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in their best interest for a film to be under their roof
for eight weeks,'' said Jeffrey S. Thomison, an analyst for
Hilliard Lyons, a securities firm in Louisville, Ky., said of the
theater companies.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the industry's problems was a disappointing summer
at the box office. Paul Dergarabedian, the president of Exhibitor
Relations, a Los Angeles company that monitors box-office
performance, estimates that gross box office revenue from this
summer's movie season, which ends Monday, will be seven percent
lower than last summer's, $2.7 billion, compared with $2.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And although some movies attracted large audiences, none
generated the excitement of last year's ``Star Wars: Episode One _
The Phantom Menace'' or this summer's television hit ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To fill that many seats,'' Dergarabedian said, ``you have to
have a marketplace that's really psyched up, that's excited not
only see the movie they came out to see, but to see another movie
next week.'' But instead of building momentum through the summer,
attendance has been dropping, he said.
</P>
<P>
   AMC officials acknowledge that the absence of a box-office
stampede has hurt its Empire 25, the company's first theater in New
York, more than its Times Square competitor, although they say both
theaters are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   The AMC spokesman, King, said that his company's interest in
Times Square dates to the early days of the neighborhood's
revitalization, long before the Loews Cineplex E-Walk was
contemplated. But AMC's complicated project took many years to
complete, in part because it involved the renovation and relocation
of a 1912 theater. The Empire 25 opened in April, five months after
the E-walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed to find that we wouldn't have that trade
area to ourselves,'' King said. After encountering competition, AMC
decided to dedicate the top floor of its new theater to arthouse
films, a market sector that has also had a slow summer.
</P>
<P>
   Loews, which has 128 screens in New York (83 of them in
Manhattan alone) and is 40 percent owned by Sony Pictures
Entertainment, a major movie studio, has more clout with
distributors and often gets first crack at the most-anticipated
pictures. As of July 31, E-Walk was the 12 highest-grossing theater
in the country, said Daniel Marks, the executive vice president of
ACNeilsen EDI, which tracks box-office returns. (Marks said AMC's
Empire 25 was too new to be ranked.)
</P>
<P>
   King said he expected AMC to get more top films eventually. ``A
newcomer doesn't get full allocation immediately,'' he said.
``Normally, it takes one or two seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater companies are taking various steps to reduce their debt,
including closing unprofitable theaters, renegotiating bank loans
and slowing the pace of construction. And moviegoers themselves are
likely to notice some of their efforts, including pre-movie
advertising, kiosks selling movie paraphernalia in theater lobbies
and more ads on popcorn bags and everywhere else exhibitors can
think of. ``We're all exploring ancillary revenue streams,'' said a
spokesman for Regal Cinemas, Dick Westerling. ``People will become
more creative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
