<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANAON-ELECTIONS-AR     09-03 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANAON-ELECTIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION APPEARS TO SWEEP PARLIAMENT SEATS IN BEIRUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Ousted Prime Minister Rafik Hariri dealt a
crushing electoral blow to Lebanon's Syrian-appointed government in
the final round of parliamentary voting on Sunday, early results
showed, sweeping all of Beirut's seats and gaining a powerful
majority of backers in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In a modern, extravagantly financed campaign the likes of which
this traditionally clan-dominated city has never seen, thousands of
the swashbuckling multibillionaire's supporters swarmed the
streets, showering every passing car with palm cards listing his
ticket. Twelve hours of criss-crossing the city turned up only four
workers in orange T-shirts distributing cards for his Sunni Moslem
rival, Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
   Official vote results are to be announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighteen of eighteen.'' Salim Diab, Hariri's campaign manager,
said an hour after the polls closed, slumping back tired but proud
in his operations room as supporters danced and cheered outside.
</P>
<P>
   Diab said Hariri's operation had 8,000 workers on the streets of
Beirut on Sunday, along with roughly 3,000 cars and taxicabs to
ferry voters to the polls. There were even ambulances to take the
ill.
</P>
<P>
   While the voting, in one of the bitterest campaigns ever here,
will not eliminate Syria's hold on Lebanon, it appears to have
drastically altered the political status quo.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Hariri defeated the two men handpicked as Lebanon's
leaders two years ago by Bashar Assad, the untried 34-year old heir
to Syrian power, during his internship here in preparation for
assuming the mantle of his father, Hafez Assad, who had run both
countries with wily, ruthless skill.
</P>
<P>
   President Emile Lahoud, the Maronite Catholic former military
commander that the young Assad chose in 1998, detests Hariri and
mounted a strong campaign with all the government's resources
against him, including hours of denunciation on the state run
television station.
</P>
<P>
   And the sitting prime minister, Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem
political fixture for decades, lost his seat in parliament despite
efforts by Syria to gerrymander Beirut into three electoral
districts and guarantee his victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hoss, an academic, is widely regarded as a decent and honest
man, unusually immune to corruption. But he is also viewed as
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   In what many analysts see as the most significant aspect of the
upset, both Hoss and Salam, according to the early results, were
swept away in the landslide.
</P>
<P>
   For many, it is a stunning political turnaround. Only a month
and a half ago, political pundits here were writing that Lahoud was
hoping for a two-thirds majority in parliament so that the
constitution could be amended to extend his six-year term, which
expires in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with the battering the government took in last week's
round of elections _ with 41 of 63 seats going to the opposition _
and Sunday's voting for the 128 seat body, Lahoud is faced with the
prospect of either accepting, or trying to find a way around,
naming his sworn enemy, Hariri, as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 18 seats Hariri appeared to have won in
Beirut _ along with the remaining 19th seat he gained in a backroom
deal with the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah on Friday _ the former prime
minister is expected to be supported by 23 winning candidates on
the joint Amal-Hezbollah ticket in southern Lebanon and at least a
dozen more from the Bekaa region in Sunday's voting.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 Taif agreement that helped end the bloody 15 year civil
war says the president is to appoint the prime minister with
support from a simple majority of parliament. And the removal of
Hoss and Salam from the political scene puts Lahoud and the Syrians
in a further bind. Under the unwritten National Accord here the
prime minister must be a Sunni Muslim and the alternative pool of
prominent candidates is now sharply reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1998, Hariri, as prime minister, built a series
of showy projects, including a rebuilding of the graceful old city
center that had been a ruined battleground called the Green Line
during the civil war. But Lahoud, who in his inaugural address
denounced all Lebanese politicians as a class, accused him of
corruption and driving the country into overwhelming debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
