<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-STEINBRENNE     09-03 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STEINBRENNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LOW PROFILE, STEINBRENNER HAS NOT CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The full-page front-page picture and blaring tabloid
headline instantly took one reader back more than 20 years, back to
a Saturday afternoon at Yankee Stadium when a George Steinbrenner
minion tapped him on the shoulder in the press box and said:
``George is in his office. Why don't you go see him?''
</P>
<P>
   The rare invitation for an audience with the Yankees' principal
owner came 21 years to the day before his verbal anti-personnel
bomb landed on Jeff Nelson, Mike Stanton and Chuck Knoblauch. In
the earlier instance, Ken Clay was the target of Steinbrenner's
contrived wrath.
</P>
<P>
   As on that occasion, a Steinbrenner henchman facilitated this
one by reaching out to a reporter and suggesting that he call the
owner in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The tap on the shoulder 21 years earlier came after Clay, a
struggling young pitcher, squandered a 5-0 lead his teammates gave
him in the first inning. He let Kansas City score a run in the
second inning and three runs in the third. Clay did not survive the
third inning of a game the Royals would win, 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter, uncertain what to expect, walked into
Steinbrenner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me about Ken Clay,'' Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about Ken Clay?'' the reporter asked against his better
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner proceeded to tell the reporter what about Clay:
``In horse racing we have what we call a morning glory. The horse
works a great 3 or 4 furlongs in the morning workout and looks
sensational. Then when the race comes, he starts sweating during
the parade to the post and when he gets in the gate and the race
starts, he stinks the place out. He spits the bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Clay is a morning glory. He spits the bit. He doesn't
have the courage. That may be harsh, but that's the way I feel. He
goes one good outing and three putrid ones. This was putrid. He
looks great in the bullpen, but he gets on the mound and chokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was scared stiff out there. He's one of the biggest
disappointments I've had since I've had the Yankees. He gets five
runs, goes out and spits the bit, chokes. Word is around he doesn't
have the guts. Give the guy the benefit of the doubt and he goes
out and chokes like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Steinbrenner has adopted a low-key public profile in
recent seasons, some people think he has mellowed. He would
probably feel insulted if someone said that to his face, but he
doesn't have to worry that his tough-boss image is fading. He
hasn't changed one bit. The Yankees just haven't given him many
chances to pull out the old George.
</P>
<P>
   What can even Steinbrenner find to fault with a team that wins
114 games in a season, that loses only three postseason games in
two years, that wins three World Series in four years, that wins 12
consecutive World Series games?
</P>
<P>
   How many fat toads come along to rouse his public ire?
</P>
<P>
   But this season the Yankees, for the most part, have not been
their dominating selves. They have never been in danger of falling
short of the postseason, but they weren't moving toward it with
their late 1990s intimidation. They weren't burying Boston and
Toronto in the standings. They weren't implementing the
scorched-earth style that Steinbrenner demands.
</P>
<P>
   And then their pre-Rivera relief tandem of Nelson and Stanton
began giving up game-altering home runs and assorted other hits and
walks. Knoblauch, already having frustrated the owner along with
everyone else with a mysterious throwing problem, languished on the
disabled list with a mysterious elbow ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the window of Steinbrenner's opportunity was open, and
he leaped through it, mouth first. His timing, however, was weird.
</P>
<P>
   Despite suffering whatever problems the owner perceived as
undermining the immediate future of the most expensive team in
baseball history, the Yankees have been winning with regularity.
Seventeen victories in the 25 games before Sunday represented their
best 25-game stretch since the first month of the season. Their
six-game lead over the Red Sox was their largest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But as if to fuel Steinbrenner's worst fears, the Yankees
suffered an improbable loss Sunday, 2-1 in 10 innings to the
Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees with their $100 million-plus payroll and Roger
Clemens, a five-time Cy Young award winner, against the team with
the major leagues' lowest payroll ($14,887,500) and a rookie
pitcher making his third major-league start. Ten players in the
Twins' starting lineup earning a collective $5,252,500 against 10
players in the Yankees' lineup with salaries totaling $58,507,143,
with half the Yankees' starters each earning more than the entire
Twins' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biggest number in Vegas,'' Tom Kelly, the Minnesota manager,
said of the betting odds on the game. ``You look at that number and
you go, `Oh my.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Matt Kinney, the 23-year-old rookie, stifled the Yankees on
one run and two hits in six innings. Three relievers kept the
Yankees stifled the rest of the way. A couple more games like this
one, and the owner will be storming through the press box, telling
reporters to ask him about Bernie Williams and David Justice and
Glenallen Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
