<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.S.-COMMITMENT-U.N.-     09-03 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-COMMITMENT-U.N.-850&AMP;TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MUST DECIDE ON U.N. COMMITMENT, U.S. AMBASSADOR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With President Clinton preparing to visit New York this week for
a meeting of world leaders at the United Nations, the American
ambassador, Richard Holbrooke, said on Saturday that the United
States must focus more on its relations with the organization,
which he called ``indispensable'' to American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``American dollars spent on the United Nations are worthwhile,''
Holbrooke said in an interview. ``We need to fix it and save it,
rather than walk away from it or weaken it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton will open a three-day series of speeches
and round-table discussions by more than 150 heads of government,
many of whom will also be talking privately with each other in
dozens of specially constructed conference nooks, partitioned from
delegate lounges, or in diplomatic missions around New York.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who is completing a year as ambassador to the United
Nations, has found much of his time consumed in lobbying his
administration colleagues on international issues and in carrying
out demands made by Congress. A group of congressmen who have often
been hostile to the United Nations have established multiple
hurdles to full American participation, blocking payment of past
dues and some new assessments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. will have to have a more profound discussion on how
the U.N. fits into its security objectives,'' Holbrooke said.
``With all its flaws, the U.N. is an indispensable organization for
American foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's potential foreign policy role in a new Democratic
administration _ if Vice President Al Gore wins the presidency in
November _ is the focus of unending speculation among other
diplomats. But he said he intended to ``work straight through until
Jan. 20'' no matter what the outcome of the election. His arrival
here was delayed a year by congressional blocks and federal ethics
investigations, largely into his contacts with American embassies
after he left a federal post. After serving as U.S. Ambassador to
Germany from 1993-1994, Holbrooke was appointed by Clinton as
assistant secretary of state, but left that post to become vice
chairman at the investment bank Credit Suisse First Boston from
1996 to 1999, during which time he was concurrently appointed by
Clinton as special presidential envoy on missions to Cyprus, Bosnia
and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that he did not disagree that reform is still
needed in the United Nations and that, in his dealings with the
organization's international civil servants, he had been ``dismayed
at the bureaucratic behavior and obstructionism.''
</P>
<P>
   He has strongly supported strengthening the U.N. peacekeeping
department and initiatives by Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
reform other areas of U.N. administration. Holbrooke's next target,
he said, is the U.N. department of public information, which he
contends is overstaffed and ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   But while Holbrooke has been vocal in criticizing U.N.
shortcomings, especially when members of Congress are visiting,
there is no doubt that his job has been made more difficult by
congressional restrictions imposed in the name of reform, other
diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke and Donald Hays, another ambassador who is a budget
and management expert assigned full time to the U.S. mission to the
United Nations, have spent many hours fighting to get American dues
to the organization reduced: down to 22 percent of the regular U.N.
budget from the 25 percent; and peacekeeping dues down to 25
percent of from just more than 30 percent. Congress has demanded
the reduction, but other member nations regard any reduction as a
violation of international treaty obligations.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from certain the U.S. mission will succeed, most other
diplomats say, since 188 other nations will have to agree.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation has also had to expend much diplomatic
capital this year to get the United States back on an important
U.N. budget committee, where it had lost its seat because of other
nations' anger at the U.S. failure to pay its dues.
</P>
<P>
   When any peacekeeping operation is planned, Holbrooke must hold
up a final decision by the Security Council for 15 days to notify
Congress and give members the right to object. At the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, a spokesman said that this was a
pledge made voluntarily by the Clinton administration, not a
congressional rule, and that it reflected the administration's
unwillingness to fight on Capitol Hill over issues involving the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has criticized the administration for asking Congress
for too little money in peacekeeping budget assessments. When money
is withheld, as it has been recently for missions in Africa, the
United Nations has to scramble to pay for adequate field
operations. Other Security Council members now say that they have
to take U.S. congressional notification into account even in times
of crisis, and that slows down the organization's response.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.N. officials and diplomats, including some from friendly
European nations, also say that Holbrooke has often been more eager
to act quickly in times of crisis than officials in Washington.
Last September, as violence in East Timor was raging on the day
Holbrooke arrived at the United Nations, both the Security Council
and the Clinton administration were slow to react. That left Annan
a lone voice of warning to Indonesia about the violence that
accompanied East Timor's vote to become independent.
</P>
<P>
   In May, when a botched peacekeeping operation in Sierra Leone
resulted in the capture of 500 peacekeepers by rebels, the
administration was again silent, refusing help to Annan. Diplomats
say that Holbrooke was known to have wanted some show of American
power, and perhaps logistical support for the United Nations, short
of the use of American troops. He is known to be impatient with the
work of some special envoys dispatched to trouble spots by the
White House.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite uneven patches, however, Holbrooke said in the interview
that he was convinced that relations between the United Nations and
the United States were better after visits to the organization by
Gore, several cabinet members and about 80 members of Congress.
Holbrooke organized a visit to the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee for the whole Security Council, an unheard of gesture for
both sides. Council members said they went _ a few reluctantly _ in
the hope that it would ease the gridlock with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been enormously impressed by the amount of good will
the member states have for the United States, and the desire for a
high degree of U.S. engagement,'' Holbrooke said, adding that the
United States should reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the United States will have to decide how
important this organization is, with all its flaws. The U.S. is
stronger now in the U.N., and the U.N. is stronger in the U.S. _
but we still have a way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
