</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BROWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL COLUMN: IVERSON HAUNTS BROWN, EVEN ACROSS THE PACIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Larry Brown was reminiscing recently about a much
simpler time in international competition, when an Olympic
basketball player for the United States had no one to carry his
bags during training camp in Hawaii, when you could not order
coconut shrimp as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in '64 had ever been to Hawaii that I know of,'' said
Brown, an assistant coach with the 2000 team and in 1964 a point
guard for Hank Iba's Olympic team that played in Tokyo, which also
featured Bill Bradley, Walt Hazzard and Jim Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like we got bags, jackets, shirts and shoes like
this group,'' he added. ``In '64, they hit us with a lei, put us on
a military bus and drove us to Pearl Harbor. We stayed in the
enlisted men's quarters, which was one big room. We ate in the
military mess hall, cafeteria-style.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has always been skilled at delivering in-my-day rants,
going on about the hardships and realities of old-school players.
But he is especially good on this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``To wake us up, they came in with a garbage can and a shovel
and banged on it,'' Brown said. ``That was our alarm clock. We got
on a bus to the Marine base, where we practiced on an open court.
The top was covered, but the sides were open. We had two-a-day
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Iba didn't have a curfew, but there was no way we were
going. We were too tired. Besides, they had one of those
military-police guys with a gun if you wanted to leave. We were
there for 31 straight days. We had a half a day off where we were
allowed to go to the other side of the island if we wanted to swim
or surf. A half-day in 31 days. That was my Hawaiian experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Allen and Allan Houston overheard Brown and shook their
heads in disbelief. They and 10 teammates stayed at a five-star
Maui hotel for more than a week. If they wanted, butlers drew
orchid baths for them for $50. The pool bar had some concoction
called a Lava Flow that was more dessert than drink.
</P>
<P>
   These are not college kids who have never been abroad. They are
multimillionaire basketball players, living large in paradise. They
work hard, they play hard. It is the only way Olympic officials
could get National Basketball Association All-Stars to come.
Private charters, bell men and concierges are all they have known
since they turned pro.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson would like it here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved for him to be here,'' Brown said of
Iverson, the Philadelphia 76ers point guard with whom he seems to
be locked in an eternal power struggle. ``Allen needs something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the old-school coach and the Slam magazine point
guard trying to coexist is already collecting dust. Iverson takes a
day off, Brown blows up, trade rumors swirl and, usually in less
than a week, they make up and promise to do right by each other.
Just as Brown's patience has reached its threshold, the education
of Iverson continues. For better or worse _ or until a megadeal
does them part _ this is the dance they do.
</P>
<P>
   But even across the Pacific Ocean, you can see the worry in
Brown's eyes. After all the skipped practices and insurrections, he
does not want to see Iverson, one of the most talented players in
the world, waste his gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking him to do anything that any other coach
wouldn't ask a player to do,'' said Brown, who said he had not
spoken to Iverson over the summer. ``What he said to other players
and our management is that he wants to do all those things. It's a
nonissue if he does. If he doesn't, there's no hope.''
</P>
<P>
   No hope?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's irreconcilable if he doesn't show up to practice,'' Brown
said. ``I'll lose my whole team. You ask any one of our players.
Anybody that works for you, if they're constantly late, or they
don't show up or they don't want to work. If he does the right
things, we got no problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never criticized his game or his heart. But he tells me
he wants to be the leader, the captain and a great player. And my
response to him is: `You've got control over all that. Not me.' If
any player on any team did the things that have happened in the
past with him, you got no chance. I'm hopeful that's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown will attend his team's NBA training camp the day after he
returns from the Games in Sydney, Australia, just as many of the
Olympians will. Unless a trade is swung before then, Brown will
meet up with Iverson there. He will try not to sound like the
father who tells his son how many miles he had to walk to school in
the snow.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a pivotal juncture in the career of Allen Iverson. A
bit of history may be what the future needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt his hope would be around Patrick or Alonzo or
Karl Malone,'' Brown said, citing Patrick Ewing and Alonzo
Mourning. ``It's about pitting him with a guy that has so much
respect for the game and has accomplished so much and is so
professional. He needs to see that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys are professional and I have as many warriors on my
team as anybody in the league _ respect the game, respect your
teammates _ but they don't have the reputation or the credentials
that Zo, Malone or Patrick would have. To have them to say
something to him or to show him the right way is really meaningful.
I feel bad he hasn't been exposed to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
