u s BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT &LR;      09-03 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S JUST ANOTHER WORKDAY FOR EDMONDS AS CARDINALS SWEEP METS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It has been a dream come true, Jim Edmonds said, to
play for the St. Louis Cardinals. The fans pack the park, wear the
colors and adore the players. The team wins, Edmonds produces and
everybody is happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable coming to work here every day and being a
part of something like this,'' Edmonds said.
</P>
<P>
   For the third game in a row, the Cardinals beat the Mets Sunday
on the final pitch of the game for a sweep of the three-game
series. Two of the game-winners were home runs by Edmonds, who
smashed a high fastball from Rick White into the right-field
bullpen to give St. Louis a 4-3 victory in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were elated, bouncing in unison as they swarmed
Edmonds at home plate. The Mets, who managed only five hits and are
slumbering as an offense, were frustrated _ and nobody more so than
White.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Edmonds to hit them both is even worse,'' White said.
``He's more of an `I'm-the-hero' guy instead of just, `We won.' He
likes to appease himself more than his team.'' That, White added,
is what angers him most.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds was dogged by that reputation before joining the
Cardinals in a trade from Anaheim this spring. It is a label he
said is unfair, a creation of the media, and he did not take
White's criticism seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty unfortunate that a guy who doesn't have any idea
who I am or anything about me would say something that silly,''
Edmonds said.
</P>
<P>
   White had not gotten over the home run after the game and said
he will think about it until he meets up with his family on Monday
in Cincinnati, where the Mets play the Reds. Another reunion should
lift the Mets' spirits: John Franco, out with a sore left pectoral
muscle, could be available on Monday after an encouraging bullpen
session Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets need Franco, who probably would have been pitching in
the ninth inning Friday, when Pat Mahomes gave up the game-winner
to Edmonds. The Mets could have used Franco Sunday in the eighth
inning, when Turk Wendell and Dennis Cook failed to protect a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scratched one run off Rick Ankiel Sunday and got seven
shutout innings from Glendon Rusch, who tired in the 98-degree
heat. But Wendell allowed a leadoff walk and a single in the
eighth, and Cook came in to face a pinch-hitter, Placido Polanco.
</P>
<P>
   Franco has not allowed an earned run since June 21, but Cook has
been erratic. His third pitch to Polanco was a hanging slider, and
Polanco ripped it into the left-field bullpen for a three-run homer
that gave the Cardinals a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``My slider's definitely a feel pitch,'' Cook said. ``I had a
real good one the other day. Today, I threw some good ones. The one
he hit wasn't real good at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The ineffectiveness of Wendell and Cook wasted what might have
been Rusch's best effort of the year. Rusch kept the Cardinals
off-balance with his change-up, allowing only four singles over
seven innings. No Cardinals got past first base as Rusch struck out
seven and walked none.
</P>
<P>
   But as usual, Rusch was given meager run support. Rusch has the
lowest run support of any pitcher in the majors, with just 3.54
runs per nine innings. Scoring has been especially difficult for
the Mets recently. The Mets have batted .198 since pounding Randy
Johnson and the Arizona Diamondbacks on Aug. 25, scoring 18 runs in
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through it before,'' said catcher Mike Piazza.
``Everybody wants to be the one guy that gets us over the hump.
Bubba had a great day today. Unfortunately, no one else could help
him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Bubba Trammell, making his first start since Aug.
15, was 2 for 4 and knocked in all three Mets runs. With two outs
in the ninth, belted a two-run, game-tying homer off Dave Veres, a
right-hander. Manager Bobby Valentine had left-handed options on
the bench, but he stuck with the right-handed Trammell, a power
hitter, and Trammell delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one time that you think about hitting a home run,
that'd be it,'' Trammell said. ``I was trying to drive the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Trammell's other hit Sunday was the Mets' first off Ankiel, a
rookie left-hander they had never faced before. Ankiel overpowered
them with a mid-90s fastball and a curveball tumbling in 20 miles
per hour slower, working three perfect innings to start the game
and getting six strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Ankiel and Darryl Kile had pitched the equivalent
of a perfect game over two days; Kile retired the last 18 Mets to
bat on Saturday, and Ankiel the first nine Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But after walking two in the fourth, Ankiel walked Jay Payton
with two outs in the fifth. He had Payton picked off first, but
Payton eluded the tag of second baseman Fernando Vina and slid
safely into second. That put Payton in position when Trammell
looped a curveball into center for the game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick also had two hits and Edgardo Alfonzo had one, but
the rest of the Mets' bats were dormant for another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is we haven't hit for the last week or 10 days,''
Valentine said. ``The good news is, we're going to hit a lot. We
play this brand of baseball every day for the rest of the way,
we'll be very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   A loss is a loss, said Mets first baseman Todd Zeile; walking
off the field at the end makes no difference. But the Mets and
Cardinals could meet in October, and this series has emboldened St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a little hope that if we ever run into them in the
playoffs, we'll have a chance,'' Edmonds said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
