<P>
   BUSH-STRATEGY (Austin, Texas) _ For most of the spring and
summer, with a seemingly durable advantage in polls, Bush chatted
genially with voters about his own good intentions, and his swipes
at Vice President Al Gore were fairly perfunctory. No more. As
Labor Day opens the curtain on the pivotal act in the 2000
presidential campaign and Bush confronts the evaporation of his
lead, he and his advisers say that it is no longer enough to tell
Americans why they should want the Texas governor in the White
House. By Frank Bruni.
