<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ELECTIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION APPEARS TO SWEEP PARLIAMENT SEATS IN BEIRUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite throughout w/new information, and 1st ref. to
Salam)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri dealt a
crushing electoral blow to Lebanon's Syrian-appointed government in
final parliamentary voting on Sunday, early results showed,
sweeping all of Beirut's seats and gaining a powerful majority of
backers in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In a modern, extravagantly financed campaign the likes of which
this traditionally clan-dominated city had never seen, thousands of
the swashbuckling multibillionaire's supporters swarmed the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri's campaigners were clustered on street corners throughout
the city all day, clad in blue, green and tan T-shirts bearing his
visage. Twelve hours of criss-crossing the city turned up only four
workers in orange T-shirts distributing cards for his Sunni Muslim
rival, Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
   Official vote totals are to be announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighteen of eighteen.'' Salim Diab, Hariri's campaign manager,
said in his headquarters an hour after the polls closed, indicating
they had won all the seats contested, as supporters danced and
cheered outside.
</P>
<P>
   While the voting in one of the bitterest campaigns ever here was
far from eliminating Syria's hold on Lebanon _ since all of the
major figures here, not least Hariri himself, have ties to Damascus
_ it appears to have drastically altered the political status quo.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Hariri defeated the two men handpicked as Lebanon's
leaders two years ago by Bashar Assad, the untried 34-year-old heir
to Syrian power, during his internship here in preparation for
assuming the mantle of his father, Hafez Assad, who had run both
countries with wily, ruthless skill.
</P>
<P>
   President Emile Lahoud, the Maronite Catholic former military
commander whom the young Assad chose to be president in 1998,
detests Hariri and mounted a strong campaign with all the
government's resources against him, including hours of denunciation
on the state-run television station.
</P>
<P>
   And Hoss, the sitting prime minister and a political fixture for
decades, lost his seat in Parliament despite efforts by Syria to
gerrymander Beirut into three electoral districts and guarantee his
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional political wisdom here was that tradition _
along with Syria's desire to see a number of possibly contending
Sunni Muslim leaders _ would make safe the seats of Hoss and of
Tamman Salam, the son of the late Saab Salam, the longtime zaim, or
leader, of Beirut's major family and a former prime minister,
himself.
</P>
<P>
   But, in what many analysts see as the most significant measure
of Hariri's victory, both Hoss and Salam, according to the early
results, were swept away in the landslide.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stunning political turnaround. Only a month and a half
ago, political pundits here were writing that Lahoud was hoping for
a two-thirds majority in Parliament so that the Constitution could
be amended to extend his six-year term, which expires in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with the battering the government took in last week's
round of elections _ with 41 of 63 seats going to the opposition _
and today's voting for the 128-seat body, he is faced with the
prospect of either accepting, or trying to find a way around
naming, his sworn enemy, Hariri, as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 18 seats Hariri appeared to have won in
Beirut _ along with the remaining 19th seat he gained in a backroom
deal with the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah on Friday _ he is expected to
be supported by 23 winning candidates on the joint Amal-Hezbollah
ticket in southern Lebanon and at least a dozen more from the Bekaa
region in today's voting.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 Taif agreement that helped end the 15-year civil war
here says that the president must appoint the prime minister with
the support of a simple majority of Parliament. And the removal of
Hoss and Salam from the political scene puts Lahoud and the Syrians
in a further bind. Under the unwritten National Accord here, the
prime minister must be a Sunni Muslim and the alternative pool of
prominent candidates is now sharply reduced.
</P>
</TEXT>
