<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BURNING-MAN0904-COX     09-03 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNING-MAN0904-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Counterculture thrives at Burning Man festival
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACK ROCK CITY, Nev. _ The Man is in flames and thousands dance
around the pyre. Luminescent fish swim through the desert air. Drum
choirs and techno music pound contrapuntal polyrhythms. Green
lasers undulate high overhead, illuminating the mountain ranges six
miles distant. And Dr. MegaVolt stands between his truck-mounted
Tesla coils, absorbing million-volt sparks into his body.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Richards, from Decatur, Ga., observes the scene with
undisguised glee and raises his voice in a brief salute of
thanksgiving: ``There is a counterculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Very counter. This is Burning Man. And unlike your grandfather's
meek, Thoreauvian alternative society, these folks aren't satisfied
with quietly contemplating the natural world. Burning Man goes to
the wilderness and rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong Burning Man art festival, which drew about 37,000
hardy souls to the second biggest empty place in the Northern
Hemisphere, and climaxed this Labor Day weekend, is tough to
characterize. Imagine a conglomeration of artists, ravers, bohos
and techies. Now place them in the forbidding Black Rock desert,
two hours northeast of Reno, a 400-square-mile alkali plain, devoid
of life, buffeted by 70 mph winds, baked in the day to a 100-degree
crispness and frozen at night.
</P>
<P>
   Now provide them with enormous disposable income from the
Internet boom, and sprinkle with creativity and a pinch of
psychoactive chemistry. The result is a 24-hour-a-day party in a
tent-city Shangri La, where ostentation takes the form of wild
clothing _ or no clothing _ spectacular art installations, and a
sustained effort to make each other laugh.
</P>
<P>
   For its week of existence this encampment, called Black Rock
City, is the sixth biggest municipality in Nevada. It has its own
post office (which stays open ``until we're too drunk to cancel
stamps,'' says one volunteer postal worker), its own newspaper,
public safety force and Department of Public Works, and provides
most city services. But bring your own water.
</P>
<P>
   Burning Man almost turned into Raining Man this year, with an
unseasonable sustained downpour Friday evening, which, combined
with chilly temperatures, drove some revelers back to their tents.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, says artist Charlie Smith. ``It made people put
their clothes back on,'' he shrugs. The party continued.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is in the center of the nine-square-mile encampment, a
clearing that is dotted with monumental sculpture and
installations, arrayed in a kind of Mall radiating out from the
commanding 50-foot wooden effigy known simply as The Man. He is
inspecting his own contribution, a 21-foot, two-ton sheet metal
heart, heated by a wood-fired cauldron to a red-hot glow. Smith
crafted the structure in an Atlanta warehouse, and with the help of
collaborator Syd Klinge, shipped it west in 50 pieces, and
reassembled it here. ``Can you think of a better place to show
sculpture?'' asks the burly 34-year-old. ``This is the gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, there is trouble in paradise. The federal Bureau of
Land Management, which leases the site to the Burning Man
corporation, has steadily raised its fees and regulations. Some
naysayers fret about the environmental impact of event, and vow to
block Burning Man 2001. And as the group has grown from its humble
origins in 1986, when San Francisco artist Larry Harvey burned an
8-foot effigy in front of a group of about 40 friends, its nature
has changed from wild and woolly rebels to a highly controlled
mini-community.
</P>
<P>
   It's safer, says Austin Richards, aka Dr. MegaVolt, who
remembers the days when more hard-core participants roamed the
playa with their own flame-throwers, and the amusements included a
drive-by firing range.
</P>
<P>
   Now weapons are banned. Also campfires, explosives and urinating
on the playa. But Richards, a high-energy physicist from Santa
Barbara, Calif., is doing his part to bring back danger. He and his
15-person crew roam the event at night, donning metal suits,
harmlessly absorbing spectacular 15-foot arcs from their twin
coils, sometimes holding blocks of wood or stuffed animals that
burst into flame in their arms.
</P>
<P>
   Says Peter Richards, who is the Dr.'s fiftysomething daddy, and
a teacher, ``I am very proud of my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Other concerns: Success. ``Are dot.com yuppies ruining Burning
Man?'' asks the headline in an alternative publication. Certainly
they are building bigger and wilder theme camps, like the Space
Cowboy encampment, with its gasoline-powered margarita blender.
</P>
<P>
   Such debate wouldn't occur in most other cultural institutions,
where more money is always better, but founder Harvey has high
ideals for this event. He sees it as a way to change passive
consumers into active participants, in a place where experience is
no longer bought and sold, but created.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, almost nothing (but ice and coffee) is for sale
in Black Rock City. It is a gift economy, says Harvey, where
commerce is replaced by self-reliance. ``Try to live without
commerce'' in the real world, he told Reason magazine earlier this
year. ``Good luck. You'll be dead in a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, at Burning Man you really do encounter people
struggling to give things away. ``Waitresses'' in starched aprons
offer canapes to passers-by on the main esplanade. Bay-area lawyer
Robin Hopkins hands out iron-on transfers from her encampment, and
offers a generator-powered iron to do the job with. The
ever-popular Freezing Man plies the boulevards in his van, handing
out popsicles and ice cream sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   The van is one of the few motor vehicles allowed on the playa by
the Department of Mutant Vehicles. Only art cars are allowed, like
the three-wheeler that resembles a Jules Verne submarine, or the
60-foot fire-breathing dragon, or the very comfortable
battery-driven sofa, that will do 15 mph when the way is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it is all things not boring suburbia,'' says Erik
Haagensen, 29, of Atlanta, relaxing in a handsome wooden yurt with
fellow Atlantan Luba Sharapan, 30.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the playa _ a prehistoric lake bed so flat that the
curvature of the earth is visible _ Burning Man's participants
cheer and amble, each outdoing the other in costume. Electro
luminescent wire is the decoration of choice this year. Some have
decorated themselves and their bicycles, towing homemade billboards
embroidered with glowing animals. In the dark the bicycles
disappear; one sees a school of iridescent fish darting through the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Richards is rightfully boggled by the scene. If this event
were a band, he knows what he'd call it: ``Thirty Thousand
Maniacs.''
</P>
<P>
   Discover Burning Man: http://www.burningman.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
