<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-STRATEGY-ART-2TA     09-03 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-STRATEGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S NEWFOUND CONFIDENCE TEMPERED BY THE HURDLES AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla., Pa., Ohio, Mich.) (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Vice President Al Gore begins the fall stretch of
the presidential campaign buoyant in the polls and brimming with
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strongest sign of this self-assurance is the Gore
campaign's visible grab for Florida, a state that has been
perceived as pro-Bush for months and where Bush's brother Jeb is
the governor. Gore operatives say they are now slightly ahead in
Florida. Gore has visited the state twice in the last week and is
popping into Tampa on Monday morning during his 24-hour whirlwind
Labor Day tour.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, advisers said, either Gore or Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, Gore's running mate, will visit Florida at least once a
week from now through the November election, as they will regularly
visit other battleground states that are becoming increasingly more
plausible for the Democrats: Pennsylvania, Ohio and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   And while the campaign has already bought television time in
three swing markets in Florida _ Tampa, Orlando and West Palm Beach
_ it is also planning a big investment in Miami, Tallahassee and
other areas as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we turn on the lights there,'' said one top Democrat,
``watch out!''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the Gore team is pumped and basking in
a spate of positive media coverage. But its newfound euphoria is
tempered with caution. There are tricky shoals for Gore to
navigate, and the campaign has some important decisions to make.
These concern how he will respond to attacks from Bush, how to
present himself as a change from President Clinton even while
advocating many of Clinton's policies, and how to counter voters'
impression that Gore is weaker on certain personality traits.
</P>
<P>
   A memorandum from Hickman-Brown Research Inc., a firm that polls
for the Gore campaign, says that Gore has made strides in important
ways: His personal popularity is up, it says; voters agree with his
positions on most issues that are most important to them and have
more faith in him than in Bush to carry out certain presidential
duties, like managing foreign policy and preparing the country for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum also says that Gore has shown major improvements
in some areas of vulnerability. The pollsters refer to these as
``key personal dimensions,'' which they define as traits related to
leadership and trustworthiness, although Republicans still perceive
Gore as vulnerable on matters of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is an aggressive opponent, flush with cash, and he has
already demonstrated that he will not lie down for a Gore
steamrollering. The Republicans, who have spent twice as much as
Gore on television commercials, are on the air now skewering Gore's
credibility on improving the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is also stepping up his criticism that the Clinton
administration has squandered the opportunities of the last eight
years. Republicans say that new commercials in the works show
Clinton making the same promises in 1992 _ for a middle-class tax
cut, for a prescription drug benefit for the elderly _ that Gore is
making today.
</P>
<P>
   How severely _ and how soon _ should Gore respond? He has a
reputation as a cutthroat competitor whose aggressiveness can fire
up the partisans but alienate independents and swing voters. The
Gore team is deploying countless surrogates, including Lieberman,
to make the case against Bush. But there is some internal debate
about the level on which Gore should engage.
</P>
<P>
   His challenge last week that Bush should ``put up or shut up'' _
an attempt to goad the governor into being more specific on his
policy proposals _ was ridiculed by the Bush campaign as a
playground taunt, but gave a hint of Gore's eagerness to get in the
fight. The Democrats also withheld a commercial they had prepared
last week criticizing Bush's record in Texas. That is likely to be
broadcast in the coming week.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most nettlesome question for the Gore campaign is
how to take advantage of the humming economy. In times of peace and
prosperity, the incumbent party is almost always rewarded. The good
news for the Gore campaign is that internal polling suggests that
in several important states, a majority of voters perceive the
nation to be on the right track. This has historically been one of
the most important indicators for whether or not incumbents are
re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   But for Gore to have climbed to his place in the polls only now
suggests that other factors are at work. The central concern is
that while voters appreciate the good times, there is lingering
resentment toward Clinton over his personal behavior, creating a
complex web of emotion that seems to ensnare Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Allan J. Lichtman, a political analyst at American University
who has written about the basic factors on which people vote, said:
``The fundamentals are in Gore's favor. Peace, prosperity,
tranquillity at home and a united incumbent party. Why has the race
even been close? The Clinton scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster, said that of all the issues
that voters rank as important, one, declining moral values, hurts
Gore the most. ``This is the aftereffect of impeachment,'' Goeas
said. ``Voters didn't want Republicans to impeach Clinton because
they thought it would rock the boat. Now that that is no longer an
issue, they are indulging in a second emotion _ they didn't want
Clinton impeached, but they think what he did was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Gore pay for that? He has worked hard to close the Clinton
chapter, staging a ``passing of the baton'' ceremony before his
convention last month and declaring himself in his acceptance
speech his ``own man.'' Still, the centerpiece of his campaign is
the thriving economy, and the economy is the most sterling part of
the Clinton legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are often open to change, but there are questions about
how much change Gore actually represents. He says he is not running
for a third Clinton term, and yet he has vowed to continue much of
the Clinton doctrine and certainly the current prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is not an award for past performance,'' Gore
told workers at a construction site here Sunday. ``I'm not asking
you to vote for me on the basis of the economy we had; I'm asking
for your support on the basis of the better, fairer, stronger
economy that we're going to create together over the next four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The coming week should reveal more of the Gore strategy as the
vice president focuses on the economy, including in a major speech
in Cleveland on Wednesday. His economic speeches this year _
drafted with the help of Clinton's former treasury secretary,
Robert Rubin _ have emphasized fiscal discipline and paying down
the debt. This has reflected the centrist ``New Democrat'' approach
advanced by Clinton. Over the last several weeks the vice president
has relentlessly pounded a populist theme that analysts said has
raised questions for some voters about whether he wants to go back
to old-style big-government spending and the financing of programs
for the poor.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Gore's current strategy is to stick to the issues, and to try to
make the campaign about the issues on which he has an advantage.
Internal polling suggests that undecided voters side with Gore on
health care, Social Security and the economy. They side with Bush
on crime and moral values, and in many states rate the candidates
about even on education.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials indicated that they were not so worried
about the lack of support on crime, noting that it is not as big an
issue as it was in 1992, it is not an issue that swing voters are
making their decisions on, and few voters think Gore has had
anything to do with crime rates anyway, so it is not very fertile
ground for him.
</P>
<P>
   But declining moral values is another matter. Gore is well aware
of this, and it goes a long way toward explaining why he picked
Lieberman, with his reputation for rectitude and his history of
criticism of Clinton's personal behavior, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Goeas, the Republican pollster, said that education and values
ranked as the two top issues for married women, and that married
women, who make up 60 percent of female voters, tended to support
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has done a good job of, at worst, neutralizing education,
but he is overwhelmingly ahead on moral values,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tad Devine, a chief strategist for the Gore campaign, said that
at this point the campaign was trying to reach as broad an audience
as possible. Over the next few weeks, he said, different groups of
people will click in to the election, and they will be
``persuadable'' at different times. He said the campaign was
talking about broad themes now, but as the pool of persuadable
voters shifted and shrank, the campaign would deliver its message
more to specific audiences, largely through direct-mail letters,
radio advertising (which reaches more identifiable groups of voters
than television does) and campaign destinations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
