<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-GUATEMALA-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McBRIDE'S GOAL POWERS U.S. OVER GUATEMALA  
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two strategic substitutions by U.S. coach Bruce
Arena turned out for the best and for the worst in a World Cup
qualifying game Sunday afternoon against Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   The insertion of Cobi Jones paid the highest dividend. He
created the game's only goal, with a perfect cross to Brian
McBride, in the United States' 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The victory came before a sellout crowd at RFK Stadium and put
the Americans a step closer to advancing to the regional finals.
That six-nation round-robin tournament next year will decide the
three nations that will represent the North and Central American
and Caribbean region in the 2002 World Cup finals in Japan and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who entered the game in the 57th minute, took a pass from
Jovan Kirovski on the right flank. He accelerated to the penalty
area and then crossed the ball to McBride at the far post, who
scored from 6 yards with a low, left-footed shot in the 72nd
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a goal,'' Arena said of his decision to insert Jones
for Tony Sanneh and Eddie Lewis for Ernie Stewart. The United
States then went to a 3-5-2 formation _ three defenders, five
midfielders and two forwards _ after having used a 4-4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was ejected seven minutes after he entered for a violent
foul on Guatemala's Fabricio Benitez. His ejection left the
Americans a man short against a well disciplined and determined
Guatemala defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``One change worked, the other didn't,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones found a way to make the right play after the Americans had
failed repeatedly to come up with the right formula to beat the
Guatemalan defense and goalkeeper Edgar Estrada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cobi basically made a perfect ball,'' McBride said of the
pass. ``He teased the goalkeeper a little to the point he had to
come out and left me with an easy job.''
</P>
<P>
   It was McBride's second goal of this qualifying round, and 13th
in 45 international appearances for the United States. He scored
the team's only goal in the 2-1 loss to Iran in the 1998 World Cup
that left the Americans last among the 32 countries in France.
</P>
<P>
   The United States (2-1-1) is second in its regional semifinal
group with seven points. Costa Rica (3-1), which posted a 3-0
victory Sunday over Barbados, is first with nine points. Guatemala
(1-2-1) is third with four points. The Americans have two games
left in the group, against Costa Rica (Oct. 11 in Columbus, Ohio)
and at Barbados (1-3) on Nov. 15. The top two teams will qualify
for the regional finals.
</P>
<P>
   Before McBride scored, the Americans had little offensive
success. Their crosses from the flanks were elementary to defend
and they were losing their air battles at both ends of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Arena decided to start Kirovski in place of Jones because he
wanted to have the flexibility of changing strategies during the
game. ``Jovan is the most natural-looking player who can become a
third forward if we decide to change tactics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great win for our confidence,'' Arena added.
``Guatemala is a tough team to break down. It was a great play by
Cobi on the goal. We expected this to be a 1-0 game. The crowd was
also 50-50, and it was good for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
