<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS SHOW UNEXPECTED FLASH AMID THUNDER AND LIGHTNING 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Given the customary symbolism affixed to
season-opening games, the Giants' season debut Sunday was not
particularly nouveau in style nor stylishly notable. In the Arizona
Cardinals, the favored Giants recognized a team in disarray and
quickly stomped to a large early lead they gingerly protected in a
21-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Giants, a team with few achievements in recent
seasons, there was an execution of purpose _ and an unexpected
flash _ within Sunday's solid, clean victory at Giants Stadium. The
Giants may have defeated a team that could be the least proficient
of any Giants opponent this season, but there is always some credit
to following a plan as designed.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had set out to run the football and gained 223
rushing yards, the most in three years. They had set out to win the
turnover battle, and they created four while committing just two
turnovers of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line, a fidgety, unsure lot that disrupted the
offense's rhythm with its penalties and breakdowns last season, did
not have a penalty and did not yield a sack. The defense sagged
late but stuffed the Cardinals early, holding them to three points
in the first three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the thunder and lightning. Above Giants Stadium
Sunday, with a bolt and a crash, it appeared to the west of Giants
Stadium, bringing about a 23-minute delay of the game in the early
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the new grass field of the stadium, the self-labeled Thunder
and Lightning combination of Giants running backs Ron Dayne and
Tiki Barber scored three touchdowns. Barber had the Giants first
two scores, one on a crazy-legged touchdown dash from sideline to
sideline and another on a 78-yard burst up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play to win the game and that's what we did,'' said Giants
Coach Jim Fassel, who is now undefeated in four season openers. ``I
know there were things that didn't go exactly right at the end.
We'll work on that. But let's not forget all the good parts of the
game, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the Giants, the best part is they didn't flop in a game
they probably couldn't afford to lose. Not with the Philadelphia
Eagles, who overpowered the Cowboys in Dallas Sunday, playing host
to the Giants next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is that we beat a team we were supposed to
beat,'' said Lomas Brown, the Giants new, but 15-year veteran, left
tackle. ``Yeah, we've got to play better. But this is a big first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants played with poise and confidence from the beginning
Sunday - at least until the fourth quarter _ and showed cohesion
that belied all the turnover on the roster. Compared with their
starting lineup in last year's opening game, there were nine new
starters. But the Giants looked tight, sending an early message
when they sent the Cardinals off the field after just three plays
as the game dawned. Offensively, the Giants moved the football
early, taking a lead they never relinquished on their second
possession.
</P>
<P>
   On that 66-yard, 10-play drive, Giants quarterback Kerry
Collins, who completed 17 of 25 passes for 172 yards, converted on
consecutive third-down plays with a 24-yard pass to Ike Hilliard
and a 13-yard screen pass to fullback Greg Comella. Barber and
Dayne, who had 78 yards on 23 rushing carries, brought the Giants
to the Cardinals' 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Barber then took a toss to the right but found a host of
Cardinals waiting for him. Barber said he followed his instincts,
which meant reversing his field to the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk and reward type of thing when you do that,''
Barber said.
</P>
<P>
   Barber's speed, brought on in part by added strength and a few
less pounds, reduced the risk. He outraced two Arizona defenders to
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, after an 11-yard pass from Collins
to wide receiver Amani Toomer eased the Cardinals safeties off the
line of scrimmage slightly, the Giants gave the ball to Barber
again, this time on a quick slant to the right side.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' remade offensive line, which steadily protected
Collins and opened a variety of holes for the running game,
provided Barber an impressive gap to run through. Barber dashed
between center Dusty Zeigler and right guard Ron Stone _ with right
tackle Luke Petitgout sealing the outside. Barber out-ran
cornerbacks Aeneas Williams and Tom Knight to the end zone, the
78-yard scoring play the fourth-longest running play in team
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm getting a little faster in my old age,'' said
Barber, who added that he expected to have a big day. ``I hope to
have 15 more big days.''
</P>
<P>
   It is part of the Giants strategy, if all goes as designed, that
Barber can help the Giants get a lead and Dayne can help them
protect it. To that end, Dayne saved his best running between the
tackles for the fourth quarter. And on the final play of a 15-play
drive, Dayne powered in over right guard for a 7-yard touchdown
that gave the Giants a 21-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we saw a little of what Ron can do for us,'' Fassel
said of Dayne, who had 36 yards on six attempts on the last
touchdown drive. ``And he'll get better.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Giants took their 18-point lead, the Cardinals began
to take more chances _ and the Giants played more prevent defense.
That combination led to two touchdown passes from Arizona
quarterback Jake Plummer to wide receiver David Boston, the second
coming with just 39 seconds remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's two touchdown passes did not negate his three
interceptions, and though he threw for 318 yards while completing
28 of 49 passes, it did not make up for an otherwise sloppy game by
the Cardinals offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a game that we controlled,'' Giants linebacker
Jessie Armstead said. ``We needed that. Opening day is about
getting off on the right foot and feeling good about yourself. We
got both those things done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
