<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILITARY-READINESS-2T     09-03 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-READINESS-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING MILITARY'S COMBAT READINESS TILTS AT WINDMILL OF
BUREAUCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush kicked off a heated
political debate when he declared that two of the Army's 10 active
divisions were ``not ready for duty, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he wanted to highlight the complexities of measuring
military readiness, however, he could have looked closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   The 49th Armored Division of the Texas National Guard _
nominally under the governor's command _ has the lowest ranking for
war-time readiness that the Pentagon gives, according to military
officials. It has been that way for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the Pentagon disputes that its active-duty forces
are not ready for combat, the 49th Guard Division's case reveals a
far more difficult question about the overall state of the American
military. It involves an arcane, sometimes subjective readiness
accounting system that can be misleading and is not easily reduced
to the sound bites of a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush and his running mate on the Republican ticket, Dick
Cheney, the former defense secretary, who has joined heartily in
the criticism, do not dispute that the American military is
technologically advanced, highly trained and well equipped.
</P>
<P>
   The real question, and one that the candidates on both sides
have only glanced on, is how the next administration intends to
prepare its forces, and for what and where.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not if you're ready,'' as a senior military officer at
the Pentagon put it, ``it's what you're ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in assessing the state of today's military is
that the Pentagon's system for measuring readiness ultimately
measures only one thing: fighting a major ground war with air and
naval support. Any units doing anything else _ and thus not
preparing for that worst case _ can run afoul of the system's
subjective but merciless readiness classifications.
</P>
<P>
   And so the two divisions cited by Bush _ the 10th Mountain and
the 1st Mechanized Infantry _ were briefly classified as unready
for war last fall, not because they suffered from budget cuts and
low morale, as Bush suggested, but rather because large parts of
the divisions were keeping peace in Bosnia and Kosovo, according to
Army and Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that it counts if you're training to fight Saddam,
but doesn't count if you're actually deploying deterring Milosevic
or containing conflict in the Balkans is a strange artifact of our
national military strategy, and makes little sense,'' said Michael
O'Hanlon, a defense analyst at the Brookings Institute in
Washington who has informally consulted for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For the 49th Guard Division in Texas, the meager readiness
rating it holds may not be the best indicator of its ability to
conduct military operations. According to the Pentagon's system,
the 49th is unfit to fight a war. Since March, however, nearly 700
men and women of the 49th, including its headquarters company and
most of its commanders, have overseen the American sector of NATO's
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia and, by all accounts, doing it
well.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the 49th is sending roughly 300 more combat troops to
Bosnia. In October, the Texas Air National Guard is sending the
unit Bush once served in, the 111th Fighter Squadron, to patrol the
no-fly zone over southern Iraq, where American pilots are routinely
responding to Iraqi antiaircraft fire with air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sort of combat the unit never saw when Bush trained as
a fighter pilot in the Texas National Guard during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Pentagon's accounting system serves a purpose,
which is to prioritize dollars for the armed services and their
combat units. The system's ratings are based on the national
military strategy, which since Cheney was secretary of defense has
called on the military to be prepared to fight and win two major
regional wars _ for example, in the Persian Gulf and on the Korean
peninsula _ at nearly the same time.
</P>
<P>
   On that scale, the Pentagon's latest quarterly readiness report
to Congress, issued last week, concluded that ``most major combat
and key support forces are ready to meet assigned taskings,
although there are force readiness and capability shortfalls that
increase risk in executing operations.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hillen, a retired Army captain who has served as a defense
policy adviser to the Bush campaign, said, ``These things are so
eminently capricious and fungible that the readiness ratings are
not really significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were a lawyer,'' Hillen said, ``you could say that,
technically, both sides are right.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the two-war scenario, the Army would need all 10 of its
active divisions, supplemented by units from the Army Reserve and
the National Guard, to satisfy the plans. That is the standard by
which the divisions are measured for readiness, but it is one that
ignores how the Army is using its forces today, and how it is
likely to keep doing so, whoever is elected in November.
</P>
<P>
   The oddity of the readiness measuring system is that forces
involved in actual military operations score lower under it. After
the Persian Gulf War in 1991, several Air Force squadrons returned
home only to be classified as unready since they had not been doing
the training that had to be checked off to qualify as ready. Never
mind that those squadrons had just returned from waging one of the
most successful air campaigns in history.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the Army is keeping peace in Bosnia or Kosovo, or
conducting exercises in Kuwait, or fighting fires in the Western
United States, those units will not be doing what it takes to meet
the system's highest standards for the war plans. After an extended
peacekeeping mission, for example, it can take months for units to
regain the highest level of readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You face very different scenarios in a peacekeeping mission,''
said one Army officer involved in monitoring readiness. ``You're
not going to move, attack and defend the way you have to in the
war-fighting mission. Those are skills that have to be practiced
over and over again until they're almost subconscious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army, like the other services, has begun to address the
problem by relying more heavily than ever on the National Guard and
Reserves. But because the Army's eight Guard divisions are not, for
now, in the nation's war plans, they have received a lower priority
when it comes to financing for equipment and training. The Army
does not expect them to be at the highest level of readiness.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Guard's 49th Division slipped to the lowest level three
years ago because of shortages in training time, equipment and
personnel, according to officials in Texas and Washington. Even
though he is commander in chief of the Texas National Guard, Bush
has little impact on the 49th's readiness, since the state provides
only 5 percent of the Guard's budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the 49th's deployment to Bosnia has freed up another
division to concentrate on the war mission. By the time the 29th
Infantry Division from Virginia takes over the American sector in
Bosnia, almost all the American troops in Bosnia will be
reservists, compared with 25 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has gone even further, proposing to include Guard
divisions in the war plans. That would relieve the strain on the
active divisions, but it could cost billions of dollars since the
Guard divisions would have to bring themselves up to a higher level
of readiness.
</P>
<P>
   So far in the campaign, neither Bush nor his Democratic
opponent, Vice President Al Gore, has proposed ways to address the
fundamental problems, at least as measured by the traditional
readiness accounting system. Bush has proposed increasing the
modernization budget by $20 billion to design, building new weapons
systems, and raising pay and benefits by $1 billion, or nearly $750
for each person in uniform. Gore, too, has proposed increasing
benefits for the troops.
</P>
<P>
   While those address problems like increasing morale or creating
new weapons, they do little to fix the problems outlined by Cheney
this week. Daily needs like spare parts and training rarely receive
attention from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And no one in either campaign has talked about the easiest
solution. If the next administration decided to change the national
military strategy, concluding that two major wars were not very
likely to happen at once, the question about whether forces are
ready would disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fix the problem,'' Hillen said, ``by changing the way
you measure it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0057 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     09-03 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA-ARUM RIFF IS JUST BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago that Oscar De la Hoya gave Bob Arum
his Olympic gold medal one emotional evening to thank the promoter
for his role in the fighter's phenomenal success.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, De La Hoya sued Arum to end their eight-year
association.
</P>
<P>
   During that eight years, Arum often described De La Hoya as one
of the best people he's encountered in a nasty business.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he used expletives to describe the one-time Golden
Boy and cited a character flaw: Lack of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Sad? Perhaps. Surprising? Not really. De La Hoya is that greedy
and Arum that egotistical.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya apparently was livid over recent comments made by
Arum suggesting the fighter should retire. And, although Arum said
he never meant to suggest such a thing, De La Hoya's reaction is
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya also wasn't too happy with anyone immediately after
Shane Mosley outpointed him in June. He implied irrationally that
the fight was fixed in Mosley's favor so those associated with the
promotion would reap another windfall for a lucrative rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Logic says he was referring to Arum, at least as much as anyone
else. Arum said the two haven't spoken since the day after the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   However, for De La Hoya, this appears to be more about business
than any perceived slights.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya had been trying to wriggle out of the contract (which
has three years remaining) long before the comments about
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He'd been trying for some time to buy his contract _ reportedly
for $3 million _ but Arum has refused to let go. In effect, the
lawsuit was the last resort to gain complete control of his own
destiny and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time De La Hoya has done such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mittleman and Steve Nelson came up with more money than
they'd ever seen _ $1 million _ to become De La Hoya's first
managers after the 1992 Olympics. About 1 1/2 years later, De La
Hoya came to the realization they were making a lot of money that
could be going into his pocket and did the logical thing: He paid
them off to get rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, De La Hoya came to the same realization with Arum.
</P>
<P>
   He's made a lot of money with Arum, more than $100 million in
ring earnings. Arum said De La Hoya walked away with $45 million
for his last three bouts alone. Their 80-20 split of the profits, a
stipulation since they renegotiated their contract in 1997, means
Arum made in the neighborhood of $11 million for those fights.
</P>
<P>
   A comment De La Hoya made after the decision to let Mittleman
and Nelson go comes to mind. It went something like this: ``I'm
paying these guys all this money for what? Making a few phone
calls?''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, De La Hoya doesn't believe he needs Arum to make
phone calls any longer: He remains one of the most marketable
athletes in the world _ even though he's lost his last two
significant bouts _ and figures he can make plenty as a freelance
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Arum doesn't really need De La Hoya, either.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most successful promoters in boxing history is a
multimillionaire himself. He doesn't really need the money De La
Hoya offered him to break the contract, the money he might make if
he sues De La Hoya for breach of contract or the money he might've
made in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Arum's primary motivation apparently is this: He doesn't want to
be just another employee of sorts whom De La Hoya discards because
he's deemed no longer useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't do that to me,'' Arum said. ``I'm going to fight them
tooth and nail. And he's gonna end up realizing that in time he's
going to pay for what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   So who's the bad guy? Neither, really.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is a businessman and the business world is a tough
place, particularly when millions of dollars are involved. Sure, he
could continue to earn ungodly sums with Arum. He simply believes
he could make more on his own _ however misguided that might be and
it's his right to try.
</P>
<P>
   He could be criticized for failing to honor a contract he
signed. However, he has plenty of company: How many other athletes
have tried to get out of a contract in search of more money?
</P>
<P>
   Arum? Well, he's one of boxing's great promoters. Again, he's
not going to let some punk kid (a term he's probably used in the
last several days) push him around. Can you blame him?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this whole thing is just part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   TIME RUNNING OUT: De La Hoya still would like to fight Mosley in
January. However, it doesn't appear this mess will be cleaned up in
time for that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley probably will fight Arturo Gatti in December and De La
Hoya a few months after that, assuming the conflict with Arum is
solved.
</P>
<P>
   MITCH HALPERN: What drove one of the world's top referees, Mitch
Halpern, to suicide remains unclear, as police have released few
details.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern, divorced about a year ago and the father of a
4-year-old girl, apparently was engaged at the time of his death.
It appears a quarrel with his fiancee might've played a role in the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern had refereed about 90 world-title fights since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   RABBIT PUNCHES: Mosley has been named fighter of the year by The
World Boxing Hall of Fame for a second time. Mosley's father, Jack
Mosley, is trainer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, Mosley has beaten Wilfredo Rivera, Willy Wise and De La
Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a lot to me,'' Shane Mosley said. ``It's a step in
the right direction as far as making history. Me and my father
winning the awards I think is just great.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The Vernon Forrest-Raul Frank fight, which ended as a no-contest
after Frank was accidentally cut by a head butt on the Fernando
Vargas-Ross Thompson undercard two weeks ago, will be rescheduled
for late this year or early 2001, Main Events said. ...
</P>
<P>
   Main Events will end the year with a bang: The promotional firm
will co-promote three major pay-per-view fights in October,
November and December: Andrew Golota-Mike Tyson, Lennox Lewis-David
Tua and Vargas-Felix Trinidad. ...
</P>
<P>
   An excellent Showtime card is set for Sept. 16 in Las Vegas. The
fights: William Joppy-Hacine Cherifi, Fabrice Tiozzo-Virgil Hill,
Joel Casamayor-Radford Beasley and Sharmba Mitchell-Felix Flores.
</P>
<P>
   The card is so deep, only highlights of the Mitchell-Flores
fight will be shown on TV. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Ayala-Johnny Tapia rematch a 10-round non-title bout _
is set for Oct. 7 on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Their first fight, won by Ayala, was fight of the year in 1999.
...
</P>
<P>
   Gatti is scheduled to face unbeaten Joe Hutchinson on Friday in
Montreal. The fight is on ESPN2. ...
</P>
<P>
   Undefeated heavyweight Clifford Etienne faces Cliff Couser in
the featured bout on HBO's ``KO Nation'' on Saturday afternoon.
Also, Bronco McKart faces Winky Wright. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Michael Rosenthal's boxing column appears Mondays in the Daily
News. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
