<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-STRATEGY-ART-2TA     09-03 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STRATEGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH LEAD GONE, BUSH TURNS FOCUS TO REFINING ATTACKS ON GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For most of the spring and summer, with a
seemingly durable advantage in the polls, Gov. George W. Bush
chatted genially with voters about his own good intentions, and his
swipes at Vice President Al Gore were fairly perfunctory. When Gore
belittled him, Bush expressed something akin to bemusement.
</P>
<P>
   No more. As Labor Day opens the curtain on the pivotal act in
the 2000 presidential campaign and Bush confronts the evaporation
of his lead, he and his advisers said that it is no longer enough
to tell Americans why they should want the Texas governor in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Voters must also be convinced that they do not want Gore there.
And that is precisely what the Bush campaign intends to do, as it
readjusts and adapts its strategy to the higher stakes of the race
and the relentless ticking of the clock.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews over the last few days, Republican officials tied
to the Bush campaign said that a new Republican television
commercial last week that cast Gore as an untrustworthy, untruthful
chameleon was a harbinger of similar salvos to be fired over the
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   And it signaled what will be a generally heightened
aggressiveness by the Bush campaign, apparent Sunday at a news
conference here in which Bush sought to gain the upper hand on the
debate over presidential debates, which Gore has been winning.
</P>
<P>
   With nine weeks until Election Day, Bush's advisers said that
they would also begin picking apart and poking holes in Gore's
policies more assiduously and raising more pointed questions about
his leadership abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are left after the conventions are the hard
sells,'' said Karl Rove, the chief strategist for the Bush
campaign, referring to the small, crucial cluster of undecided
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are no longer going to be driven just by the exposition
of a positive agenda,'' Rove said. ``They're going to say, `That's
fine, but how does that differ from the other guy's?' And that
means drawing sharp distinctions and differences in an appropriate
way.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Bush this week begins discussing a plan for prescription
drug benefits under the Medicare program, he will not simply
promote his ideas, his advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   He will also tell senior citizens that Gore's proposal, which
involves more federal regulation, smacks of nationalized health
care and represents a bid for ``the government to be their
pharmacist,'' said Karen Hughes, the campaign's director of
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes was previewing more than a sound bite; she was making
clear that the Bush campaign, with increasing vigor, would portray
Gore as an old-style Democrat bent on intrusive government
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bush campaign officials said that they planned to put a
more exacting microscope over Gore's calls for increased government
spending and assert that the vice president's appetite for new
programs endangered projected federal surpluses. Gore has levied
the same charge against Bush's sweeping tax cut proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is also paying close attention to other
aspects of the campaign, for example, monitoring polls in
battleground states so that Bush can tailor his schedule to those
fluctuating yardsticks.
</P>
<P>
   After meetings on Saturday during which Bush's aides hashed over
new evidence that Gore was pulling ahead in Pennsylvania, the Bush
campaign extended his schedule for this week to include a second
visit, on Friday, to that crucial state. Bush was already planning
to be there Tuesday for the unveiling of his prescription drug
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be agile and flexible and change things around
as we go,'' said one Bush aide.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush is already deep into preparing himself for the debates.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, a close
Republican ally of Bush's, visited Austin in his role as the
stand-in for Gore in rehearsals, according to one of Bush's
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser said that Gregg and Bush did not actually position
themselves at lecterns or simulate the formal trappings of a
debate, but practiced the kind of back-and-forth exchanges that
would probably occur between the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this activity, Rove's use of the phrase ``an
appropriate way'' to describe how Bush would distinguish himself
from Gore pointed to a potential problem for the Bush campaign as
it gets more aggressive. Sharp attacks on Gore could come across as
a hypocritical contradiction of Bush's pledge to ``change the
tone'' of politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican officials said that pitches like the one used in
last week's commercial _ which mocked Gore's appearance in 1996 at
a fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple and his boasts about creating
the Internet _ had tested well with swing voters in focus groups
conducted by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush, in an interview on Friday, hinted that there was
plenty more ammunition against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of different things we could have used,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush was on a day trip to Louisiana and Arkansas that reflected
the campaign's ongoing analysis of the electoral map. Neither of
those states belongs firmly to either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers expect him to dominate elsewhere in the South and
will thus focus most strongly on Florida, where Gore is mounting a
strong challenge. Its 25 electoral votes are the the nation's
fourth richest prize, behind California and New York, where Gore
should prevail, and Texas, which is a cinch for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush will visit California next week and his advisers
want to force Gore to spend time and money there, their only
genuine hope on the West Coast seems to be Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast, with the exceptions of New Hampshire and possibly
Maine, is also a stronghold for Gore, which leaves the states in or
abutting the Midwest as the most intense war zone.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers regard Indiana as an almost sure win and Ohio and
Missouri as likely victories that need tending. As these advisers
seem to see it, Illinois and Minnesota are likely losses, although
Illinois will get some attention.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin and Iowa are possibilities. And then come Michigan and
Pennsylvania, ripe with electoral votes. Bush will pass through
both of these states more than once this week, along with visits to
Illinois, Wisconsin, Ohio and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of events, the Bush campaign plans to extend to other
issues its practice of introducing middle-class families who would
benefit from his proposed tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will probably stand alongside senior citizens who prefer
his prescription drug plan to Gore's and people in their 20s or 30s
who like his call for the option of private investment accounts
within the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   But several of his advisers acknowledged that Bush's message had
to transcend _ and, in a sense, trump _ policy details, because
polls show that more voters see Gore's positions on issues as
compatible to their own.
</P>
<P>
   So Bush will assert that no matter where Gore stands, he cannot
deliver, because he lacks the ability to forge bipartisan
cooperation. And Bush will talk, as he has since last year, about
Gore's prescriptions being the reflections of a man who believes in
government as the font of all wisdom while his own remedies are a
gesture of faith in people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if it got to be about specific issue positions, you're
playing on Gore's turf,'' one adviser to the Bush campaign said.
``But if you make issues about broader realities and broader
dynamics, you're on our turf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
