<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS HITS 40TH HOMER, BREAKS REGGIE'S TEAM RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Troy Glaus turned 24 only a month ago, but Sunday he
broke the Angels' single-season home run record with his 40th of
the year in the sixth inning off White Sox pitcher Matt Ginter.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jackson held the record with 39 since 1982, but Glaus
found no reason to feel satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what I'm about,'' said Glaus, who is hitting .281
and has 90 RBI. ``Individual records don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates, though, are impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great accomplishment,'' said right fielder Tim Salmon,
who earlier this season passed Brian Downing to set the Angels'
career home run record. ``Am I surprised? No. The guy's going to
hit 40 home runs every year, at least. I'm happy for him, I'm
pushing for him to hit 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stays here a long time, he's going to break all the
records. He's going to be one of those players people talk about
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   What seemed to overshadow Glaus' accomplishment, however, was
that it came in a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys offensively are putting up some tremendous
numbers, but it's no consolation unless we get to where we want to
be,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``That's what I like about this
club. (Records) are very hollow if we don't win. They're not happy
with personal numbers and they shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   SPIEZIO SIGHTING: Scott Spiezio couldn't be blamed if he sent
Scioscia a memo reminding him he still plays for the Angels. After
all, Spiezio has all but disappeared since the Angels traded for
Ron Gant on July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio got a rare start Sunday and responded by tying his
career high with four RBI, three coming in on his 14th homer of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But before Sunday's game, Spiezio had just 26 at-bats since Gant
joined the team, including only 24 at-bats during the month of
August. Scioscia has gone primarily with Gant and Orlando Palmeiro
in the DH/part-time outfielder role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, any time you're not in the lineup it's
frustrating,'' said Spiezio, who began spring training as a
candidate for the starting spot at second base. ``I want to be in
there every day, but it's not going to happen. Instead of sulking
and crying about it, I wait for an opportunity. If it's one at-bat,
it's one at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might sit for three days, then get one at-bat in the ninth
against a (John) Wetteland or a (Mariano) Rivera. If I'm sulking, I
have no chance against those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio's opportunities have been limited even more of late
because Darin Erstad has been in the DH spot while he nurses a
strained rib cage muscle. Gant and Palmeiro are natural
outfielders, while Spiezio's start Sunday was his first in the
outfield in his career.
</P>
<P>
   QUALITY TIME: Derrick Turnbow, the 22-year-old Rule V draftee,
got into a game Sunday that was still in question. All of his 19
previous appearances were during blowouts one way or the other, but
he entered Sunday's game in the sixth with the Angels holding an
11-9 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The first batter he faced _ Frank Thomas _ hit a home run. But
Turnbow retired the next three hitters, including a strikeout of
Herbert Perry with a 95 mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   MERCKER TO SIT: Pitcher Kent Mercker said his strained rotator
cuff is something he's experienced before and simply requires rest.
However, he will not make his next scheduled start and will likely
go to the bullpen when he's healthy enough to pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher is expected to take Mercker's start Thursday in
Detroit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
