<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANNOUNCES ALTERNATE PLAN FOR DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: 2nd take will move by 10 p.m. EST)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Trying to end questions about his willingness to
debate and turn the tables on his opponent, Gov. George W. Bush on
Sunday announced a schedule of three hand-picked debates that he
wanted to participate in, only one of which is guaranteed to be
broadcast on the three major networks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointedly challenged Vice President Al Gore to meet him on
these chosen dates and terms. And he tried to turn Gore's response
into a referendum on the vice president's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has said he will debate anytime, anywhere, and he
has already accepted the debates that I am accepting today,'' Bush
said. ``It's important for the American people to be able to trust
the next president to keep his commitments, and therefore I take Al
Gore at his word that he will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his proposal, Bush was rebuffing a schedule set up by
the Commission on Presidential Debates, which was created by both
parties and has supervised the presidential debates since 1988.
That agency had proposed three debates, all to be broadcast on the
major networks, and Gore has accepted that plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who made his announcement at a hastily called news
conference on the lawn of the governor's mansion Sunday afternoon,
said he would debate Gore on a prime-time edition of NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' next Tuesday, on ``Larry King Live'' on CNN on Oct. 3,
and in St. Louis on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   His idea drew an immediate reaction from Gore, who said he was
``very disappointed,'' and from Gore's campaign manager, who flatly
rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Another Gore aide said that Bush's plan would be acceptable as
long as he agreed to the three commission debates. ``We've already
accepted these,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ``We have no
problem with these. We just want to make sure we do the three
presidential ones.''
</P>
<P>
   While the posturing and positioning on Sunday were over debates,
they were also an attempt by each campaign to make a statement
about the character of the opponent. Gore's aides have been
suggesting that Bush is afraid of a prime-time confrontation,
raising the question of whether he is up to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, with his move on Sunday, tried to make this a test of
Gore's character and credibility, because of his frequent promises
to debate Bush anytime, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Gore campaign's reaction to Bush's debate
proposal, Bush's spokeswoman, Karen Hughes, said, ``We'll be there
and we'll see if Al Gore will keep his word.'' She added, ``After
eight years of prevaricating, after eight years of `no controlling
legal authority' and of debate over what the meaning of `is' is,
the American people deserve a president who will keep his word.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was just beginning his 24-hour Labor Day marathon tour
in Philadelphia, said only that he was ``disappointed.'' Speaking
to reporters outside Pat's Steaks, where he was getting a cheese
steak sandwich, he said: ``I'm very disappointed in this reaction,
because what's needed is to respect the rights of the American
people, to see the debates on all the networks in prime time.'' He
added: ``That's the way it's been done since 1988.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000903.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0080 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-03 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WORKING HARDER, LONGER
</HEADLINE>
  By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot of good news to report this Labor Day.
Unemployment is very low and wages are rising. The benefits of the
booming economy are being widely distributed. Workers at the bottom
are finally enjoying significant increases in their
inflation-adjusted wages. Better yet, the U.S. is experiencing a
surge in the growth of labor productivity which, as noted in a
book-length report from the Economic Policy Institute, is
``probably the best indicator of an economy's capacity to provide
for the material needs of its population.''
</P>
<P>
   This good news is the result of the rapid economic growth and
most especially the sustained low unemployment that really got
rolling in the mid-1990s. The key issue has always been the same
for working people _ jobs, jobs, jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employment opportunities have expanded considerably,
especially for historically disadvantaged groups, including women,
blacks and Hispanics,'' the report said. ``The long-term rise in
job instability and job insecurity, which continued well into the
current economic recovery, finally appeared to have abated at the
end of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the share of workers in nonstandard _ often substandard _
work arrangements, such as temporary work and part-time work, has
declined as opportunities for regular full-time employment have
grown.''
</P>
<P>
   Nirvana, yes?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there's the time crunch. Families with children
have had to work harder and harder over the past few decades to
maintain a decent standard of living, and that phenomenon
continues. The number of earners per family has increased, as have
the average number of weeks worked per year, and the number of
hours worked per week.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't leave a lot of quality time for families to enjoy
the benefits of their added income. As a woman in New Jersey
recently said: ``We're a working family all right. That's all we do
is work.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the matter of indebtedness. The institute's
report, which is titled ``The State of Working America 2000-01''
and is published by Cornell University Press, makes it clear that
despite the rosy stock market stories of the past few years, the
typical American family accumulated more debt in the 1990s than it
made from the appreciation of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The authors wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``The total wealth of the typical American household improved
only marginally during the 1990s. The net worth of the typical
household rose about $2,200 in the 1990s _ from $58,800 in 1989 to
$61,000 in 1998. While this household's assets grew modestly _
stock assets were up by $5,500 and nonstock assets by $8,500 _ its
debt rose as well, by $11,800. Thus, the relatively modest gains in
stock and nonstock assets combined with the offsetting rise in
household debt meant that the 1990s were far less generous to
typical households than business-page headlines often suggest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Middle-income families are ahead of where they were four or
five years ago to the tune of two or three or four thousand
dollars, and that's not chicken feed,'' said Jared Bernstein, a
labor economist and one of the authors of the report. ``But they
are more indebted, working more and more hours, and the stock
market boom has largely passed them by.''
</P>
<P>
   The times may be terrific, but American working families are not
well-prepared for significant downside economic surprises. ``On
some level,'' said Bernstein, ``their future is largely dependent
on staying where we are with regard to unemployment and
productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the public profile of the poor has diminished almost
to the point of invisibility. But they are still there. Despite the
economic gains of the past few years, the national poverty rate in
1998 _ the latest year for which complete statistical data was
available _ was 12.7 percent, just one tenth of a percentage point
less than in 1989, and one full percentage point higher than in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in five American children lives in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The tight labor market is helping, and poor families are working
more. But the progress is painfully slow.
</P>
<P>
   Historians will look back at Labor Day 2000 and marvel at how
well America was doing. And then they will assess how wisely,
during these best of times, we invested our considerable resources
in the unfinished business of creating a brighter future for
everyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
