<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DEDRIC WARD SHOWS HE'S BIG ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Ever since Keyshawn Johnson departed to Tampa
Bay in a flurry of contract demands, the question has hovered over
the Jets: Could Al Groh and Dedric Ward justify the deal?
</P>
<P>
   Groh for being willing to trade a Pro Bowl wide receiver. Ward
for being his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Jets opened Groh's tenure as coach with a 20-16
victory over the Packers Sunday, Ward made the biggest play _
snatching Vinny Testeverde's pass and streaking down the sideline
for a 61-yard gain to the Packers' 2-yard line that positioned
Testeverde's quick pass to Curtis Martin for the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the 5-foot-9-inch Ward was about to debate Johnson's
persistent argument that he would be irreplaceable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into that,'' Ward said at his locker.
``We don't talk about the guys that are not here.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to talk about the guy that is not here. His big
play did all the talking for him. He showed that he's big enough.
But down deep, he had to feel proud of what he did in catching five
passes for 104 yards, a 20.8-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it like that,'' he said quietly. ``I just
think everybody's going to pick up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the big play itself, Ward preferred to credit Dan
Henning, the offensive coordinator who called it from the coaches'
booth upstairs at Lambeau Field, and Testeverde for throwing it so
accurately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a play we work on every week,'' Ward said. ``I'm not
going to tell you what the name of the play is other than it's our
`touchdown play.' The cornerback bit on it and Vinny made a great
read on it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also the type of play that Johnson, for all his talent,
seldom made _ the long gain that scores or sets up a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   With his size, Johnson was better at catching sideline passes
and slants over the middle, but he didn't have Ward's sheer speed
in being able to run away from most defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics doubted if the Jets' offense could survive with two
relatively small wide receivers; Wayne Chrebet, who caught five
passes for 47 yards Sunday, is only 5-10.
</P>
<P>
   But early in Dan Marino's career with the Miami Dolphins, he was
at his best in collaborating with two small wide receivers, Mark
Clayton and Mark Duper, for dozens of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In pro football, it's not the height of the wide receivers that
counts as much as the skill of the quarterback throwing to them.
</P>
<P>
   For much of Sunday's game, Testeverde was understandably rusty.
In addition to returning from the left Achilles tendon torn in last
season's opener, he also suffered a turf-toe injury that limited
him to fewer than 45 snaps in the exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half, Testeverde completed only 11 of 25 passes
for 82 yards as running back Curtis Martin carried to a 10-10
halftime tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envisioned it being a little more crisp,'' the 36-year-old
quarterback said of his passes, ``than it was in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Testeverde had more the look of the
quarterback who had taken the Jets to the AFC championship game in
1998 before losing a shootout with John Elway's Broncos in Denver,
the quarterback the Jets need if they are to challenge the
Indianapolis Colts for the AFC title now that Bill Parcells is no
longer the coach.
</P>
<P>
   But in winning his opener as the Jets coach, Al Groh refused, at
least publicly, to celebrate. Or even to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very resolute,'' he said, ``to remove my personal
emotions from this situation. This was not a first-game win for me,
but a great win to start the season. It wasn't about me at all. My
ego is not such that I see this in terms of Al Groh at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the new coach was here all by himself. His longtime
boss and the Jets' former coach, Bill Parcells, did not make the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   The new owner, Woody Johnson, arrived by chartered jet and flew
home on the team's charter, but Parcells was nowhere to be seen.
When the Jets are in their training complex, he's in his office
there as the director of football operations, alias general
manager, but it's as if he doesn't really know how to act in that
role.
</P>
<P>
   He feels that if he's seen around Groh or the players too much,
he'll be accused of interfering. He also knows that if he's not
seen at all, if it seems that he too far removed, he will be
accused of not caring enough.
</P>
<P>
   But when other legendary coaches evolved into a general
manager's role, they were always visible _ Vince Lombardi and Bill
Walsh, for example. And then there is Al Davis, briefly a
successful coach with the Oakland Raiders, who sometimes was too
visible and too vocal as their managing general partner, alias
managing general genius.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fine line that Bill Parcells is walking. And as it turned
out, the Jets and Al Groh didn't miss him. But as a director of
football operations, he should be at his team's games. He wouldn't
be interfering. He would only be inspiring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
