<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PACKERS-NYT &LR;      09-03 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG FINISH GIVES THE JETS A WINNING START 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Curtis Martin wanted to do more this season,
wanted to squeeze more power and strength from his compact body to
fill the chasm in the Jets' offense created by the departure of
receiver Keyshawn Johnson. He had run in the stairwell of his
Florida condominium in preparation for this and then had best
preseason of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Jets gave their fans and opponents a glimpse of what
post-Johnson life will look like in a 20-16 victory over the Green
Bay Packers, and it looked an awful lot like a Martin highlight
reel.
</P>
<P>
   While quarterback Vinny Testaverde took the first half to scrape
off the rust that enveloped him from spare preseason action in his
return from an ankle injury, Martin propelled the Jets. He ran for
110 yards and a touchdown and caught six passes for 34 yards,
including one for the game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Packers rallying in the second half behind their
quarterback Brett Farve _ and with the Jets frequently
self-destructing under the weight of penalties and dropped balls _
the Jets needed a spectacular 61-yard reception by Dedric Ward to
set up the winning touchdown with 3 minutes 30 seconds to go and a
leaping interception by safety Victor Green with 1:08 remaining to
preserve Martin's gem.
</P>
<P>
   That had Al Groh celebrating his first victory as the head coach
and Testaverde weeping from the emotion of his comeback from the
devastating Achilles' tendon injury he sustained in last season's
opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said this game had the potential to be one of those games
that creates a team for the rest of the season,'' Groh said. ``This
is one, but a significant one for us, more than just the win. There
was an opportunity for our players' will to crack.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there ever. Testaverde was worried about how he would
perform after having so little work during a preseason when he was
hampered by a jammed toe, and his timing clearly suffered early.
</P>
<P>
   On the third play of the Jets' first drive, Testaverde expected
wide receiver Wayne Chrebet to cut to his left. Instead, Chrebet
ran straight and the Packers' Darren Sharper picked off the pass,
returning it to the 4-yard line. The Packers scored on the next
play on a 4-yard pass from Favre to Tyrone Davis to take a 7-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde completed just 11 of 25 passes for 82 yards in the
first half, so the Jets turned repeatedly to Martin. Of the 15-play
drive that culminated in Martin's 2-yard touchdown run that evened
the score late in the first quarter, Martin was in on 11 plays. And
when Martin missed the last drive of the first half because he had
sprained his left knee, the Jets were unable to pound the ball into
the end zone on three plays from within 11 yards, and settled for a
23-yard field goal by John Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Even Martin, who spoke frequently during training camp of
wanting an expanded role from his already enormous load, wasn't
expecting so much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking about me catching the ball more this
year,'' Martin said. ``I was surprised, but I believe I was ready
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, though, did not look ready in several areas for
stretches of the game. Twice they found themselves in the end zone
with apparent touchdowns, only to have one _ a 7-yard reception by
Chrebet _ called back because of a trip by tackle Jason Fabini and
another brought back because Ward bobbled the ball as he ran
through the end zone. The Jets also had 10 penalties for a total of
75 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets' defense _ which had been questioned for several
shaky preseason performances _ repeatedly kept the Packers out of
the end zone, forcing them to kick three field goals, even as
Farve, who had little preseason work because of elbow tendinitis,
slowly worked his way back to form. In all, the Jets held the
Packers to 211 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to give Testaverde time to find his groove, and
he found it with Ward, who has been charged with being the No. 2
receiver now that Johnson has gone to Tampa Bay. Testaverde
finished with 23 completions in 44 attempts for 261 yards, and the
most spectacular of those yards came on the play that ultimately
won the game.
</P>
<P>
   With the Packers leading, 16-13, after yet another field goal
midway through the fourth quarter, the Jets took over at their
26-yard line. Three plays later, Ward streaked down the sideline.
This was the same play on which Testaverde had hit Chrebet for a
75-yard touchdown in the preseason against New Orleans. On that
play, Testaverde hit Chrebet over the middle. This time, he saw
Ward going down the sideline. He hit him in stride at the 30 and
Ward ran toward the end zone. He was pushed out at the 2. After two
unsuccessful runs, Martin peeked around a defender to grab
Testaverde's 3-yard touchdown pass that gave the Jets their final
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde would talk later about how the emotion of his
comeback _ coupled with memories of his late father _ sent him
weeping from the field. Testaverde sat at his locker and wept after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt kind of silly bawling in front of my teammates,''
Testaverde said. ``It hit me all at once. Getting the win, feeling
the presence of my father, wishing he was here, all those things
made it emotional and made it special.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets needed one more special play to secure the victory.
With the Packers driving with less than two minutes to play, the
Jets were backing up. On second-and-3 at the Jets' 35, Farve reared
back and threw to the right sideline. Green leaped and grabbed the
ball at the 9, robbing Bill Schroeder of a possible touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good throw,'' Green said. ``But it was a better
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was a better victory for a team beset by so many
questions entering the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we had character building last year,'' Martin said
of the Jets' disappointing 8-8 season. ``This year, this game,
showed the result of that character building. I'm not saying we're
there. But we're on our way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
