<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY, SEPT. 4 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MISSILE-DECISION-NYT (moved Saturday, September 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday,
September 2 about the origin of President Clinton's deferral of a
decision on a national missile defense system misstated the date of
the only previous instance an official could recall in which
Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen was overruled within the
administration's foreign policy team. That instance _ in which he
argued against imposing sanctions on Myanmar _ occurred in 1997,
not 1996.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-POLLARD-NYT (moved Friday, September 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, September
1 about Hillary Rodham Clinton's efforts on behalf of Jonathan
Pollard, the convicted spy, misstated the date on which she met
with the New York Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, and with
Assemblyman Dov Hikind. It was Aug. 23, not Aug. 30. The article
also misstated the date Hikind was informed of Clinton's
intervention. It was Aug. 26, not Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FLA-AFFIRM-NYT (moved Tuesday, August 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 29
about the rise in minority enrollment in Florida colleges since the
state ended race-based admissions misstated the year in which
California voters ended affirmative action. It was 1996, not 1997.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FUR-AD-COLUMN-NYT (moved Thursday, August 31)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August
31 about a campaign for American Legend mink coats, misspelled the
surname of a singer and actress who appeared in earlier
advertisements. She is Lena Horne, not Horn.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-BARKS-NYT (moved Friday, August 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary sent on Friday August 25
about Carl Barks, the cartoonist who created Scrooge McDuck,
misstated the surname of the author of a book about him, and a
cartoon panel with the obituary carried an erroneous credit. The
author is Edward Summer, not Summers. The cartoon was from his book
``Uncle Scrooge McDuck, His Life and Times (Celestial Arts, 1980),
not from Walt Disney Productions.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-GUINESS-NYT (moved Sunday, August 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary sent on Sunday, August 6
of the actor Alec Guinness, misstated the name of a character
played by Martita Hunt in the 1946 film ``Great Expectations.'' It
was Havisham, not Habersham.
</P>
