<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0095 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEBATE-1STLD-WRI     09-03 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-530(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANNOUNCES ALTERNATE PLAN FOR DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Adds 2nd take to earlier story.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Trying to end questions about his willingness to
debate and turn the tables on his opponent, Gov. George W. Bush on
Sunday announced a schedule of three hand-picked debates that he
wanted to participate in, only one of which is guaranteed to be
broadcast on the three major networks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointedly challenged Vice President Al Gore to meet him on
these chosen dates and terms. And he tried to turn Gore's response
into a referendum on the vice president's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has said he will debate anytime, anywhere, and he
has already accepted the debates that I am accepting today,'' Bush
said. ``It's important for the American people to be able to trust
the next president to keep his commitments, and therefore I take Al
Gore at his word that he will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his proposal, Bush was rebuffing a schedule set up by
the Commission on Presidential Debates, which was created by both
parties and has supervised the presidential debates since 1988.
That agency had proposed three debates, all to be broadcast on the
major networks, and Gore has accepted that plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who made his announcement at a hastily called news
conference on the lawn of the governor's mansion Sunday afternoon,
said he would debate Gore on a prime-time edition of NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' next Tuesday, on ``Larry King Live'' on CNN on Oct. 3,
and in St. Louis on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   His idea drew an immediate reaction from Gore, who said he was
``very disappointed,'' and from Gore's campaign manager, who flatly
rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Another Gore aide said that Bush's plan would be acceptable as
long as he agreed to the three commission debates. ``We've already
accepted these,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ``We have no
problem with these. We just want to make sure we do the three
presidential ones.''
</P>
<P>
   While the posturing and positioning on Sunday were over debates,
they were also an attempt by each campaign to make a statement
about the character of the opponent. Gore's aides have been
suggesting that Bush is afraid of a prime-time confrontation,
raising the question of whether he is up to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, with his move on Sunday, tried to make this a test of
Gore's character and credibility, because of his frequent promises
to debate Bush anytime, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Gore campaign's reaction to Bush's debate
proposal, Bush's spokeswoman, Karen Hughes, said, ``We'll be there
and we'll see if Al Gore will keep his word.'' She added, ``After
eight years of prevaricating, after eight years of `no controlling
legal authority' and of debate over what the meaning of `is' is,
the American people deserve a president who will keep his word.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was just beginning his 24-hour Labor Day marathon tour
in Philadelphia, said only that he was ``disappointed.'' Speaking
to reporters outside Pat's Steaks, where he was getting a cheese
steak sandwich, he said: ``I'm very disappointed in this reaction,
because what's needed is to respect the rights of the American
people, to see the debates on all the networks in prime time.'' He
added: ``That's the way it's been done since 1988.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of the commission debates, Gore said: ``It is a bipartisan,
nonpartisan tradition, and it's not about Governor Bush, it's not
about me, it's about the American people and giving the American
people the chance they deserve to make an informed judgment as to
who they want to be the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers said that Bush was deliberately trying to shrink
the audience, because unless there was blanket coverage on all five
networks, viewers would likely stray to other programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless these debates are roadblocked, you don't get the kind
of viewership you do with the commission debates,'' said one aide,
noting that Bush's proposal for the NBC debate would bump up
against popular shows like ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?'' and
``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how much exposure the noncommission debates
proposed by Bush would get or whether the television networks would
agree to broadcast debates held by a rival television news outlet.
Evans said that both NBC and CNN had offered to make their footage
available to other networks.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it clear what format there would be to the one
commission debate that Bush accepted. Evans said that this still
had to be negotiated and that all the Bush campaign had accepted
was the St. Louis venue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said on Sunday that his campaign would agree to two
vice presidential debates, one in Winston-Salem, N.C., sponsored by
the debate commission and another one in a forum yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Bush played video clips of Gore in
appearances with Tim Russert on ``Meet the Press'' in July and on
``Larry King Live'' in March in which he said he would be happy to
appear in debates on their shows. As the videos played, Bush stood
at a lectern tapping his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is generally considered by political strategists to be a
weaker debater than Gore and his aides had been angling for
different formats. On Friday commission officials told aides to
Bush that they would not revise the locations of schedules for the
forums, because the work was too far advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had selected the three formats because they would
be varied and because he wanted one debate on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give the American people an opportunity to see the
candidates in a wide range of locations and formats, from a
free-flowing, spontaneous discussion with Larry King to tough
question-and-answer sessions with a moderator like Tim Russert,''
he said, ``to the more formal and structured setting of the
presidential debate commission. As I have said earlier, my opponent
has already accepted these invitations.''
</P>
<P>
   As the debate over debates has simmered, Bush has appeared on
the defensive, looking as if he was seeking a better format for
himself. He and his aides were clearly trying to turn the tables
and use the struggle over debates to focus on Gore's character and
make him look untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush's news conference, Hughes, his communications
director, reminded reporters that Gore had said he would debate
anytime and anywhere. ``We take him at his word,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And on CNN, before Bush's news conference, Ari Fleischer a Bush
spokesman, also noted that the vice president had been accepting
numerous debate offers, and said, ``I predict to you, they're going
to change their position all of a sudden again.'' Using a favorite
refrain of the Bush campaign, Fleischer said of Gore, ``The vice
president will say one thing and do another.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush issued his challenge hours before flying to Chicago, where
he planned to begin the Labor Day kickoff of the general election
campaign. Polls show the race to be a dead heat or else give Gore a
slight lead. The debates are considered an important forum that
could well help undecided voters to make up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   By offering to hold the first debate next week, Bush portrayed
himself as eager for the confrontation. ``The debates we are
accepting begin early next week because we are eager to compare the
specifics of our plans for more individual freedom, choice and
responsibility, with our opponent's plans for a bigger, more
intrusive Washington bureaucracy that dictates and mandates from
afar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his senior advisers had been saying for weeks that they
wanted to explore options beyond those proposed by the bipartisan
debate commission, because they felt that there could be other
debates of equal or greater value to voters.
</P>
<P>
   But one adviser conceded Sunday night that in selecting debates
that would be moderated by the journalist Tim Russert in one case
and the talk-show host Larry King in another, Bush was guaranteeing
that he would be taking questions from people who had quizzed him
before, and with whom he felt familiarity and comfort. The
commission had not yet announced who would be moderating its
debates.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist in Washington said that by spurning
two of the three commission debates, which would be more
structured, Bush was showing ``that he's concerned about filling
the full two-minute answer'' in a debate with formal time
parameters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry will bail him out,'' said the strategist, referring to
King. ``Larry will keep it moving.'' The strategist added that the
two debates not sponsored by the commission ``aren't real debates.
They're performances on a talk show.''
</P>
<P>
   But several of Bush's advisers said that while journalists were
sure to deride Bush's decision, most voters would care only about
the fact that Bush was debating and would find all the noise
surrounding the negotiations to be meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not stupid. We've been looking at this,'' said one
adviser. ``Nobody knows who the commission is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
