r a BC-GROUP-HOME-KAN &LR;      09-03 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUP-HOME-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER TOOK DISABLED MEN ON UNAUTHORIZED JOURNEY THAT TURNED
FATAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY and MIKE RICE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two developmentally disabled men who died
Saturday in a sweltering station wagon in Swope Park should never
have been taken there, according to the executive director of the
organization that housed them.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are investigating the incident, in which a
26-year-old caregiver took Steven Warren, 34, and Michael O'Neal,
55, from their group home to the park. Warren and O'Neal had lived
at the Community Living Opportunities Inc. group home at 9322 W.
50th Terrace in Merriam, Kan., for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trip to that area was unauthorized,'' said Michael
Strouse, executive director of Community Living Opportunities.
``The driver was acting independently.''
</P>
<P>
   Strouse said the two were supposed to have been taken on a short
trip to a fast-food restaurant in Johnson County, Kan., and
shouldn't have been taken anywhere near Swope Park in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies on Sunday showed that they died of heat-related
causes. No charges had been filed in the case Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of work to do in this case, a lot of interviews
to do,'' said Paul Morrison, Johnson County prosecutor. ``We're
going to check out the caregiver's story. We're going to be waiting
on lab results for a while. Both of the gentlemen were on
medication because of their physical problems, which can become a
factor in this kind of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Strouse said both men were severely disabled and were taking
medication that could cause adverse reactions in extreme heat. One
had a history of seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the hottest day of the year, with the temperature
reaching 106 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The caregiver said he left the men in the station wagon in the
park for a short time. When he returned, he found them unresponsive
in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   He then drove them to Shawnee Mission Medical Center's emergency
room about 5 p.m. A doctor there declared the men dead.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear why the caregiver took the men to Shawnee Mission
Medical Center, about 10 miles west of Swope Park, rather than to
Research Medical Center, just a few blocks from the park.
</P>
<P>
   Strouse said that during extreme weather conditions, such as
Saturday's, employees were to follow procedures on whether
residents can be outside and for how long.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know how long the men were in the station
wagon.
</P>
<P>
   The driver has been employed by Community Living Opportunities
for three months but had worked earlier in caretaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also had a career in the military and came here with good
references,'' Strouse said.
</P>
<P>
   Agency employees undergo extensive certification training and a
stringent background check, Strouse said. The driver had no
criminal background or history of incompetence and was fully
trained for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, a caretaker from another Community Living
Opportunities group home in Johnson County disappeared on a Friday
with three developmentally disabled women.
</P>
<P>
   They left the home to run errands but were found 31 hours later
in their van at Prospect and Independence avenues in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In that incident, Robert L. Newsome was charged with three
felony counts of mistreatment of a dependent adult and two
misdemeanor counts of theft.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Strouse said, Newsome had more than a decade of
experience in social services and had impeccable references when he
was hired two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It's common for caretakers to take group home residents out for
activities, said Mark Elmore, executive director for Johnson County
Developmental Supports, which coordinates care and activity
programs for groups such as Community Living Opportunities that
help the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   But staff members must understand how important it is to watch
their charges closely, Elmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really bad,'' he said of the deaths. ``My first
thoughts are with the families. The tragedy of this is that it
makes no sense. It's an outing gone bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Community Living Opportunities Inc. has several group homes in
Johnson County and operates a recycling center at 80th Street and
Metcalf Avenue, where some of the residents work. The agency was
founded in 1977 by John and Betty Pelot, whose son, Jimmy, was
autistic and didn't speak.
</P>
<P>
   The Star's Bill Graham contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
