<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS FROM CHINA VISIT KANSAS CITY TO STUDY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Liu Ze has been in the United States just
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Liu, who goes by the name Derek, already sees a big
difference from his native Beijing. Here, when he walks around the
city, drivers let him cross in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   They even wave and smile when they do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a king,'' he said while talking about life as an
American college student. He sat in the office of professor Patrick
Randolph at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Liu is one of five Chinese citizens studying law this year at
UMKC.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph began teaching law in China seven years ago and the
last two years has persuaded Chinese students to come to Kansas
City to study law. The students get scholarship aid to study at
UMKC. They also have received some help from law school alumni and
professors.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Chinese students want to learn about the American
legal system because, as China's political and economic systems
become more open, the legal system there is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more China understands and admires about America, the
better off we'll be,'' Randolph said.
</P>
<P>
   But as the students are learning about American law, they also
are learning about American life.
</P>
<P>
   When Zhang Xi, who goes by Simon, arrived in Kansas City last
year, he couldn't believe how mobile everyone was.
</P>
<P>
   He's used to a country where most people get around on bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he drives, too.
</P>
<P>
   Liu, who will be here one year to earn a master of laws degree,
is amazed that Americans form lines and stay in them without
cutting in and without arguing.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't happen in China.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Americans' pragmatism. Many Chinese do a lot of
abstract thinking, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in America it's ``Let's do something, not hot air or just
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The students want to learn the American life while they're here,
but they also hope they can expose American students to Chinese
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is the unknown (in America),'' said Liu. ``It is
associated with evil. But now they can see Chinese people; they
eat, drink. They go to the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Liu laughed at his own remark, and Zhang joined in.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chinese student, Shen Fang, has realized how different
the countries' educational systems are.
</P>
<P>
   ``School is the best thing (for me) here, but also the worst
thing,'' she said, adding that she thinks American students work
much harder in school than students at many Chinese universities.
</P>
<P>
   She said China and America, although enemies in the past, have
much to share. She said China practically copied U.S. law when it
recently created a securities law.
</P>
<P>
   And the way the Chinese legal system uses mediation, rather than
constant bickering, could help the U.S. system, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Liu agreed: ``If Americans are humble enough, they can learn
from other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, wearing a shirt that said ``Washington, D.C., 2000'' and
depicted the U.S. Capitol and the American flag, said he wants to
learn American law because as China changes its economy, the legal
system will change, too.
</P>
<P>
   For example, as the country moves toward having more personal
property, real estate law needs to be developed and practiced.
</P>
<P>
   With increased trade and business ties with other countries and
global corporations, lawyers in China will need to know how
America's legal system works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be theearly bird,'' said Zhang, who plans to stay at
UMKC three years to earn a juris doctor degree. ``I come here and
study the law and hope I can use it in my home country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
