<SLUG> BC-BRONZE-STAR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARS LATER, KOREAN WAR VETERAN CLAIMS HIS BRONZE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN SHULTZ  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Nothing can stop Fred Swearngin, or so
he's been told.
</P>
<P>
   Not the howling artillery shells North Korean troops tried to
drop in his hip pocket, nor the brain aneurysm that cut short his
combat time.
</P>
<P>
   There's a statement the 71-year-old throws out, one he says he
uses a lot and has heard from his friends just as frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky,'' he said. ``I was shot at _ I was shot at, but I
didn't get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   And after ducking the bullets, smaller ones on the field and a
big one at a hospital, he left the Army and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Swearngin, of Overland Park, got some closure to his
year of military life.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight years after his honorable discharge, Swearngin _ the
former military policeman, the former Prairie Village police
patrolman, the current security guard _ was presented the medals he
had won for his service in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   It was a handful, but the prize of the bunch was the Bronze
Star, awarded for bravery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952 Swearngin had passed up the star and the chance for the
awards for his service.
</P>
<P>
   No one took them to his bed at Walter Reed Army Medical Center
in Washington, D.C., where he recovered from brain surgery, and he
didn't bother to seek them out.
</P>
<P>
   He left the promise of the awards, outlined on his discharge
papers, in a safe-deposit box. He tried to leave much of the war
there with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of went on with life,'' he said. ``I didn't pursue
it.I've never said much about the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to talk about it. I lost a lot of my best
friends. One of my best buddies had his arm blown off. They
actually called (the war) a police actionbut that sure looked like
a war to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago he broke his silence. Swearngin pulled his Form
DD-214 from the box and wrote Washington for his medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the sad feelings now _ I'm a happy individual,''
he said. ``I feel that I did my small portion.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is still quiet when asked about the war, talking only in
short bursts.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about how he, at 22, was at Heartbreak Ridge, the
bloody battle over a seven-mile stretch of strategically placed
hills, and fought in the slow reclaiming of Seoul, both in 1951. He
talks about the artillery trucks he directed toward the front that
returned hauling bodies.
</P>
<P>
   He was a combat MP with the 25th Division, he said, not unlike a
traffic officer working under artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very little protection,'' he said of the combat MPs.
``When troops are advancing, you're the first one out there. When
they pull back, you're the last.''
</P>
<P>
   No bullet struck him; no shell deafened or demolished him. But
he ended up in an Army hospital in Tokyo just the same.
</P>
<P>
   About eight months into his tour, his vision grew blurry,
Swearngin said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors there told him he had an aneurysm _ a bulge in an artery
that threatens to burst _ in his brain.
</P>
<P>
   It was from an earlier condition and was unrelated to combat. He
had five years to live, they said.
</P>
<P>
   He was sent back stateside, to Walter Reed, where doctors used
clips to shore up the artery. In May 1952, he was released from the
hospital and the Army. He quickly stashed his release papers,
locking them away.
</P>
<P>
   The time was hardly uneventful.
</P>
<P>
   A few years and a few jobs later, he became a police patrolman
in Prairie Village and then a traffic cop.
</P>
<P>
   He worked injury accidents and wrote citations _ about 600 one
month, , said a former co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real superior producer,'' said Prairie Village Police
Sgt. Dennis Nealey. ``A real nice guy, probably one of the
better-known traffic cops in Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the few people who could write somebody a
ticket, and they'd want to shake his hand for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Swearngin retired in 1983 and took a year vacation. Then he
jumped back into uniform, this time as a security guard at Shawnee
Mission Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   That's where he is now, where the younger people with whom he
works joke about never getting rid of him and hope they never do,
said Swearngin's supervisor, Charlie Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in law enforcement ever since Korea,'' Swearngin
said. ``I guess I like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
