u p BC-NJ-SENATE-RACE-(TRIMS     09-03 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-RACE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. RACE FOR SENATE IS ABOUT MONEY, MONEY AND THE LACK OF MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In the three months since the New Jersey
primaries, Rep. Bob Franks, the little-known Republican candidate
for U.S. Senate, has managed to raise just over $1 million for his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Corzine will spend more than that on television commercials
this week.
</P>
<P>
   That blunt contrast, more than anything else, is shaping the
fall campaign for the Senate as it begins in earnest on Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's riches have given him an advantage most first-time
candidates could only dream of. By spending $35 million in the
Democratic primary, shattering national records, Corzine, who
retired last year as co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., turned
himself from a political unknown into a household name. Emboldened,
he has since adopted a kind of Rose Garden strategy, avoiding
face-to-face encounters with his rival.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, overmatched financially, is trying to make Corzine's
money a campaign issue, attacking him in press releases and news
conferences for refusing to disclose his tax returns and for
favoring costly social programs that Franks says would bankrupt the
government. By daring Corzine to debate him and criticizing him for
refusing, Franks is hoping to make voters question Corzine's
credibility and fortitude, even his intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Corzine's name-recognition advantage over Franks, a
series of recent independent polls has suggested that the Senate
race in New Jersey is tightening.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's advisers have expressed befuddlement at surveys
showing a closer race, wondering aloud what could be driving the
independent polls, since little of public interest has taken place
in the Senate campaign since the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   But Cliff Zukin, director of the Star-Ledger/Eagleton-Rutgers
poll, said the Republican National Convention might have helped
Franks by getting voters' attention. ``Even though it's focused on
the presidential level, it brings Republicans home,'' Zukin said.
``They see the flag, they hear the speeches, and they remember why
they were Republicans to begin with. So it brings Republicans back
not just to the party's presidential nominee but to the Senate
candidates as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Corzine's campaign is not waiting to see
whether the race tightens any further. On Monday night, several of
his advisers said, Corzine will begin running the first two
commercials in his general-election television campaign. The
advertisements _ one 30 seconds long, the other a minute _ will be
broadcast in the New York City and Philadelphia media markets at a
cost of more than $1.1 million in the first week.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The advisers said the shorter commercial touched on education,
gun control and a prescription drug benefit for Medicare
recipients, and would argue that Corzine's stands on those issues
were aligned with New Jerseyans' values. The longer advertisement,
they said, reintroduces Corzine with a slightly altered message,
saying, for example, that he has ``the fiscal discipline of a
successful businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By beginning his air attack now, Corzine will be able to
communicate with New Jersey voters long before television stations
in New York and Philadelphia become saturated with advertisements
for the Senate candidates in New York and Pennsylvania as well as
the presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bet is now, even if Franks has two or three weeks of
effective commercials, they'll be less effective,'' the adviser
said, ``because Franks is competing not just with Jon Corzine, but
with Hillary and Lazio in New York, with Rick Santorum and Ron
Klink in Pennsylvania, and with Al Gore and George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks' only defense, for now, is to warn of a voter backlash
against Corzine's methods. ``After spending $35 million, Jon
Corzine is not as popular as one would expect,'' said Franks'
campaign manager, Charlie Smith. ``It demonstrates to me that this
election is about more than just television advertising. It's about
being able to represent the values and concerns of people. And
voters are smart. They can't be bought.''
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine appears undeterred by one recent poll showing that
31 percent of voters were greatly bothered by his campaign
spending. Beginning his television campaign now, nine weeks before
the Nov. 7 election, means he could easily spend $15 million more
on television alone. And his aides said Corzine had bought $2
million worth of commercials to be shown only during Olympics
broadcasts in October.
</P>
<P>
   Money, meanwhile, is Franks' great weakness. His aides have said
he needs to raise at least $8 million to stand a chance, but since
the primary he has only raised about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He raised $500,000 at an event honoring Senator John McCain,
R-Ariz., and $140,000 at the Republican convention. But since then,
he has shown little success. Two events in Texas with Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison produced only $50,000, as did an event with Rep.
Rick Lazio of New York, and several days of campaigning and
fund-raising along the Jersey Shore produced $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest direct mail appeal for money, Franks asked
previous contributors to his congressional races to donate $99,
``or, if you prefer, a monthly contribution of $33 in each of the
three months remaining until Election Day.'' He added: ``I don't
have to match Jon Corzine's spending. I only need enough
advertising to let voters compare my record of fiscal
responsibility in Congress to Jon Corzine's agenda of irresponsible
`universal government.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kept to a shoestring budget, Franks is also resorting to some
pugnacious tactics. He sent two campaign workers to the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles last month, where they wangled
credentials to get inside the Staples Arena during Corzine's speech
and handed out critiques of it afterward. Even more puckishly, the
Franks campaign has set up a Web site, www.mruniversal.com, that
depicts Corzine's face over a cartooned muscleman's body, and
leavens Franks' more serious attacks with satirical barbs that
range from witty to sophomoric.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of such tactics, the Corzine campaign has become careful
almost to a fault. At the first joint appearance of the two
candidates, a forum set up by the Veterans of Foreign Wars at a
high school in Toms River last Tuesday night, Corzine's aides
refused to allow Franks even to sit in the auditorium while Corzine
spoke. Franks was forced to wait his turn behind a closed door in
an adjoining office.
</P>
<P>
   When Franks finally addressed the 200 or so veterans there, one
reason Corzine might not have wanted to share a stage with him
quickly became clear: Corzine was politely received, but Franks was
the more practiced speaker and took only a few seconds to get the
first of many rounds of applause.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Franks will need every edge he can muster. While Corzine
is free to campaign as little or as much as he likes _ he had a
full schedule of beach walks and street fairs this weekend _ Franks
is caught in a difficult vise. He is forced to spend as much time
as possible raising money, as he did all day Saturday. And on
Tuesday, when Congress resumes its session, he will have to leave
for Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
