u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      09-03 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAFFE BY RIVERA HELPS TWINS BEAT YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Upset with himself for his uncharacteristic walk of
Torii Hunter, Mariano Rivera got into his windup and went through
his normal routine: he glanced toward the runner at first, then
looked away, all the while deciding where to throw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But while Rivera contemplated a move, Hunter, proving to be
either sly or lucky, took off for second base. As the Minnesota
Twins' center fielder sprinted toward the bag, Rivera stood
unaware, oblivious to what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez and Derek Jeter began screaming at their seemingly
dazed teammate, yelling, ``Step off! Step off!'' But by the time
their shouts for Rivera to step off the rubber were heard, Hunter
was more than halfway to second, and the pitcher had already
committed to throwing the ball to first.
</P>
<P>
   The play was blown, and as a result, the Twins had the go-ahead
run in scoring position in the 10th inning of Sunday's game at
Yankee Stadium. Moments later, after manager Joe Torre ordered an
intentional walk of Jacque Jones, the No. 8 batter in the lineup,
Rivera served up a two-out single to pinch-hitter Denny Hocking,
who scored Hunter to give Minnesota a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The odd play, which Rivera said he had never before experienced,
cost the Yankees a series sweep of the Twins and sullied another
strong performance by Roger Clemens, who threw eight solid innings,
nearly half of them in the rain, to continue his magnificent roll
of the past two months. Afterward, the typically reliable Rivera
was angry with himself not for taking his eyes off of the runner or
for throwing toward first, but for walking the speedy Hunter to
begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear `Step off' that means throw to second, but I was
already on my way to first,'' said Rivera, whose record dropped to
7-4 with the loss. ``If I had thrown to second, it would have been
a balk. But that's not the point. The point is that if I never
walked the guy that never would have happened. He just timed it
perfect. I was aware that he wanted to run, but I wasn't expecting
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said the Yankees work on that particular scenario
throughout the spring and that Rivera usually handles the situation
better than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously didn't see the runner because normally you see
the runner and just step off _ that's your first natural
reaction,'' said Torre, before the Yankees left for Kansas City,
where they begin a four-game series Monday. ``We beat ourselves
basically with that play. It's unfortunate that we let this one get
away because at home you should win extra-inning games.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Yankees been able to solve Minnesota's rookie right
hander, Matt Kinney, who held them to two hits and one run over six
innings, Clemens would have emerged with his eighth straight
victory. Working masterfully through the Twins' lineup, Clemens
registered eight strikeouts while allowing only three hits and
walking just one batter. His one weak moment came in the seventh,
when Ray Coomer sent a fastball over the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Clemens was the dominating pitcher Yankees fans have
come to expect since his seeming rebirth began with his activation
from the disabled list on July 2. Sunday's outing was his 13th
straight without a loss since returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger was terrific,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, idealistic fans probably held out hopes of seeing a
perfect game from Clemens. Facing a lineup that entered with a .140
batting average (13 for 93) against him, Clemens retired the first
nine Twins batters. Minnesota's first hit came in the fourth, on a
ground ball to left field by Jay Canizaro.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens got the next three hitters out, and then the rain began
to come down. The umpires informed Clemens that a delay might soon
follow, so, for a moment, he admitted to slipping out of his
groove. Still, the Twins managed only one hit over the next two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, the rain began falling with all the speed and
ferocity of one of Clemens' fastballs, and after another 1-2-3
inning, Clemens walked slowly off the field, knowing that his work
was through. The tarp came next, signifying the start of a
54-minute delay.
</P>
<P>
   Kinney was not as powerful as Clemens, but his slick timing on
when to use his curveball kept the Yankees off balance. Only Tino
Martinez got to him, hammering his 13th home run of the season in
the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had pretty good stuff _ he was kind of funky,'' Martinez
said of Kinney. ``He threw hard and had a good breaking ball and a
funky delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez nearly ended the game in the ninth when he drove an
offering from Eddie Guardado, who earned his fifth victory of the
season, off the top of the right-center-field wall. When Martinez
connected, the Yankees in the dugout, including Torre, rose from
their seats, hoping the shot would clear the fence.
</P>
<P>
   When it didn't, the 10th inning, and Rivera's strange gaffe,
followed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
