<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0112 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-LAWRENCE-ZONING-KAN &LR;      09-03 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWRENCE-ZONING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWRENCE HOMEOWNERS WANT TO LIMIT KU STUDENTS IN THEIR
NEIGHBORHOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRAD COOPER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ These are the kind of tales that would lead you
to believe college students live like heathens:
</P>
<P>
   Garbage piled high on the front lawn. Boisterous parties late
into the night. Intoxicated partyers urinating in bushes.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of behavior that makes homeowners cringe.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the kind of behavior that some Lawrence residents say
is creeping into their neighborhoods near the University of Kansas
campus as landlords buy up single-family homes and then rent them
out, many to students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we have to put up with that in an area zoned for
single families?'' asked Mary Elizabeth Debicki, who lives just
west of campus.
</P>
<P>
   Some homeowners want the Lawrence City Commission to tweak the
city's zoning law so it limits to two the number of unrelated
persons who can live in a home in a single-family residential area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto is two is a family, three is a crowd,'' said Arly
Allen, who lives just south of the KU campus and is one of the
neighborhood leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not object to renters as long as they are two unrelated
people or they're a family.''
</P>
<P>
   The limit is now four, allowing students, especially those short
of cash, to band together and rent a house for $200 to $300 a month
per person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come to realize that four unrelated people living
together lead to five, six or seven unrelated people living in the
same place,'' Debicki said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They live a student life. When they are out of class, they
invite all their friends in. There is a lot of partying. That is
normal, acceptable college behavior, but just not in a
single-family neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance advocated by neighborhood residents would not
affect any of the university's dormitories, fraternities or
sororities.
</P>
<P>
   It is aimed only at parts of town that are zoned for
single-family residences, including an area just south of the KU
campus where the city has received complaints from residents about
rental property.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has distinct ramifications for the wallets of KU
students such as Luke Pfannenstiel, a biology senior from
Hutchinson who shares a house with three roommates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would definitely make housing more expensive,'' said
Pfannenstiel, who with his roommates shoulders a $1,200 monthly
rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the big draw of living with a big group of people in a
house is that the rent is split that many more ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing (the residents) are trying to avoid is large
house parties, and not everybody does that. We're fairly quiet, and
we don't have 500 people over on the weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of changing the law say it will exclude thousands of
KU students such as Pfannenstiel from affordable housing. They say
stories about uncooperative students are exaggerated. And if there
are problems, a city nuisance ordinance could be used to keep
neighbors in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens in Lawrence who are supporting this effort think
that college students inherently are disrupting to single-family
neighborhoods,'' said Holly Krebs, a student leader opposing the
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a fair assessment of college students or
our lifestyle. There are lots of students that aren't disruptive to
single-family neighborhoods. It seems like it's a very indirect way
of trying to address a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey of cities with universities in the Big 12 Conference
revealed only two cities _ Lincoln, Neb., and Lubbock, Texas _ with
laws that limited to two the number of unrelated persons living
together in single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
   Cities such as Manhattan, Kan.; College Station, Texas; and
Waco, Texas, allowed four, while others such as Austin, Texas, and
Boulder, Colo., had no limits, according to the study, which was
conducted by Lawrence administrators. Columbia, Mo., has set the
number at three.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs, 22, lives in a home just northwest of campus with two
other persons. She said she and her roommates got along with their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I don't have a child or just because I don't have
a husband yet and don't have that family doesn't mean I cannot
contribute to that neighborhood,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this zoning battle is the Lawrence City
Commission, which must balance the needs of its residents with the
needs of a college community that contributes to the vitality of
this city with a population of 77,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very difficult issue,'' said City
Commissioner Martin Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the student population is a large asset for the
community. They do a lot for the community, and we realize they
need to have an economical place to rent to be able to go to
school. Balancing that with protecting our neighborhoods is one of
the main concerns we're facing.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Commission is scheduled to take up the issue when it
meets Tuesday night. Any proposal that is recommended by the
commission must go to the Planning Commission for consideration and
then back to the full commission for final action. The issue may
not be resolved until November or December.
</P>
<P>
   Two proposals are being sent to the City Commission. One drafted
by the neighbors would allow a three-year phaseout period for
landlords renting property to three or four persons.
</P>
<P>
   The other proposal drafted by city staff would require
properties that don't conform to the single-family zoning
designation to register with the city. After the lease expires, the
property would then come under the new law.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of policy, Lawrence generally enforces its zoning
laws when it receives complaints from residents or when city
inspectors observe violations. Unless the commission spells out a
different policy, the city probably would enforce the new law the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense among city commissioners that some
single-family neighborhoods are at risk as rental property
continues to pop up and the number of students living off campus
rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned about neighborhood stability,'' said Lawrence
Mayor James Henry. ``It really bothers me to see what were once
single-family neighborhoods becoming rental districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors attribute the problem to the vast number of KU
students who do not live in university housing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, there were 24,313 students enrolled at KU, according to
a university report. Of that number, 13,764, or 58.8 percent, lived
in rooms or apartments in the city. By comparison, 4,845, or 20.7
percent, lived in on-campus housing last year.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood leader Allen suggests that the university do more
to house students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university has outgrown, from our perspective, the ability
to house students,'' Allen said. ``More students are coming to
Lawrence than the university can or cares to house.''
</P>
<P>
   KU student housing director Ken Stoner said the university was
accommodating everybody that applies to live in on-campus housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not turn away students for housing,'' Stoner said. ``We
are housing more students, and our demand is good. We adjust the
way we offer the space to make sure that the students who need
housing _ we get them housing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Columbia reduced from four to three the
number of unrelated persons allowed to live together in
single-family neighborhoods. Homes rented to four persons at the
time the ordinance was adopted were grandfathered in.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia senior planner Chuck Bondra said three seemed to
alleviate a lot of the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get pretty upset if somebody decides to convert their
house to a rental and then rent it out to four students with four
cars and girlfriends and boyfriends and everybody else,'' Bondra
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have struck a balance by allowing up to three. That seems
to be more tolerable because I think the complaints have gone down
since we did that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
