<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-U.S.OPEN-ART-NYT &LR;      09-03 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S.OPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINUS TEEN SPIRIT, SELES DEFEATS CAPRIATI TO REACH QUARTERFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT18 and NYT19 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deep in the middle of the curious spectators inside
Arthur Ashe Stadium, Monica Seles and Jennifer Capriati stood on
the court as grown-ups, with budding bags beneath their eyes and
hardly a giggle left in their old souls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was impossible not to flash back to 1991 and remember
two innocent teen-agers bashing balls in a U.S. Open semifinal with
uninhibited force. It was hard not to view both as victims _
Capriati because of self-destruction, Seles because of a stabbing _
and not wonder what kind of rivalry there could have been had they
not disappeared for so long.
</P>
<P>
   But recall is also unfair. When Seles and Capriati arrived to
play their fourth-round match Sunday night, they weren't there to
stage a re-enactment. They just wanted to win. And with her
patented two-fisted strokes that have not changed with time, a fit
Seles sliced through the thick heavy air to advance to the
quarterfinals at the U.S. Open, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone expected this to be the epic of '91,'' said Capriati,
who was 15 when she lost to Seles in that mesmerizing three-setter.
``That's history. It's a new day and age. It's completely different
now. In that sense, it's like, well, maybe it's not good enough now
like then.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an epic, but the 15th-seeded Capriati and sixth-seeded
Seles let their strokes rip and wowed the crowd with their
strength. Neither held anything back, but Seles' polish on the big
points was a clear sign of her progress toward threatening the
elite players. Capriati is still trying to find her niche.
</P>
<P>
   Both were just pleased to get through their night match without
the frustration of the downpours that nearly ruined the day
session.
</P>
<P>
   Through two tortuous rain delays, about a half-dozen unsettling
thoughts whirled around the head of Marat Safin as if they were
attached to a mobile. His focus was in decline, his serve was on
the blink, his attention span was....Wait, now where were his
socks?
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the locker room, as the rain poured outside, a
sweat-soaked Safin realized he didn't have clean clothes in his
duffel bag. At that moment, a daylong scavenger hunt began for
Safin. While searching for a solution to the sudden slide in his
game, he was also hunting down Jeff Tarango for a fresh pair of
socks, then Nicolas Kiefer for a new shirt and shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the people, they will like it if somebody
smell on the court,'' Safin explained in his hearty Russian accent.
``I just forgot my socks in the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an absent-minded day for the sixth-seeded Safin. Instead
of securing his third-round match on Day 7 of the Open Sunday,
Safin lost his concentration and allowed a two-sets-to-none lead on
Sebastien Grosjean slip away.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, Safin was staring at a match locked up at 4-4 in
the fifth set when a rain delay of 1 hour 19 minutes arrived. Then,
after 28 minutes of play, Safin was ahead by 5-4 in the fifth-set
tiebreaker when another cloudburst stopped play for 1:40.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, five minutes after play began again inside Arthur Ashe
Stadium, a match that began at 11 a.m. ended at around 5:30 p.m.
when Safin watched a forehand by Grosjean bound wide. A relieved
Safin had escaped his third-round scare, 6-4, 7-6 (3), 1-6, 3-6,
7-6 (5).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like this on the floor,'' said Safin, smiling as he
folded his hands in prayer. `` `Please, please, please, go out,
out, out.' I didn't want to even think what going to be if that
ball goes in.''
</P>
<P>
   One point this way or that, and another blow could have been
delivered to an already star-depleted men's draw. The plan by the
ATP was to use this tournament as a springboard to introduce the
tour's up-and-coming players to a U.S. audience under a ``New
Balls, Please,'' slogan. But the Open has been the site of a series
of uninspiring matches where some top young players have bowed out
with barely a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Complete unknowns, like the qualifier Hyung-Taik Lee, are being
discovered while some big names have vanished. Although top-seeded
Andre Agassi's loss was understandable considering the illness of
his mother and sister, second-seeded Gustavo Kuerten went out in
four sets in the first round and fifth-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov
exited in three sets in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Safin survived for another round, playing on legs still
wobbly from his five-set victory two days earlier. Once again, he
was in a desperate situation. The breeziness of his match against
Grosjean came to a jarring end in the third set. Suddenly,
everything changed. The powerful serve that usually springs out of
Safin's 6-foot-4 frame started to go awry. He stopped attacking and
became planted well behind the baseline. He started yelling at
himself instead of calmly approaching each point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went crazy,'' Safin said. ``How is it possible?''
</P>
<P>
   But just as he began to regroup, about the time he was roaring
back from a 2-0 deficit to tie the fifth set at 4-4, the ominous
clouds that had been hovering all day broke open. Quickly, both
players headed to the locker room only to emerge for just a
28-minute stretch before the next rain delay during a nerve-racking
tie breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the situation when you stay in the locker room
and start to think, `Oh, my God, I'm down in the fifth set,'''
Safin said. ``Then the tiebreaker is 5-4; and I don't know what to
do with the ball. It's a lot of headache because you don't know.
You start to think all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go from the locker room, you're completely _ you are
scared. I don't know, you think too much. I think you can become
crazy like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like normal human beings, I was afraid. My eyes were bigger
than my head.''
</P>
<P>
   He put his fears aside, though, and converted his nervous energy
into a fresh attack. Once he returned to the court, in borrowed
clothes, Safin aggressively finished off the match. And he did it
without making a scene. For once, the temperamental Russian didn't
even break a racket along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are too new,'' said Safin, who has broken at least 50
rackets this year. ``I string them yesterday. I didn't want to ...
I promise to myself that I will not do it today. Actually, I was
quite nice on the court, no?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
