<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0116 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-QUOKKA-QUOKKA-SFCHRON     09-03 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUOKKA-QUOKKA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
SHOWTIME FOR QUOKKA &HT;    By VERNE KOPYTOFF
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   A photograph of Michael Johnson, the world-record holder in the
200 and 400 meter sprints, hangs prominently in a hallway at Quokka
Sports, the San Francisco online sports publisher.
</P>
<P>
   The image is an appropriate choice for the company that, like
Johnson, plans to strain and sweat during the 2000 Summer Olympics
in Sydney later this month.
</P>
<P>
   In its biggest undertaking ever, Quokka has joined with NBC
television to create the NBCOlympics.com Web site. Long focused on
low-profile sports like sailing and mountaineering, Quokka is now
expanding rapidly to chronicle mainstream athletics in an effort to
attract a broader audience.
</P>
<P>
   But Quokka faces serious hurdles in attempting to become one of
the leaders in its field. The company has intense competition from
more-established Web sites and is still looking forward to the day
that it will earn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quokka has a strong belief in storytelling that has proved
popular in action sports,'' said Alan Ramadan, Quokka's chief
executive. ``We are demonstrating that sports enthusiasts for all
sports appreciate good storytelling too.''
</P>
<P>
   For Quokka, that means incorporating its signature in-depth
coverage and innovative imagery into not only the Olympics, but an
array of other sports like golf, car racing, baseball, basketball
and football. The company's philosophy is to please the
most-devoted sports fans, at times to the point of what may seem
like obsession.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the joint Quokka-NBC Olympic Web site will include
20,000 pages of text and 27,000 images. Visitors will get diagrams
of athlete injuries, reports from competitors and simulations of
the triathlon course along the Sydney waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson's heart rate, speed and stride rate during an
Olympic Trials sprint is also posted on the Web site. Quokka hopes
to include more of such laboratory-style information for other
sports in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka's involvement in the Olympics began last year, when the
company agreed to create a Web site for the games with NBC to
complement the network's exclusive television coverage. The
partnership gives Quokka 51 percent of the Web site's revenues and
oversight of virtually all the content.
</P>
<P>
   While the opportunity to work on such a high-profile project is
considered a victory for Quokka, it is costly. Quokka will spend
between $20 million and $30 million on the Web site, with the only
major investment from NBC coming as television promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka hopes to make money from the Web site by selling
advertising _ Visa and General Motors have already signed up _ and
by offering online shopping. But Quokka expects to recoup only
about half of its expenses, which include hiring 150 temporary
employees for the Olympics to supplement its staff of 400.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, Quokka's workers were laboring at their
computers to prepare the NBCOlympics.com Web site for what promises
to be both an ordeal for the firm and its moment of glory. Workers
will be positioned in Sydney and San Francisco around-the-clock to
update the Web site from now until the beginning of October.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBCOlympics.com is going to be feast-or-famine for Quokka,''
said Andrew Sturner, president of corporate and business
development for Sportsline.com, a Quokka competitor. ``It's a
make-or-break event.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Quokka executives see this year's Olympics as only the
beginning. They expect the firm's financial sacrifice to pay off
later, if not from its agreement with NBC to produce a Web site for
the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City, then from the Web site
it will create for the 2004 Summer Games in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka executives predict that the company will be profitable by
mid-2002. If so, it will be the first time since the firm was
founded in 1996 by an American and two Australians.
</P>
<P>
   In its infancy, Quokka, named after a relative of the kangaroo,
built a reputation for covering extreme sports by following the
Whitbread race (an around-the-world yacht competition),
mountaineering in Pakistan and a 150-mile footrace across the
Moroccan desert. The company began branching out to more-popular
sports in mid-1999 when it introduced Web sites for motor racing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Quokka has accelerated its growth by acquiring
several companies, including Mountainzone.com, which focuses on
sports like hiking and climbing, and Golf.com. A deal to buy Total
Sports, devoted to baseball, football and basketball, is expected
to be finalized in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to get 200 million people to watch
sailing,'' said Alvaro Saralegui, Quokka's chief operating officer.
``We could have grown without expanding to other sports, but not
into as big a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Quokka's push to a broader audience sets the stage for it to do
an increasing amount of work for NBC, which announced last month
that it may invest $141 million in the company. The firms
collaborated on a Web site for the U.S. Open golf tournament in
June and may join again when the Quokka's Total Sports deal is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Quokka could close the big gap in traffic between it and
competing Web sites like ESPN.com and Sportsline.com. Both of those
companies had at least 4 million unique users in July, according to
Media Metrix, the online ratings firm, while Quokka had only
399,000. ESPN is partly owned by the Hearst Corp., which also owns
The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Web sites are particularly valuable as promotional tools
for television and magazines. They are typically geared to lure
sports enthusiasts who revel in exceedingly detailed coverage that
cannot be easily duplicated on air or in print.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka estimates that 10 million unique users will visit the
NBCOlympics.com Web site during the Sydney games. Most users will
be logging on to the site hours after events have finished because
of the time difference.
</P>
<P>
   One thing most visitors to the Web site will be unable to find
are video clips of the games in Sydney because of objections by the
International Olympic Committee. Only subscribers to certain
broadband providers will get to see video clips of the Olympics _
and then only up to 20 minutes of highlights a day. Similar to
NBC's broadcast of the games, the clips will be on tape delay.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Quokka is staking its future on offering video
designed for viewers with broadband Internet access. The company is
banking that the number of people with high-speed Internet
connections will proliferate to justify the investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have all this great technology,'' said Christopher Todd,
an Internet industry analyst for Jupiter Communications, a market
research company. ``The problem is that it doesn't have a large
reach so they're not getting a mass audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan O'Brien, a media analyst with Forrester Research, a market
research company in Cambridge, Mass., predicted that Quokka will
prosper if it survives the fickleness of the stock market and
venture capitalists. He said that compared with other online sports
companies, Quokka's presentation is far more complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you turn the clock forward five or six years, when Quokka
has libraries of material and a knowledgeable staff, they could be
looking well,'' O'Brien said. ``What comes with being a pioneer is
arrows in the back if you underdeliver.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
