<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE READY TO BOUNCE BACK FROM BIG LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. _ Defensive back Karalus Doyle stood
near the tunnel entrance at Falcon Stadium, patted his teammates
and told them everything was OK.
</P>
<P>
   Everything really wasn't OK. CSUN had just walked off the field
after being pummeled by Air Force 55-6 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If the Matadors can bounce back mentally, there's no reason to
believe they won't be fine. After all, it was a game against a
Division I-A opponent and it doesn't count toward the Big Sky
Conference title. Most important, CSUN didn't have any major
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like a preseason game,'' punter Ethan Beck said.
``Of course, we made tons of mistakes. But I think we're way better
than our last (season opener). I saw some good things defensively
and offensively that I didn't see last year against Kansas (in a
71-14 loss). I didn't see much at all there. I think we'll bounce
back.''
</P>
<P>
   And the loss doesn't appear to have taken a shot at CSUN's
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Air Force) receivers weren't as good as we thought,''
Doyle said. ``Our DBs can cover anybody in the nation. They're not
better. We just made a lot of mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Marcus Brady led a sluggish CSUN offense, which had
only two first downs in the first half. The offense _ which
averaged 450 yards last year _ mustered just 227 yards. Still,
Brady doesn't think the game hurt CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is a positive,'' Brady said. ``You can always learn
from the mistakes you made.''
</P>
<P>
   And there will be plenty of mistakes to witness on film. Not
only did the offense struggle, the defense allowed 583 rushing
yards and couldn't figure out how to defend the option. The defense
allowed 698 total yards.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Joseph Roberson said the Matadors wouldn't have to
worry about defending against the option the rest of the season.
But Roberson, who had five tackles _ including a sack _ quickly
stopped to give credit to Air Force's solid execution. And he
continuously talked about re-dedication to the football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work harder, we don't complain about having to do
any extra running and we work harder in the weight room,'' Roberson
said. ``You have to allow this experience to humble you and not
place blame on any person. You have to put the responsibility on
your shoulders to get better. ... You have to accept that you were
playing a different caliber athlete and you have to work harder to
be at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coach Jeff Kearin didn't hesitate when asked if he still
felt the game was beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question,'' Kearin said. ``Win, lose or draw it was
a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors must put it behind them and prepare to play
Southwest Texas State at San Marcos. CSUN travels for the second
consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to Southwest Texas whether we want to or not,''
Kearin said. ``... Tomorrow is a new day and a new week.''
</P>
<P>
   And a chance to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either win or lose,'' defensive back Travis Campbell said.
``One team's a winner and the other one loses. The score didn't
matter. We all played our (butts) off. It's done with. There's
nothing we can do about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
