<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0118 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NAPSTER-NAPSTER-SFCHR     09-03 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-NAPSTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
MORE COLLEGES TRY WARNINGS INSTEAD OF NAPSTER CRACKDOWNS &HT;    By BENNY EVANGELISTA
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 3,000 incoming students at the University of Virginia
wishing to obtain an e-mail account this year had to answer 10
multiple-choice questions, including the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``With Napster or similar services ... you:
</P>
<P>
   A. Have found a great way to protest record company pricing
policies.
</P>
<P>
   B. Know you will be able to stay within your budget for the year
due to the funds you will save by not purchasing CDs.
</P>
<P>
   C. Have violated University policy; have violated federal law;
have violated the university's Honor Code; have put yourself at
real personal risk for a lawsuit for copyright infringement; have
opened your computer so that anyone on the Internet can obtain any
file from it; have contributed to network congestion (or complete
network stalls) in the residence halls from uploads and downloads
of MP3 files to and from the entire Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take an MBA to figure out the answer the university
wanted was not ``A'' or ``B.''
</P>
<P>
   But the university hasn't blocked students from using popular
file sharing programs like Napster, Scour or Gnutella.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the University of Virginia, like many colleges around
the country, hope they can keep the use of Napster-like programs
from getting out of hand by educating students about all the legal
and technical ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was part from a practical point of view and partly
philosophical,'' said university spokeswoman Louise Dudley. ``This
university was founded by Thomas Jefferson and the idea of free
exchange of information. You make information available, but you
can't assume that all of the uses are illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Napster, a San Mateo, Calif., technology startup, caused a great
stir around the country last spring when hundreds of colleges and
universities blocked or restricted its use because students
swapping MP3 songs were clogging high-speed Internet connections at
those institutions.
</P>
<P>
   As the school year gets into full swing this week, university
officials are keeping an eye out for any Napster-related problems,
although there isn't a high level of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   A Gartner Group study released last week showed 34 percent of
the 50 most-wired colleges and universities in the country have
enacted a ban on Napster, including Arizona State, the University
of Southern California and Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   However, the study found a longer list of institutions that have
not banned the program, including Stanford University, the
University of California at Berkeley, the University of California
at Los Angeles, Princeton University and Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   At Stanford, officials aren't expecting any problems, but say
they will watch for bandwidth congestion that could affect other
educational uses of the Internet. That's a problem that has also
cropped up in the past when students tried to launch Web-based
businesses using the university's systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some concern about the bandwidth being used, but
that shouldn't be a problem this year,'' said Stephen Hansen,
Stanford's computer security officer. ``I don't think issues here
are any worse than anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   The colleges that have enacted bans gave bandwidth congestion as
the main reason, said Gartner senior analyst P.J. McNealy. But he
said that reason may also be an excuse to reduce liability for
copyright infringement issues that still have to be decided by the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Major record labels represented by the Recording Industry
Association of America are suing Napster claiming the program
allows users to swap illegally copied versions of their songs.
Napster contends the company and its members are doing nothing
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in San Francisco issued a preliminary injunction
against Napster in July, but the U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of
Appeals issued a stay of that order until it can hear arguments
from both sides. Napster users can continue to trade songs until at
least Oct. 2, when the appellate court is scheduled to hear the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Most college administrators have been reluctant to declare
copyright infringement as the reason for banning Napster, to avoid
any legal entanglements, McNealy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legal liability is the monster lurking at the end of the
hallway here,'' McNealy said. ``The number of sites that have
Napster-like content are voluminous. You could start tripping down
that slippery slope (trying to determine) which ones do you start
banning.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Napster loses its case, ``will the RIAA and other music
bigwigs start going after colleges and universities and students to
make an example of them?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McNealy, though, said colleges may find they have to enact bans
or restrictions if students start to heavily download songs,
especially as the appeals court hearing date nears.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought Napster was big when school let out for the
summer, it's only grown bigger over the summer,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
