<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-INVESTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
ONLINE INVESTING: POTENTIAL INVESTORS ADVISED TO CHECK INDUSTRIES
ON WEB &HT;    By HARRY DOMASH
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   A faithful reader asked me for a list of sites for information
on specific industry sectors. That was a great question, because
it's important to know what's going on in the industry before
investing in a company. Here are my favorite sites to find out.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Upside's E-Biz 150 &LR;  ( &LR; www.upside.com &LR; ). Upside Today's E-Biz
150 should be required reading for tech investors. It's a list of
the 150 largest technology companies, rated for their chances of
future success.
</P>
<P>
   The companies on the list are divided into five groups:
wireless, next-generation networks, services, applications and
commerce, and platforms and tools. Taken together, the five groups
comprise a who's who of technology.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings are done by principals of the Yankee Group of
Boston, a leading business and technology consultant to technology
companies. The information for the ratings comes primarily from
more than 1,500 meetings the Yankee Group holds with industry
participants each year.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are given a score ranging from one to five (five
is best) in each of the five categories deemed by the Yankee Group
to be critical to future success:
</P>
<P>
   Innovation: awards best scores to companies showing the most
innovation when developing new products.
</P>
<P>
   Market share: highest scores go to companies with growing, but
already large, market shares in their primary line of business.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas strength: gives most points to companies doing at least
half of their business overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Alliances: evaluates company's alliances with major industry
players.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Growth: highest grades go to companies growing sales faster
than 30 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   The companies comprising each group are listed according to
their total score (highest first). The listings include a breakdown
of the company's score in each category and a short paragraph
describing the company's strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings are published every February, but being six months
old isn't a detriment. The factors they rate change slowly. Select
E-BIZ from the top menu, and then click on E-Biz 150 below the
previous menu to find the ratings. I've been following Upside's
Yankee Group ratings since 1996. Naturally, they've made some bad
calls during that time, but they're giving away information here
that you can't buy anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; TechNewsWorld.com &LR;  ( &LR; www.technewsworld.com &LR; ). TechNewsWorld
is the best source for technology industry news. They compile
reports from a variety of sources, far more than any other site
I've seen. The site carries only the first few sentences of each
story. You have to click on a link taking you to the originating
site to read the complete story. TechNewsWorld is continuously
updated, 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; The Register &LR;  ( &LR; www.theregister.co.uk &LR; ). This British site's
logo, ``Biting the hand that feeds it,'' describes its
intentionally provocative approach. The Register covers technology
with mostly original stories. Categories include hardware,
semiconductors, software, networks, Internet and business. The
Register is always interesting, but sometimes they get it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; ChangeWave &LR;  ( &LR; www.changewave.com &LR; ). The ChangeWave site ties
in with a new book titled ``ChangeWave Investing'' by Tobin Smith.
In the book, Smith outlines a method of selecting tech stocks by
identifying significant technology-driven changes in society and
then finding companies likely to prosper from these changes. Much
of the site requires a subscription, but you can sign up for
Smith's free weekly newsletter. In each issue, Smith describes a
tech sector meeting his criteria for a Change Wave. His reports are
an easy read, very informative, and include his favorite stocks in
the sector. It's good information if you're interested in
technology investing.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Biotech &AMP; Pharmaceuticals &LR;  ( &LR; www.biospace.com &LR; ).
BioSpace.com is known as the place to go for biotech industry news.
Especially interesting in that regard is Clinical Trial News listed
under For Investors. I pay most attention to Phase III section. The
approval cycle for new drugs can drag on for years. News coming out
of Phase III trials (the final phase) can signal big stock moves in
either direction.
</P>
<P>
   BioSpace recently added a research section also listed under For
Investors. Click on BioSpace Investor Analysis to access
informative write-ups on a number of subjects. The Cancer Update,
for instance, includes detailed information on the progress of a
variety of drugs in different stages of the approval process. Also
check out the Company Snapshots listed on the research page. The
so-called snapshots are detailed descriptions of a company's
products in development. The snapshots section is new, and only
nine companies were listed when I checked last week. However,
they're adding about two new snapshots each week, so they should
have an extensive library within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; DrugTopics.com &LR;  ( &LR; www.drugtopics.com &LR; ) The online version of
Drug Topics Magazine, although targeted to pharmacists, is a good,
easy-to-understand source of news about the pharmaceutical
industry.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; American Banker.com &LR;  ( &LR; www.americanbanker.com &LR; ). An
excellent resource for news and in-depth reports about banking and
related industries. Click on Research Cntr for a list of industry
links if you can't find what you need on American Banker's site.
Check out the links under Technology &AMP; E-Commerce if you're
interested in investing in companies serving the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; WorldOil.com &LR;  ( &LR; www.worldoil.com &LR; ). News, in-depth reports,
current prices, forecasts _ it's hard to imagine what you'd want to
know about the oil industry that you couldn't find here.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; VerticalNet &LR;  ( &LR; www.verticalnet.com &LR; ) VerticalNet maintains
57 separate sites it calls communities, each covering a different
industry. The variety is tremendous. Choices range from fiber
optics and wireless networks, to public works and solid waste, to
the bakery and beverage industries, to health care, machine tools,
adhesives, and more. The communities are oriented toward industry
professionals, but you'll find a wealth of useful information in
the News and Analysis sections.
</P>
<P>
   Making money in the stock market isn't as easy as it looks.
These sites will help you get the solid information you need to
make better investment decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-03-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
