<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATE CANDIDATES BOTH COPING WITH VOTER FATIGUE AND
PERSONAL STYLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Political Memo) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In most political contests, Labor Day is a point of
embarkation: The start of the two-month journey during which the
candidates campaign in earnest, when the themes and issues that
will shape the election fall into place, and when voters start to
judge who the candidates are and what they are saying.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rick Lazio, the starting gun
is firing on a Senate race that has, in one form or another, been
running for nearly 20 months now. The result is what both sides
described this weekend as a distorted playing field that is
complicating nearly every strategic decision they face between now
and Election Day, and that is working to the decided disadvantage
of the Democratic first lady and the Republican congressman from
Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   For the electorate, the extended run-up to the general election
has resulted in a form of voter fatigue, the result of an unusual
familiarity with the candidates that comes from the near-saturation
coverage of this race. That is particularly the case for Clinton,
who has been at this almost full time since last summer, but also
for Lazio, who bounded onto the field in May.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to both candidates say that this has raised the bar on
what they need to do to capture the attention of New Yorkers, and
it accounts for the early barrage of high-octane attacks from both
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   As important, advisers to both candidates say, this long
preamble has brought a magnifying glass to the political skills of
Lazio and Clinton, neither of whom has ever run for statewide
office before. As a result, the discussion among political leaders
on this Labor Day is more apt to be about the candidates'
weaknesses, which are considerable, than their strengths. And there
is a realization that with nine weeks left, these two candidates
are unlikely to get much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them are in a bad dynamic,'' said Rick Wilson, a
Republican consultant who was an adviser to Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's Senate campaign. Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic consultant
who is not affiliated with either candidate, said that the long
run-up to the general election has made things ``much, much
harder'' for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Clinton. The first lady is, by any measure, a much more
skilled candidate than she was when she began her ``listening
tour'' in upstate New York in July 1999. She has told friends in
Washington that she has come to appreciate, if not quite share, her
husband's passion for the campaign trail, after a long period in
which she viewed it as an unhappy chore.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton continues to come across as scripted, measured and,
at times, uncomfortable in public settings. To the continued
frustration of many Democratic leaders, she remains stubbornly
cautious and averse to taking chances, a trait that is arguably not
ideal for someone seeking a public office in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is said to be more apt to rely on lessons drawn from
past races and on contemporary polling, rather than on her
instincts or those of her advisers, in deciding how to proceed.
Thus, although Clinton is in the thick of a highly unconventional
contest, she is running a very conventional campaign. Her talk of
``children and families'' and attempts to tie Lazio to conservative
policies in Washington make her sound like dozens of other
Democrats who are running for Congress but who happen not to call
the White House their home.
</P>
<P>
   There are many New York Democrats who argue that approach is not
enough to defeat Lazio, given the unusually strong dislike for
Clinton among many voters. And many of them also note that a
comparison of polls today with those of a year ago suggests that
she is running in place.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's strategy is unlikely to change, said one of her
longtime advisers, who described her as confident and comfortable
with the careful course she has charted.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lazio, when he first entered the race, several Democrats
warned that he posed a more serious threat to Clinton than Giuliani
did. He did not carry the weight of Giuliani's unpopularity in some
parts of New York, and, perhaps most important, seemed to bring a
hunger for victory and an appetite for campaigning that Giuliani
seemed to lack.
</P>
<P>
   But this weekend, it was as easy to find Republicans officials
expressing concern about Lazio's campaigning skills as it was to
find Democrats fretting about Clinton. (These are the kind of
observations that tend to be offered anonymously _ to guard against
charges of disloyalty, but enthusiastically _ in the hope that a
public airing of the views might prod the candidates into
reconsidering their ways.)
</P>
<P>
   The most serious and abiding concern about Lazio is how he comes
across as a candidate. Although he is 42 and was elected to
Congress in 1992, his own advisers acknowledge that he sometimes
seems more like a junior member of a Suffolk County town board than
a potential successor to Daniel Moynihan, one of the nation's most
distinguished senators. Clinton's advisers view this as a definite
advantage, and are considering such things as having the first lady
deliver a foreign policy address in an academic setting to press
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   And to the concern of some senior New York Republican leaders,
Lazio has yet to do anything to address this perceived liability.
Instead, he has indulged in some campaign moments that seem to
stress the lighter side of his personality. For example, he was
photographed plunging down a slide at the Erie County Fair; a few
days later, he wiped his feet on a doormat with Hillary's name
affixed to it. At the same time, he has made only one major speech,
on tax cuts, and has resisted pressure from some advisers to do
more.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The other area of concern about Lazio among Republicans is the
lax pace of Lazio's campaign, which stands in contrast to Clinton's
more energetic efforts this year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, both candidates announced they were taking off a
few days before Labor Day, with Lazio heading out to the Hamptons
and Clinton going to the White House and to New York's Finger Lakes
region.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton seemed to do anything but vacation. In Washington,
she summoned her campaign staff to the White House, where she went
through several hours of debate practice, with Bob Barnett, a
Washington lawyer and book agent, playing the part of Lazio.
Barnett played the part of former President George Bush in mock
debates with President Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also went to two fund-raisers and spent three hours at
the state fair in Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Lazio appears to have been serious about his
vacation plans, venturing out only once _ to a beach club in
Rockaway Sunday, where he shook hands and pronounced himself ``very
comfortable with where we are in key parts of this state.'' He has
gone days without appearing at a single public campaign event. And
when he offered a tax-cut plan two weeks ago, one reason it was
notable was that it was the first major policy address he had given
since entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is working a lot harder,'' said a senior New York
Republican strategist who is one of Lazio's most public supporters.
``And she's beginning to hit her stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign manager, Bill Dal Col, said the candidate had
used this time to raise money and prepare himself for the fall
campaign. And there are clearly some strategic considerations:
Lazio has argued to his aides that the best way to win the race is
to keep the spotlight on Clinton. He has, one adviser said,
repeatedly resisted stepping up his campaign schedule or scheduling
any more major speeches for now.
</P>
<P>
   But some of Lazio's advisers have concluded that tactic will not
work against Clinton, and Dal Col said that Lazio would soon begin
to spell out a more detailed campaign agenda. The question then
will be whether he waited too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
