<SLUG> BC-FBN-BARBER-GIANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBER SHIFTS DIRECTION AND A STAR IS REBORN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAFAEL HERMOSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Things were so different at Cave Spring
High School in Roanoke, Va. Tiki Barber knew he was the best player
on the football field then, which usually meant that every other
player chased him around.
</P>
<P>
   Barber again believes he can beat anybody. When Barber, the
Giants running back, took a toss from quarterback Kerry Collins in
the first quarter Sunday, he ran nearly as far as he could to the
right side of the field and stared at a mountain of Arizona
Cardinals. Barber stopped, turned and cut back across the field.
Collins provided one block and Barber squeezed into the end zone
for the game's opening score, a 10-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You believe that you're better,'' Barber said. ``I'm going to
beat this guy on this play, no matter what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber did and, because he scored two dramatic touchdowns
Sunday, helped the Giants to a 21-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Barber conceded that the boundless confidence he now displays
was sapped two years ago, when he was in a season-long slump after
a good rookie season. He lost his starting job and, worse, his
self-assurance. His talent alone could not get him by.
</P>
<P>
   Barber has regained his confidence and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised one bit,'' Barber said. ``I knew I was going
to have a big game, and I'm planning on having 15 more, hopefully
18 more.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber added a 78-yard touchdown run to finish with 144 yards on
13 carries, his second 100-yard game as a professional. He also had
three receptions for 25 yards and three punt returns for 18 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Barber was not humble, but he also was not boasting after
rushing for two distinct but impressive touchdowns. He was the
perfect complement for Ron Dayne, the Giants' first-round pick last
April and the other half of the running back platoon.
</P>
<P>
   As Barber was running across the field for that first touchdown,
he said, he could sense the Arizona players hoping someone else
would catch him. It was a hot and muggy day, and nobody was
prepared for Barber's improvisation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to a decision it was going to be me getting negative-3
yards or doing some things I used to do in high school and trying
to go back the other way,'' Barber said.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Lomas Brown said: ``Tiki's not afraid to do
that. He's fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   The first score made his second touchdown run seem almost
routine. With the Giants at their 22-yard line, the defense shifted
left and Barber knew what was next. Giants guard Ron Stone and
tackle Luke Petitgout opened a gaping hole on the right side, and
Barber sped through. He beat Arizona cornerbacks Tom Knight and
Aeneas Williams, with Knight failing to make a leaping tackle at
the Cardinals' 25.
</P>
<P>
   Barber recalled feeling everyone in the stadium looking at him
and not wanting to fall short of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   He left leaving the Giants' final touchdown for Dayne. The two
call themselves thunder and lightning and combined for 222 yards.
They could not be any more different. While Barber showed his
ability to slice through defenses, Dayne simply bashed his way
through. He gained 78 yards on 23 carries, a 3.4-yard-per-carry
average, modest but effective numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a little lineman coming at the guys,'' Brown said of
the 5-foot-10-inch, 253-pound Dayne. ``He's going to take a toll on
them. All we have to do is stay on our guys because we know we have
a bruiser behind us or we have this little sprinter.''
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-quarter drive epitomized Dayne's style. He carried six
times for 36 yards, including a 7-yard run through the right side
for a touchdown and a 21-3 Giants lead. Barber had four carries for
27 yards on that drive and waited to hug Dayne after the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun watching him because he's so different than me,''
Barber said. ``When he makes some guys miss or runs over a guy, I
wish I could do that. But at the same time, I bet he wishes he
could run 78 yards for a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne admitted he was nervous at the start of his first
regular-season professional game, but he eased into a comfort zone
by the second half. He agreed that he was more assertive than he
had been in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I played pretty good, too,'' Dayne said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
