<HEADLINE>
PARK &AMP; KREUTER QUITE A HIT TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If anyone doesn't mind being labeled ``specialty
catcher,'' it's Chad Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter has been the Dodgers' personal catching caddie for Chan
Ho Park throughout 2000 and teamed with him for Sunday's game
against the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Park had a reputation for shaking off catchers, but in spring
training the Dodgers asked the newcomer Kreuter to help cure that
habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a challenge for me, to work with pitchers and get them
on the right wavelengths,'' Kreuter said. ``And I saw (Park) as a
great talent that needs a little guidance in the right direction.
And we hit it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux has thrived at sticking with one battery mate
throughout his run of success in Atlanta. Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said there are different circumstances for different
pitchers, using regular Braves catcher Javy Lopez as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe (Lopez) gives too high a target or maybe he likes to go
away all the time. It can be 1,001 things,'' Johnson said. ``That
guy on the middle of the field, you want him happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Park has reason to feel good of late. Entering his 29th start on
Sunday, he had compiled a 2.36 earned-run average over the last 10
outings.
</P>
<P>
   In his three previous starts, Park went 3-0, allowing just three
earned runs in 24 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter does his homework when preparing Park or any of his
pitchers for their starts. He studies the opposition, matching up a
pitcher's strength to expose the batter's weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Park's history of not trusting the pitches called by his
catchers he and Kreuter have worked well in that capacity _ is a
problem Kreuter understands from a scientific angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not robots. We're all programmed a different way,''
Kreuter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of catchers see things the way they hit. They
like certain pitches or they don't hit certain pitches. So they try
to pitch guys that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter, 36, is used to the task of catching the same pitcher
for every start. And Kreuter's first taste of serving that role was
with one of the all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was Nolan Ryan's personal catcher as a (1989 rookie in
Texas).'' Kreuter said. ``I wouldn't have played my year in the big
leagues in 1989 if it wasn't for Nolan Ryan wanting me to be his
personal catcher. I think it's an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter considered himself a ``sponge'' learning under the
tutelage of Ryan that season. Now he's the grizzled veteran and
tutoring the 26-year-old Park for as long he sticks around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be here all the time to catch him,'' Kreuter
said. ``It's impossible. I'm 36. ... If I last another 10 years,
it'd be a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Shortstop Alex Cora was back in the lineup Sunday
and showing no effects of a flu bug that has spread around the
Dodgers' clubhouse over the last month. ... Reserve outfielder
Bruce Aven continues to be bothered by a strained left oblique
muscle. He could be out for another week. ... The three scoreless
innings thrown by relievers Antonio Osuna, Jeff Shaw and Matt
Herges on Saturday night lowered the Dodgers' major-league-low
bullpen ERA to 3.73. ...
</P>
<P>
   Eric Gagne, who managed just one victory in seven decisions
during his 2000 stint with the Dodgers, earned the win for Triple-A
Albuquerque on Saturday. Gagne (5-1 at Albuquerque) was charged
with three unearned runs in 5 2/3 innings in the Dukes' 16-8 win at
Iowa. ... The sounds of Latino music could be heard throughout
Dodger Stadium on Sunday. The club hosted ``Viva Los Dodgers''
Latino Heritage Celebration in the stadium parking lot. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
