<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dear Diary: I was recently seated in the second row
at a preview performance of ``Imperfect Chemistry,'' a new musical
at the Minetta Lane Theater. As the couple seated beside me were
settling in, the woman apologized to those within earshot for any
potential inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that she had rescued an injured pigeon from the
street, got a paper bag from a nearby store and brought the poor
creature to the theater so she could take it to the veterinarian
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   There was some crinkling and crackling of the bag at first as
the bird rattled around, but as the first musical number began, it
settled down and was quiet for the rest of the show. One can only
suppose it approved of the music. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ JARRETT KROLL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   It was a perfect August night, and Cindy Wallis was at Lincoln
Center at an outdoor jazz concert featuring the saxophonist Sonny
Rollins. Suddenly her attention was riveted by the man in front of
her. She couldn't believe her eyes. He had picked the pocket of the
person in front of him, lifted the cell phone and calmly proceeded
to make a call. When the conversation ended, she watched mesmerized
as the ``thief'' gently returned the phone to the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Today's warm breeze
</P>
<P>
   Still filled with flowers
</P>
<P>
   Has a shiver in its touch.
</P>
<P>
   _ CONSTANCE BROCK &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary: Maria's Hot Dogs, a stand in Rockland County, is run
by a young woman who has frequently been asked the same questions
and obviously reached the end of her patience. She posted a notice
that is excerpted here:
</P>
<P>
   1. Are you married? No
</P>
<P>
   2. Can we go out as friends? No
</P>
<P>
   3. Am I a real blonde? No
</P>
<P>
   4. Do you work out? No
</P>
<P>
   5. Do I want to have your baby? No
</P>
<P>
   6. Did you pose for Playboy? No
</P>
<P>
   7. Am I lying? No.
</P>
<P>
   _ LEN LEONETTI &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary: I was walking along 63rd Street near Broadway
waiting for a green light so I could cross over to Lincoln Center.
A large tour bus full of passengers pulled over near the curb. The
bus driver honked his horn and opened the door. He called my name
and turned to his passengers and said, ``Everybody, I would like
you to meet Mrs. Dawson, my kindergarten teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   All the people waved at me, shouted ``hello,'' and stared. The
driver, Tex Williams, was in my kindergarten class at Public School
191 behind Lincoln Center about 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It made me feel so special and remembered. I know now what it
feels like to be a celebrity in New York City, to be recognized and
acclaimed by a doting public.
</P>
<P>
   _ RITA V. DAWSON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Winkler's octogenarian aunt, Shirley Fisher, was at 14th
Street and First Avenue, trying unsuccessfully to find a taxi to
take her to a doctor's appointment uptown. After 10 minutes, a man
about 40 appeared at her side, also trying to hail a taxi. ``Just
remember, I was here first,'' she said. Another 10 minutes went by,
and as she paused in her taxi efforts, she noticed that the man had
disappeared. Soon after, an occupied cab slowed down, the back
window rolled down and a voice said, ``Hop in.'' She did, and made
her appointment on time. The man had walked over to Second Avenue
where there was less traffic and succeeded in getting a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary: A friend recently took me to lunch at a Midtown
steakhouse. Shortly after we were seated, we noticed a solitary man
across the aisle being served a beautiful and expensive porterhouse
steak. He asked for some ketchup, and when it arrived poured most
of the contents of the bottle over the steak.
</P>
<P>
   A woman at a table adjacent to his commented to her companion,
``What a terrible thing to do to a perfectly good steak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Madam,'' the gentleman replied calmly, ``if you are willing to
pick up the check, I'll eat the steak any way you want me to.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ HARVARD HOLLENBERG
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Lynwood Sawyer Jr. has passed on what might be called the
New Yorker 10-Second Shell Theorem. It originates with his friends
Ron and Di Oates, recent visitors from England. Their conclusion:
``In any given encounter (cash register, ticket desk, sidewalk
collision), New Yorkers will be indifferent, brusque, uncivil and
even hostile. If, however, you are willing to wait 10 seconds,
until their public carapaces have melted, they will become the most
gracious, accommodating people on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer admits that they might have a point. But he says, ``I'm
still waiting for some public exchange lasting more than 10 seconds
to test out their postulate.''
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL DAYS &QC;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Old yellowed buses
</P>
<P>
   Filled with low octane fuel
</P>
<P>
   And high octane kids
</P>
<P>
   Accelerate across fresh paved roads
</P>
<P>
   As yet untouched by the skid marks
</P>
<P>
   Of either joy or sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   On these early mornings
</P>
<P>
   Worn-out grinding gears
</P>
<P>
   Downshift away from the
</P>
<P>
   Certainty of academic madness
</P>
<P>
   And steer clear of the wild
</P>
<P>
   Turns of first-love sadness.
</P>
<P>
   And as the days drive
</P>
<P>
   Toward an untouched future
</P>
<P>
   Any overworked adult who
</P>
<P>
   Used to be a child, recollects
</P>
<P>
   The sweetness of hopeful hearts and
</P>
<P>
   Recalls the dream of fresh starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROGER GRANET &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Outdoor cafe on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The players: Tina Kramer and Peter Seligman of Derwood, Md., and
their 9-year-old daughter, Molly.
</P>
<P>
   Action: Molly observes the endless parade of chic New Yorkers
with fascination. After some time, she turns to her mother and
asks, with some concern, ``Mom, did you pack me any black
clothes?''
</P>
<P>
   Mom hadn't, but Molly did acquire a black outfit before her
return home.
</P>
<P>
   Marcie Livingston still remembers the young boy who lived next
door when, as a newlywed, she moved into Stuyvesant Town. ``Do you
live here?'' he asked as he saw her going into her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My neighbor used to live here,'' he said.
 &QL; 
Dear Diary: I was walking near Grand Central Terminal when I
noticed one of New York's finest arresting a sidewalk vendor with a
blanket full of homemade CD's _ all the latest releases,
shrink-wrapped. As he was being handcuffed, the vendor was
protesting loudly. ``There's no difference in this and Napster! Why
are you arresting me?''
</P>
<P>
   The officer kept fastening the cuffs behind the man's back and
asked, ``What's Napster?''
</P>
<P>
   The vendor replied that it was on the Internet. The officer
chuckled and said, ``Well, I don't patrol the Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
